<BYLINE>By RUTH RENDON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SPACE CENTER, Houston (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The three Apollo 11 astronauts had another `` splashdown'' Thursday, this time in the form of a party with thousands of <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION> employees celebrating the 20th anniversary of their lunar landing. Astronauts <PERSON> Neil </PERSON> <PERSON> Armstrong </PERSON>, <PERSON> Buzz </PERSON> <PERSON> Aldrin </PERSON> and <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Collins </PERSON> arrived from <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, where they had lunch with President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>. `` Twenty years ago, I sat in mission control when these guys came down and I would n't miss this for the world,'' said <PERSON> Hans </PERSON> <PERSON> Mark </PERSON>, a former <ORGANIZATION> Johnson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Space </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> director who is now chancellor for the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION>. The space center party was patterned after the informal celebrations that followed each Apollo mission. A crowd estimated at 10,000 attended the event. `` This is just like the splashdown party 20 years ago, except then they threw everybody in the pool,'' said <PERSON> Cookie </PERSON> <PERSON> Leisenring </PERSON>, a former employee of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aeronautics </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Space </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION>, who was trying to take pictures of the astronauts. <PERSON> Collins </PERSON>, <PERSON> Aldrin </PERSON> and <PERSON> Armstrong </PERSON> each got loud applause upon arrival. Separate outdoor areas were designated for different departments such as engineering and development, and recovery crew. Inside, a band played in a gym-sized room decorated with star-shaped ballons and blue balloons with the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> flag on them. <PERSON> Mark </PERSON> said the astronauts were very pleased to return and visit with old friends. Many of those in the crowd wore buttons showing <PERSON> Armstong </PERSON> on the moon and reading, `` July 20, 1969-1989 We Were There.'' On July 20, 1969, <ORGANIZATION> Armstrong </ORGANIZATION> and <PERSON> Aldrin </PERSON> planted their footsteps on the moon while <PERSON> Collins </PERSON> circled above in the spacecraft that later carried the three men back to <LOCATION> Earth </LOCATION>. The splashdown party is one of many events being hel???? z ~ 2to commemorate that historic After the party, the three former astronauts were to attend a private party where they would watch a light display on Clear Lake dubbed `` Thousand Points of Light.'' That celebration was to begin at 9:56 p.m. _ the moment <ORGANIZATION> Armstrong </ORGANIZATION> stepped on the <LOCATION> moon </LOCATION> two decades ago _ when a group of boats simultaneously switch on strings of lights.
