<HEAD>House Approves Spending Bill for Housing, Space and Veterans Programs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>Eds: CORRECTS $400 million to $400 billion in 10th graf: ``Schumer
estimated,'' ^By DENISE CABRERA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> approved a $ 65 billion spending bill for housing, space and veterans programs Thursday but decided to cut funding for a controversial program at the <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Housing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Urban </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Development </ORGANIZATION>. The bill, passed by a voice vote, provides no new money for a <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION> program currently being investigated by four congressional panels and the <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> for fraud and mismanagement. A <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION> inspector general's report alleged several former <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION> officials and Republican party fundraisers, including former Secretary of Interior <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Watt </PERSON> used political influence to get funding for projects on which they were highly paid consultants or developers. `` We did not want to fund a program which is having such difficulty,'' said Rep. <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Green </PERSON> of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, ranking Republican on the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> Appropriations subcommittee that oversees funding for <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Veterans </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> and independent agencies. The bill also would reclassify all deputy assistant secretaries, administrators and directors at <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION> and other agencies covered by the legislation as career positions. Persons now in these positions are political appointees of the president. However, it was funding for a planned space station on the <LOCATION> moon </LOCATION> and expanded <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> exploration that dominated debate on the bill on Thursday, the 20th anniversary of man's first lunar landing. Rep. <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Schumer </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-N.Y. </LOCATION>, attempted to transfer $ 714 million from the space station to veterans medical services, pollution control and research and low-income and elderly housing. `` The space station is not the way to go to space. It is the B-2 bomber of the space program,'' said <PERSON> Schumer </PERSON>. <PERSON> Schumer </PERSON> estimated the space station and a proposal by President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> for a manned mission to Mars would cost $ 400 billion. `` I am a believer in space technology,'' said <PERSON> Schumer </PERSON>, `` but you ca n't have everything.'' `` As we reach for the stars, let us not forget those who live underneath them'' he added. While <PERSON> Schumer </PERSON>'s proposal might save money in the short term, <PERSON> Green </PERSON> warned that decreasing spending for space by small amounts at a time would drive the overall costs up. `` The one thing that is going to drive the cost of the space station through the roof is to nickel and dime it,'' said <PERSON> Green </PERSON>. <PERSON> Schumer </PERSON> `` really saves a penny this year but he will be spending pounds and pounds in later years,'' added <PERSON> Green </PERSON>. <PERSON> Schumer </PERSON>'s proposal was defeated by a 291-125 vote. The <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> appropriations bill earmarks $ 1.65 billion of <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION>'s $ 12.2 billion budget for the space station The bill reduces the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration budget request for <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION> by $ 1 billion. The bill also provides: _ $ 15.1 billion for <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION>, including $ 9.1 billion for assisted housing and $ 456 million to fully fund programs under the <PERSON> Stewart </PERSON> <PERSON> B. </PERSON> <PERSON> McKinney </PERSON> Homeless Act _ $ 29.5 billion for the <ORGANIZATION> Veterans </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION>, including $ 820 million for veterans medical care _ $ 35.5 million for the <ORGANIZATION> Consumer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Product </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Safety </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> _ $ 5.4 billion for the <ORGANIZATION> Environmental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Protection </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION>
