<HEAD>With AM-DC-10 Crash</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OKLAHOMA CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Federal records indicate past major problems with the tail engine of a <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> DC-10 that crashed Wednesday as it attempted to make an emergency landing with about 290 people aboard. The jet's tail engine, or engine No. 2, failed just prior to the crash, and the 15-year-old plane experienced `` complete hydraulic failure,'' <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aviation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Fred </PERSON> <PERSON> Farrar </PERSON> said. However, it could not be determined Wednesday night whether the tail engine that experienced the previous problems was the same No. 2 engine that was on the jet when it crashed. Meanwhile, a passenger who rode same DC-10 from <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Denver </LOCATION> Wednesday morning said the plane had been delayed because of technical problems. Mrs. <PERSON> Ruth </PERSON> <PERSON> Dinsmore </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Mount </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Laurel </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.J. </LOCATION>, said passengers boarded tha plane and and it began to leave the terminal at <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION> <LOCATION> International </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Airport </LOCATION> shortly after 10 a.m., when `` everything sort of shut off.'' Mrs. <PERSON> Dinsmore </PERSON> said the pilot came on the PA system and said `` a little gizmo'' had gone wrong. She said the plane taxied back to the terminal, where the plane sat for about 15 minutes while the `` gizmo'' was being fixed. <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> records, obtained for <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> by the <ORGANIZATION> Aircraft </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Owners </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pilots </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, indicate that on Oct. 7, 1988, the No. 2 engine overheated and shut down just after takeoff from <LOCATION> O'Hare </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Airport </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>. An inspection of the engine later revealed that a turbine blade had failed and broken free from the engine's platform. On Sept. 30, 1988, the No. 2 engine also reportedly quit operating at 16,000 feet because of `` extensive high pressure and low pressure turbine damage,'' the report said. The primary cause of the shutdown was a blade that separated at the blade root due to an `` ailing edge crack,'' the report said. On July 20, 1983, the report said, the No. 2 engine shut down due to `` vibration.'' An inspection revealed a broken turbine blade, the report said. The report also indicated problems with the other two engines on the plane. On Sept. 26, 1986, the plane's No. 1 engine was replaced after an inspection revealed a cracked second-stage blade. On Nov. 13, 1987, the report said, the flight crew reported that the No. 3 engine vibrated and lost power as the plane climbed to 4,000 feet after taking off from <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> An engine tear-down later revealed that an engine blade failed and caused additional bearing failure.
