<HEAD>On the Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MARTINSBURG, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A group that wants to improve the image of taverns in the state's eastern <LOCATION> Panhandle </LOCATION> elected a topless bar owner as president, and he says his job has n't been easy. `` I'm not interested in getting publicity about the fact that I own a topless bar. Luckily, it has n't blown up in my face, yet,'' said C.B. `` Butch'' <PERSON> Pennington </PERSON>, owner of the <ORGANIZATION> Opequon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hill </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lounge </ORGANIZATION> and president of the <ORGANIZATION> Tri-County </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Club </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Tavern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Owners </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>. The association was created following an April gambling raid on 33 bars in the Panhandle in which police confiscated 70 illegal gambling devices, including poker machines. `` The biggest mistake that people have is that all you go into a tavern for is to drink and gamble,'' <PERSON> Pennington </PERSON> said. `` That's just not so. You go in to talk to people. It's like going into a friend's house You relax and swap stories.'' <PERSON> Pennington </PERSON> said the owners were upset by the raid because the state <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> previously ruled that poker machines are legal. The group plans to lobby state and local government to improve business conditions for tavern owners. `` We just want to show them that we're in a legitimate business and, like everybody else, we deserve a fair shake,'' <PERSON> Pennington </PERSON> said. `` We know more than just how to mix drinks. There are some things we can do to help old folks, children, charities, things like that.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW BEDFORD, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The postman may always ring twice, but sometimes he rings 32 years too late. <PERSON> Mildred </PERSON> <PERSON> St. </PERSON> <PERSON> Onge </PERSON> received her mail as usual Tuesday only to find a post card addressed to Mr. and Mrs. <PERSON> Gordon </PERSON> <PERSON> Simmons </PERSON>. Mrs. <PERSON> Simmons </PERSON> was her name in 1957, the year marked on the card. Her brother and sister-in-law had sent it while vacationing in <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> 32 years ago. `` I did n't believe it. I really did n't believe it,'' said Mrs. <PERSON> St. </PERSON> <PERSON> Onge </PERSON>, 67, who has been widowed twice. `` My brother has been dead since 1977 and my husband -LRB- <PERSON> Simmons </PERSON> -RRB- has been dead since 1963.'' New Bedford Postmaster <PERSON> Antone </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Silva </PERSON> has seen three such late letter deliveries in his 24 years on the job. He said the card could have gone astray within the post office, or been misdelivered and mailed again years later. `` Thirty-two years is a long time,'' said Mrs. <PERSON> St. </PERSON> <PERSON> Onge </PERSON>, who was 35 when the card was mailed. `` My husband would have laughed.''
