<HEAD>Airliner Crashes in Iowa with 298 on Board, Dozens Survive</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 4 grafs to UPDATE with three infants, sted one, cockpit
crew survived crash, 61 bodies found, search suspended due to darkness;
picks up 4th graf, `Nagin said ...'.</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos SCX1,2,3,4,5; LaserColor SCX6; LaserGraphics NY57,66</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MELISSA JORDAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SIOUX CITY, Iowa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> DC-10 carrying 293 people crashed Wednesday in an explosive ball of fire and cartwheeled down a runway after the pilot tried to make an emergency landing. At least 178 survived the crash, officials said. A fire official initially estimated 185 to 195 were killed in the crash, but officials later backed off the figure. `` We simply do n't have an estimate we can rely on,'' Fire Captain <PERSON> Terry </PERSON> <PERSON> Schmidt </PERSON> said at a news conference Flight 232, from <LOCATION> Denver </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION> via <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>, carried 11 crew members and 282 passengers, including three infants on laps, said <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Lawrence </PERSON> <PERSON> Nagin </PERSON>. He said the three members of the cockpit crew survived the crash and were being treated for injuries. <PERSON> Dick </PERSON> <PERSON> Bohs </PERSON>, spokesman for Gov. <PERSON> Terry </PERSON> <PERSON> Branstad </PERSON>, said 61 bodies were found. The search for bodies at <LOCATION> Sioux </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gateway </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Airport </LOCATION> was suspended late Wednesday due to darkness and was to resume Thursday. <PERSON> Nagin </PERSON> said a list of the dead and survivors would be released as soon as possible. He could not confirm the number of dead. The plane crashed on an inactive runway at <LOCATION> Sioux </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gateway </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Airport </LOCATION> after circling for about a half-hour while pilots told passengers to prepare for a crash-landing, survivors said. The accident was one of the deadliest air disasters in <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> history. The 15-year-old plane had `` complete hydraulic failure'' before the crash just after 4 p.m., <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aviation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Fred </PERSON> <PERSON> Farrar </PERSON> said. The tail engine failed, and this may have caused a hydraulic failure, said <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Raynesford </PERSON>, another <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> spokesman. <PERSON> Nagin </PERSON> said he did not know if hydraulic problems were a factor. A passenger who rode same DC-10 from <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Denver </LOCATION> on Wednesday morning said the plane had been delayed in <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION> because of technical problems. <PERSON> Ruth </PERSON> <PERSON> Dinsmore </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Mount </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Laurel </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.J. </LOCATION>, said the plane began to leave the terminal at <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION> <LOCATION> International </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Airport </LOCATION> shortly after 10 a.m., when `` everything sort of shut off.'' Mrs. <PERSON> Dinsmore </PERSON> said the pilot came on the PA system and said `` a little gizmo'' had gone wrong. It was 15 minutes before it was fixed, she said. Late Wednesday, City Manager <PERSON> Hank </PERSON> <PERSON> Sinda </PERSON> said 185 people were taken alive to <ORGANIZATION> St. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Luke </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Marian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION>, both in <LOCATION> Sioux </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>. He said seven had died at the hospitals. The search for bodies was difficult because they were scattered in a field of corn 4 feet tall. Rescuers continued to search the corn fields late Wednesday. Dr. <PERSON> Romaine </PERSON> <PERSON> Bendixen </PERSON>, clinic commander of <ORGANIZATION> Iowa </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION>'s 185th tactical fighter group, said he was the first