<HEAD>Archaeologists Unearth Remains of At Least 2 Bodies</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELLEN MILLER HADDOW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LAKE CITY, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Archaeologists have uncovered the bones of as many as four people in a mass grave near the reputed site where self-proclaimed cannibal <PERSON> Alferd </PERSON> <PERSON> Packer </PERSON>'s victims perished, the scientists said Wednesday. The diggers, who found the bodies of at least two men and possibly four on Tuesday, said they also found burlap and a green suspender clip holding remnants of brown cloth. `` The cloth is most remarkable,'' said archaeologist <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Ayres </PERSON>. `` It could help us put a date on things.'' The scientists are part of an expedition formed by <ORGANIZATION> George </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Washington </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> law professor <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Starrs </PERSON>, who is looking for clues to the truth about what occurred on the snow-packed mountain ridge in 1874. <PERSON> Packer </PERSON>, who formed a gold-hunting party with five other men, said the group became stranded on the ridge two miles south of <LOCATION> Lake </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> during a bitter winter. <PERSON> Packer </PERSON>, the lone survivor, wandered into what is now <LOCATION> Lake </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> in April 1874. He told authorities that <PERSON> Shannon </PERSON> <PERSON> Bell </PERSON>, a member of the group, killed the other four gold seekers and that he was forced to kill <PERSON> Bell </PERSON> in self-defense. <PERSON> Packer </PERSON> said he consumed the remains of the five in order to survive. He was convicted of manslaughter and sentenced to 40 years in prison. The case has been a topic of debate ever since. The archaeologists' findings indicated the men's bodies were wrapped in burlap and buried in a mass grave, said <PERSON> Walter </PERSON> <PERSON> Birkby </PERSON>, curator of physical anthropology at <ORGANIZATION> Arizona </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Tucson </LOCATION>. The bones were in a jumbled mass, forcing scientists to move slowly in uncovering them. As the scientists worked in the dig site, which <PERSON> Starrs </PERSON> calls the `` bone zone,'' residents and onlookers kept watch nearby. <PERSON> Ayres </PERSON> said the scientists would test the cloth, suspender clip and other artifacts to estimate their age. The scientific expedition began Monday.
