<HEAD>Energy Department May Face Possible Criminal Charges, Plant Shutdowns</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BURNS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> faces more criminal probes of its nuclear weapons plants _ and mounting public pressure to close them _ unless it controls their environmental and safety problems, federal auditors say. In a report highly critical of department management, the auditors said urgent action is needed to ensure that environmental laws are obeyed and the public is reassured that the government can reliably and safely run the weapons plants. The report dated July 14 was made public Wednesday by a <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> panel as a senior <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> official disclosed that a special group of experts from outside the department had been dispatched to a weapons plant in <LOCATION> Colorado </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Leo </PERSON> <PERSON> Duffy </PERSON>, a special assistant to Energy Secretary <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Watkins </PERSON>, said in testimony prepared for a <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> subcommittee that the experts will attempt to verify the origin of a manmade radioactive element discovered at the Rocky Flats plant near <LOCATION> Denver </LOCATION>. The plant processes plutonium for weapons manufacturing. Scientists of the <ORGANIZATION> Environmental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Protection </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> have said it is possible the radioactive materials strontium and cesium were produced by an accidental nuclear reaction, even though <ORGANIZATION> Rocky </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Flats </ORGANIZATION> operations do not include the splitting of atoms. <PERSON> Duffy </PERSON> said that while earlier <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> reviews of the radioactive material gave no evidence that a chain reaction had occurred, <PERSON> Watkins </PERSON> wants an independent study to `` help alleviate public concern regarding safety at this facility.'' <PERSON> Phil </PERSON> <PERSON> Keif </PERSON>, a department spokesman, said the experts arrived at the site last week and are expected to report their findings by mid-September. He said he had no other details. <PERSON> Duffy </PERSON> also disclosed that the <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Environmental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Protection </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> have launched an investigation of alleged criminal violations of environmental laws at the Feed Materials Production Center, an <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> weapons plant at <LOCATION> Fernald </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Duffy </PERSON>'s statement provided no details, and the <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> said they could not comment. <PERSON> Duffy </PERSON> did not present his remarks in person because the subcommittee hearing was interrupted before his turn to speak, and it was not resumed. The auditor's report, from the <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>'s office of inspector general, said the department is unable to ensure that its nuclear facilities _ including 17 major weapons plants in 12 states _ are meeting state or federal environmental standards. `` Thus it faces the possibility of facility shutdowns, criminal prosecutions of employees and increased congressional constraints over internal operations,'' the report said. Rep. <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Luken </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Ohio </LOCATION>, chairman of the subcommittee, said he was shocked to learn that the department had no way of determining its own compliance with environmental laws. He harshly criticized <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Layton </PERSON>, the inspector general, for not finding this flaw earlier. `` You're not a watchdog, you're a lap dog,'' <PERSON> Luken </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Layton </PERSON> disputed the charge, but later acknowledged that `` in hindsight it may have taken too long'' for his office to take a broad look at the environmental problems. <PERSON> Layton </PERSON> told <PERSON> Luken </PERSON> he decided to take the unusual step of making public a `` flash'' preliminary version of the audit `` because of the urgency'' of the problems it identifies. Among the key findings is that the <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> is unable to solve environmental problems at its weapons plants because managers and other employees are not properly trained and are not fully knowledgeable about environmental law. The report also said the department had failed to adequately oversee the work of the private companies that operate the weapons plants under federal contracts.
