<FIRST>r w PM-HydraulicFailure     07-20 0570</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Hydraulic Failure,560</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pilot's Report of Hydraulic Failure Signals Loss of Control</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-DC-10 Crash Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BRISCOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> WASHINGTON </LOCATION> _ The pilot's report of `` complete hydraulic failure'' just before a <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> DC-10 cartwheeled into the ground at <LOCATION> Sioux </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION>, signaled he was losing control of the airliner, officials say. Authorities said the hydraulic failure in the spectacular crash Wednesday may have been triggered by an uncontained engine failure, which would mean that engine parts shot out, possibly into the fuselage. Officials in <LOCATION> Sioux </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> initially estimated that 185 to 195 of the 293 people aboard Flight 232 were killed, but officials later said they did not have a reliable estimate. `` The pilot reported the loss of all of his hydraulic system, which made it very, very difficult to control that aircraft,'' said <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aviation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Leyden </PERSON>. `` We know he had a real problem bringing the aircraft down and lining it up with the runway.'' <PERSON> Leyden </PERSON> said the plane's wheels were down but little else is known about the amount of control the pilot had in the final minutes after he warned passengers to prepare for a crash landing. `` We ca n't speculate on exactly how much control he had or what happened up there. All we know is he had a very, very difficult time controlling the aircraft,'' said <PERSON> Leyden </PERSON>. The <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Airline </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pilots </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> and manufacturer <ORGANIZATION> McDonnell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Douglas </ORGANIZATION> were all sending teams to assist in the crash investigation led by the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Safety </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Leyden </PERSON> said hydraulic failure would mean a loss of primary control over nearly every control surface on the wide-bodied, three-engine airliner. A plane's hydraulic system helps push its wheels down, opens and extends flaps to increase the lift of the wings. It also governs other control surfaces of the airplane on the wings and tail, and controls the brakes once the plane is on the ground. Failure of the system does not necessarily mean the pilot has no control, but it could make it more difficult to stabilize the aircraft, particularly in landing. Even with a hydraulic failure, backup mechanical systems could have allowed some control over wheels, flaps and other surfaces that control flight and landing, <PERSON> Leyden </PERSON> said. But he and other aviation experts said manual control can be difficult. Some aviation experts said they doubted the complete system could have gone out. `` I think we can say that we have a flight control problem, but we did not have an airplane that was totally out of hydraulics, or he would n't have been flying at all,'' said <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Nance </PERSON>, a pilot and aviation writer, in <LOCATION> Seattle </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Arthur </PERSON> <PERSON> Wolk </PERSON>, an aviation attorney and licensed transport jet pilot in <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION>, said complete hydraulic failure on a DC-10 should be impossible because of required backup systems. Investigators cited partial hydraulic failure as contributing to a May 1979 crash of a DC-10 that killed 273 people seconds after takeoff from <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> O'Hare </LOCATION> <LOCATION> International </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Airport </LOCATION>. The engine on that plane tore off and somersaulted over the wing, doing extensive damage to hydraulic fluid lines and electrical cables. Loss of hydraulics also was a factor in a 1974 crash of a Turkish DC-10 in <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION> that killed 346 people. A buckling of the floor caused by decompression when a cargo door blew off severed hydraulic lines. After that, the control lines in DC-10s were rerouted along the ceiling.
</TEXT>
