<HEAD>Santiaguito Volcano Erupts</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GUATEMALA CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The Santiaguito volcano spewed red-hot lava and a 15,000-foot column of ash and steam, a seismology official said. A resident of the city of <LOCATION> Coatepeque </LOCATION>, 25 miles south of the volcano, said ash fell on the city when the volcano erupted Wednesday and lava could be seen glowing on the mountain after dark. <PERSON> Eddy </PERSON> <PERSON> Sanchez </PERSON>, assistant director of the seismology station in <LOCATION> Guatemala </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, said <LOCATION> Santiaguito </LOCATION>, 140 miles west of the capital, is constantly active but Wednesday's eruption was unusual. The <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Emergency </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> and authorities in <LOCATION> Coatepeque </LOCATION> said they were on alert. If the activity continues, coffee and other fields in the western provinces of <LOCATION> Quezaltenango </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Marcos </LOCATION> and <PERSON> Retalhuleu </PERSON> could be affected, emergency officials said. <PERSON> Santiaguito </PERSON> is considered a second crater of the adjacent 12,447-foot <LOCATION> Santa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Maria </LOCATION> volcano. The town of <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Palmar </LOCATION> was moved from the slopes of the volcano in 1988 after lava flows formed dams above it. The dams broke, causing mudslides that nearly destroyed <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Palmar </LOCATION>.
