 <LOCATION> Sioux </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> is a sprawling commercial center with 82,000 residents and is best known for its meatpacking industry and two sisters who give advice to millions of newspaper readers. The city is in <LOCATION> northwest </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION> on the east bank of a giant bend in the <LOCATION> Missouri </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION>, at a spot where the <PERSON> Lewis </PERSON> and <PERSON> Clark </PERSON> expedition stopped in 1804. <LOCATION> Sioux </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gateway </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Airport </LOCATION> is used by five commercial airlines, including <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION>. It has about 22 arrivals a day, mostly 737s and 727s, but DC-10s have landed there. Two of the city's most famous natives are twins <PERSON> Esther </PERSON> <PERSON> Pauline </PERSON> and <PERSON> Pauline </PERSON> <PERSON> Esther </PERSON> <PERSON> Friedman </PERSON>, who grew up to write the <PERSON> Ann </PERSON> <PERSON> Landers </PERSON> and Dear Abby columns. Meatpacking giant <ORGANIZATION> IBP </ORGANIZATION> and <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Morrell </PERSON> and <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> each operate large meatpacking operations in the city, as do 10 smaller packing operations. The city is part of <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION>'s 6th congressional district, represented by <PERSON> Fred </PERSON> <PERSON> Grandy </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> Sioux </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> native who starred as Gopher in `` The Love Boat'' television series. The only fatality of <PERSON> Lewis </PERSON> and <PERSON> Clark </PERSON>'s expedition to scout the <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Purchase </LOCATION> occurred while it was camped on the river _ just across from what is now <LOCATION> Nebraska </LOCATION>. Sergeant <PERSON> Floyd </PERSON>'s grave is marked by a monument overlooking the <LOCATION> Missouri </LOCATION>. The last fatal plane crash at <LOCATION> Sioux </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> occurred in May 1987, when three people died in a light plane.
