<HEAD>Lucas Could Face More Questions on Civil Rights Nomination</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: Should stand</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto WX6</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Lucas </PERSON> could face more grilling on his nomination to be the nation's civil rights chief as the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Judiciary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> seeks to resolve questions about his fitness for the job. `` There are a lot of charges against him. We need to get to the bottom of them,'' Sen. <PERSON> Howell </PERSON> <PERSON> Heflin </PERSON>, D-Ala., said Wednesday after <PERSON> Lucas </PERSON> was questioned for more than three hours about his views, his qualifications and his character <PERSON> Lucas </PERSON> defended both his commitment to the drive against discrimination and his actions when customs inspectors found $ 8,800 worth of undeclared goods in his luggage. Afterward, Sen. <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Simon </PERSON>, D-Ill., who chaired the proceeding, said members reserved the right to recall him for more questioning <PERSON> Heflin </PERSON> told reporters <PERSON> Lucas </PERSON> should be questioned again about a number of issues, including the fact that the black Republican from <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION> made misstatements on a sworn application to be admitted to the <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> bar in 1981. <PERSON> Lucas </PERSON> did not disclose on the form that he had once failed the <LOCATION> District </LOCATION> <LOCATION> of </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Columbia </LOCATION> bar examination when asked if he had taken the test in other states. <PERSON> Lucas </PERSON> testified that when he filled out the 1981 form he interpreted the question to pertain only to any previous applications to the <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> bar. `` There was no intent to mislead,'' he said. Several Democrats on the panel questioned whether <PERSON> Lucas </PERSON>, a lifelong Democrat who became a Republican in 1985, had the legal credentials and commitment to assistant attorney general for civil rights. `` It remains to be seen whether Mr. <PERSON> Lucas </PERSON> is the right man for this important job,'' said Sen. <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON>, D-Mass. `` If a case is brought to me involving a cross burning on the lawn of a citizen, believe me, this is not just cold facts to me,'' said <PERSON> Lucas </PERSON>, 61, who was sheriff and later chief executive of <LOCATION> Wayne </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mich. </LOCATION>, which includes <LOCATION> Detroit </LOCATION>. `` I have been there. I have smelled the smoke,'' <PERSON> Lucas </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Lucas </PERSON> defended a series of recent <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> decisions that civil rights lawyers say will make it harder to win discrimination cases in federal courts. <PERSON> Lucas </PERSON>, echoing a pledge by Attorney General <PERSON> Dick </PERSON> <PERSON> Thornburgh </PERSON>, said he would monitor the impact of those decisions on discrimination suits and push for legislation if the rulings thwart civil rights enforcement. But Sen. <PERSON> Howard </PERSON> <PERSON> Metzenbaum </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Ohio </LOCATION>, said he was troubled by <PERSON> Lucas </PERSON>' defense of the recent high court rulings, adding, `` I've been around long enough to know time slips away.'' <PERSON> Metzenbaum </PERSON> also questioned <PERSON> Lucas </PERSON> about why he was fined $ 594 by the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Customs </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> in 1985 for failing to declare $ 8,884 worth of merchandise the <PERSON> Lucas </PERSON> family brought back from a trip to the <LOCATION> Far </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION>. `` How do you explain concealing receipts and merchandise from the customs inspectors?'' <PERSON> Metzenbaum </PERSON> said, reading from an April 24, 1985, report of the incident at the <LOCATION> Seattle </LOCATION> airport. The report said `` there was a deliberate effort by all -LRB- family -RRB- members to conceal goods and receipts.'' <PERSON> Lucas </PERSON> explained that customs agents found several pieces of undeclared jewelry in a cosmetics case carried by one of his daughters who accompanied him on the business trip to <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Lucas </PERSON> said he reported $ 4,800 worth of merchandise, relying on what his wife and two daughters told him they had bought. `` I reported exactly what I was advised of. I did not personally examine any of these things,'' <PERSON> Lucas </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Lucas </PERSON> said he discussed the incident with <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> agents who investigated his background before his nomination by President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> as well as with committee staff members. <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Runkel </PERSON> called the customs violation `` pretty minor-league stuff.'' `` Our feeling is that he had a very strong appearance today, answered any and all questions put before him by the committee,'' <PERSON> Runkel </PERSON> said. `` We are ever more confident that he'll be confirmed.'' Sen. <PERSON> Orrin </PERSON> <PERSON> Hatch </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Utah </LOCATION>, calling <PERSON> Lucas </PERSON> `` a take-charge guy who gets things done, who does what's right,'' vowed to fight hard for his <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> confirmation.
