<FIRST>r w PM-Technology-FOI     07-20 0345</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Technology-FOI,370</SECOND>
<HEAD>DOE, NASA Call for Export Restrictions on Technical Information</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROSE ANN ROBERTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The Freedom of Information Act gives foreign competitors `` unique access'' to <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> technology, and an <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> official suggests restrictions might be needed to stem the flow. `` The government's role is to make sure that <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> industry has the initial opportunity to develop U.S.-sponsored'' research, <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Williamson </PERSON>, deputy assistant energy secretary for international affairs, said Wednesday. `` The Freedom of Information Act ... has granted foreigners unique access to our technology,'' he said. <PERSON> Williamson </PERSON> and <PERSON> Kenneth </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Pedersen </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aeronautics </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Space </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> told the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> subcommittee on international scientific cooperation they support restricting the FOI law to limit foreign access to information where it could hurt <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> competitiveness. The panel was considering how foreign access to <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> science and technology compares to <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> access to foreign technology. <PERSON> Pedersen </PERSON> and <PERSON> Williamson </PERSON> conceded that providing exemptions would be difficult. `` It is an effort to balance two very important objectives,'' <PERSON> Pedersen </PERSON> said. <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION>, he said, wants to continue to provide access without giving foreign competitors an edge. He proposed giving certain technology to <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> industry for a specified time before making it available for general release. `` We are n't looking for an open-ended authority,'' <PERSON> Pedersen </PERSON> said. `` We're trying to get a door on the barn before too many horses leave.'' <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Millburn </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>, which already has some FOI exemptions, told the subcommittee the <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> supports the <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION> and DOE requests. Deputy Secretary of Commerce <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Murrin </PERSON> said the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> wants to `` support, foster and encourage'' the exchange of scientific and technological information. But he and others testified that the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> is often shortchanged in such exchanges. `` Many of our scientists and engineers are still subject to what is known as the ` Not Invented Here Syndrome,' which makes those afflicted by it undervalue the importance of research performed elsewhere,'' <PERSON> Murrin </PERSON> said. `` The Japanese, on the other hand, eagerly seek new scientific and technological knowledge from any source,'' he said.
