<HEAD>Report Says Detonation Switches Untested</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONNA CASSATA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> chairman wants <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> Dick </PERSON> <PERSON> Cheney </PERSON> to authorize independent tests of special switches used to detonate <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> missiles following reports that the manufacturer failed to test the product. In a letter to <PERSON> Cheney </PERSON> released Wednesday, Rep. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Dingell </PERSON>, D-Mich., said the company also worked on the switches with equipment `` which had not been inspected, calibrated or tested for conformance with accepted criteria for up to seven years. <PERSON> Dingell </PERSON> cited the findings of the <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Criminal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Investigative </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> which investigated printed wiring boards, also known as stator switches, manufactured by Asher Engineering. The service found that from 1982 to the present the switches were not tested in accordance with military guidelines and failed to meet specifications, <PERSON> Dingell </PERSON> said in the letter. The subcontract awarded to Asher Engineering was for production of stator switches for the <LOCATION> Phoenix </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> AAMRAM </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Standard </ORGANIZATION>, Sidewinder, Sparrow, Maverick, Harpoon and Harm missile systems. `` Without working stator switches, these missiles will not detonate,'' <PERSON> Dingell </PERSON> said. The chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> subcommittee on oversight and investigations called on <LOCATION> Cheney </LOCATION> to authorize spending for independent tests of the switches. `` The subcommittee is concerned that the devastating impact of not continuing to use <PERSON> Asher </PERSON> stator switches and the possible recall of seven years worth of missile production will create tremendous pressure within the system to use the substandard or defective components,'' <PERSON> Dingell </PERSON> said. A woman who answered the telephone at Asher Engineering in <LOCATION> Baldwin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Park </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>, said no one at the company could comment on the letter. The <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION>'s deputy assistant inspector general, in an memo April 20, said the untested switches `` could present a serious hazard to both the missile system and to national security if found to be faulty.'' In the memo, <PERSON> Daniel </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Foley </PERSON> also said investigators have n't determined whether the switches were used on other weapons systems The <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Avionics </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> performed a quick audit of Asher in May 1989 and concluded `` it is evident from the samples that the manufacturer used different processes on the same type boards and had poor process controls.'' The <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION>'s director of reliability, maintainability and quality assurance, in a July 10, 1989, memo, said, `` there is not sufficient technical justification for using these circuit assemblies in such a critical application.''
