ne out of the night sky: Why did n't the crew merely turn left and get out of Soviet territory? `` That's what boggles our mind, why did n't they?'' said <LOCATION> Houston </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Turner </PERSON> said <PERSON> Houston </PERSON>'s conclusion that plane spent its last three hours in <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> territory `` sheer speculation.'' But the available radar data for the initial part of the flight and information provided by the Soviets and Japanese governments shows `` that airplane was well right of course,'' said <LOCATION> Houston </LOCATION>. `` There is mountains of evidence and it's irrefutable.'' The crew thought they could `` sneak through <LOCATION> Russia </LOCATION>?'' asked <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Court Judge <PERSON> Aubrey </PERSON> <PERSON> Robinson </PERSON>. <PERSON> Houston </PERSON> said the pilot probably concluded, `` I think I'll take a shot at it.'' The pilot may have believed he could `` get away with it, and he damn near did,'' said <LOCATION> Houston </LOCATION>.
