<HEAD>A Socialist Star is Born</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TETSUO JIMBO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KOHRIYAMA, Japan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Children await her with bunches of flowers. Crowds follow her slavishly, shout her name and seek handshakes. Scores of undercover police officers trail her protectively as she traverses the campaign trail. <PERSON> Takako </PERSON> <PERSON> Doi </PERSON>, the charismatic leader of <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s once lightly regarded Socialists, is getting something that few politicians from her party have had: superstar treatment. `` To be honest, I never imagined she would become this popular three years ago,'' said <PERSON> Sukio </PERSON> <PERSON> Iwatare </PERSON>, a party official and veteran lawmaker, as Ms. <PERSON> Doi </PERSON> spoke Wednesday to a crowd in <LOCATION> Kohriyama </LOCATION> in the northern <PERSON> Fukushima </PERSON> prefecture. `` I think it is nothing but her lovable personality that led to this <PERSON> Doi </PERSON> fever. It is amazing that she can easily draw thousands of people everywhere she goes.'' Pollsters and analysts say a new sales tax and an influence-peddling scandal have turned voters against the <ORGANIZATION> Liberal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, the conservative group that has dominated Japanese politicans for 34 years. Women's groups also have criticized new Prime Minister <PERSON> Sousuke </PERSON> <PERSON> Uno </PERSON> after allegations surfaced that he kept paid mistresses. Ms. <PERSON> Doi </PERSON>'s popularity is expected to make the Socialists the main beneficiaries of voters' ire in Sunday's elections for half the 252 seats in the upper house of Parliament. Her party, the largest opposition group in <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION>, hopes to increase its representation in the chamber from 43 to at least 65. Pollsters say the <ORGANIZATION> Liberal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democrats </ORGANIZATION> likely will fall from 142 seats to fewer than 120. Three years ago, Ms. <PERSON> Doi </PERSON> became the first woman to head a major Japanese political party. Her predecessor had resigned over the labor-backed party's defeat in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s last national elections. Since then, the 61-year-old Ms. <PERSON> Doi </PERSON> has moved the party away from doctrinaire leftist ideas. On Wednesday, about 3,000 people packed the parking lots in front of <PERSON> Kohriyama </PERSON>'s railway station as Ms. <PERSON> Doi </PERSON> campaigned for the party's local candidate Some watched from balconies of nearby department stores. `` It is time to bring changes in politics,'' Ms. <PERSON> Doi </PERSON> called out from the top of a campaign truck. After a pause for cheers, she added: `` Give us a chance to run the government. We can do it. We can make tomorrow's <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> better together.'' The candidate, <PERSON> Choei </PERSON> <PERSON> Aita </PERSON>, a 60-year-old former labor union official challenging two ruling party incumbents, said Ms. <PERSON> Doi </PERSON> `` talks about specific policies but she makes it so easy to understand for ordinary people.'' He added that her speech gave him `` a very good feeling'' about winning Sunday. If the opposition were to win control of <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION>'s more powerful lower house, in elections that do n't have to be held before next year, Ms. <PERSON> Doi </PERSON> could become <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s first woman prime minister. `` Though there are many more hurdles to be cleared, the opposition camp never had such a golden opportunity to take over the government before,'' said <PERSON> Takayoshi </PERSON> <PERSON> Miyagawa </PERSON>, president and noted political analyst at <ORGANIZATION> Seiji </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Koho </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION>, a prominent research firm. `` And if the opposition actually takes over the government, the head of the largest party in the opposition camp would naturally become prime minister,'' he added. The opposition, however, has been criticized for concentrating on criticism rather than presenting alternative policy proposals. <PERSON> Doi </PERSON> emphasizes that her party would not bring make drastic changes if it gained power. `` Continuity is important in politics,'' she told a news conference after her speech. `` It is wrong to think we were trying to bring drastic changes to this country.'' The Liberal Democrats say the Socialists would take such steps as scrapping the U.S.-Japan Security Treaty. Ms. <PERSON> Doi </PERSON> said her party would not unilaterally abandon the pact.
