<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> is moving to avoid exceeding the national debt limit next month even while urging <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> to extend the ceiling before lawmakers leave for a month-long August recess. `` It is virtually certain, absent such action, that <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> will run out of cash and default on its obligations on Aug. 15,'' Undersecretary <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Glauber </PERSON> told <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Finance </ORGANIZATION> taxation and debt management subcommittee Wednesday. `` I urge you to seek the cooperation of your colleagues and to act quickly on the debt limit in order to prevent unnecessary problems in <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> financing operations and default on the government's obligations,'' he said. The government is seeking a $ 300 billion increase in the current $ 2.8 trillion long-term debt ceiling. Without an increase, <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> officials say the government would have problems issuing paychecks and Social Security payments in September. The <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> already has passed such legislation. Shortly before <PERSON> Glauber </PERSON> appeared on <LOCATION> Capitol </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hill </LOCATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> announced it was suspending indefinitely the sale of special securities for state and local governments. Such action has been taken before when <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> was unable to agree on legislation raising the debt limit. State and local governments buy the special <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> securities as a temporary investment vehicle for money they raise in the bond market. If the securities are not available, it could force cancellation of bond sales by state and local governments, leading to confusion and turmoil in the municipal bond market. <PERSON> Glauber </PERSON> did not mention the suspension in his testimony on <LOCATION> Capitol </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hill </LOCATION>, but he did warn of the other effects of congressional inaction on the debt limit increase. `` Without an increase in the debt limit by Aug. 1, full investment of the Social Security trust funds may not be possible,'' he said. The <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> is required by law to invest the trust fund assets in interest-bearing government securities, which are a form of government debt and are counted with other government bonds and notes against the debt limit. While <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> normally appropriates money to cover any interest lost to the trust funds during a period when they can not be invested, this action has raised complaints from interest groups representing the elderly. <PERSON> Glauber </PERSON> also warned that congressional inaction into September would prevent the <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> from paying the government payroll for September, including payroll and pension checks exceeding $ 23 billion.
