<HEAD>DC-10 Has Troubled History</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 1st graf to restores AP Logo; SUBS 4th graf, `Wednesday's
crash ...' to give latest figure for the number aboard.</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-DC-10 Crash Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BRISCOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The crash of a DC-10 in <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION> comes just as <ORGANIZATION> McDonnell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Douglas </ORGANIZATION> prepares to deliver the last of the workhorse airliners plagued by some of history's worst air disasters. The wide-bodied, three-engine aircraft used by 51 world airlines and built by <ORGANIZATION> McDonnell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Douglas </ORGANIZATION> has had cargo door problems, been accused of design flaws and was once grounded for more than a month by the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aviation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION>. The DC-10s have been the workhorse of many airlines, carrying from 250 to 380 passengers, depending upon how their interior is configured. A DC-10 was involved in history's worst <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> air disaster that killed 273 people in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> in 1979 and in one of the worst single-plane disasters in the world, the 1974 crash of a Turkish Airliner in <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION> that killed 346 people. Wednesday's crash of <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> Flight 232 on its way from <LOCATION> Denver </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> during an emergency landing attempt in <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION> had the potential of eclipsing the 1979 crash, but more than half the 293 people aboard survived after the plane cartwheeled into the ground in a ball of flames. The pilot had radioed `` complete hydraulic failure'' prior to the crash landing, <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> officials in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> said. Failure of the hydraulics system, which is the main means of controlling wing flaps and other mechanisms that guide the aircraft, also has figured in other DC-10 crashes, although the primary cause has varied. The <ORGANIZATION> Turkish </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> crash was blamed on faulty cargo door design, which was later altered after nonfatal incidents of doors popping off other DC-10s in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>. The loss of the door led to decompression that buckled the floor which, in turn, severed hydraulic lines essential to taking off, steering and landing an airliner. Floors in wide-bodied jets were strengthened and hydraulic lines rerouted after the incidents. In the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> crash, hydraulic lines along the wings were severed when one of the plane's engines came loose and somersaulted over the wing. The <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> grounded all <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> DC-10s but allowed them to fly 37 days later. The <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> determined erroneous maintenance procedures by <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> caused the engine supports to crack. The board also said some systems in the plane were vulnerable to damage. <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Reed </PERSON>, spokesman for <ORGANIZATION> McDonnell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Douglas </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Louis </LOCATION>, said 445 DC-10s have been built since 1969, including military models dubbed KC-10s. Plagued by financial losses following the <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> crash and heavy competition from other wide-body airliners, the company's <ORGANIZATION> Douglas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aircraft </ORGANIZATION> unit announced in 1983 it was ending production of the model, except for military tanker versions that were on order. Two passenger planes remained unsold, and the last one of those is to be delivered to <ORGANIZATION> Nigeria </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> in a few weeks, <PERSON> Reed </PERSON> said. In 1980, a retired <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> pilot, <PERSON> Fred </PERSON> <PERSON> G. </PERSON> <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON>, told a news conference he had refused to fly the DC-10 during his last six months as a captain because it was unsafe. He said although the plane has several hydraulic systems, they are interconnected through pumps so that failure of one system jeopardizes the others. <ORGANIZATION> McDonnell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Douglas </ORGANIZATION> officials have consistently defended the aircraft as safe, blaming bad publicity for a decline in orders. The big tri-jets also have been involved in several crashes that were blamed on pilot error or problems not related to design or maintenance. In addition to the <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> crash, two other DC-10s crashed in 1979. An <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Zealand </ORGANIZATION> model hit the rocky slopes of a volcano at the edge of <LOCATION> Antarctica </LOCATION>, killing all 257 people aboard. And 74 people died when the pilot of a <ORGANIZATION> Western </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> DC-10 landed on a <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> runway that was closed for repairs.
