<HEAD>Troops Can't Stop Mob Violence in Resort Region, Soviet Reports Say</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAREY GOLDBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Authorities evacuated 1,500 tourists and banned new visitors from the <LOCATION> Black </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sea </LOCATION> region of <LOCATION> Abkhazia </LOCATION>, where troops have been unable to halt a bloody feud between rival ethnic groups, <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> media said today. Armed bands of Georgians and Abkhazians continued to roam the roads in the resort area 870 miles south of <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> said. Authorities declared a state of emergency and imposed a curfew in the region on Tuesday and by today had confiscated more than 2,500 firearms, <ORGANIZATION> Radio </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Moscow </ORGANIZATION> said. But the report said `` attacks on citizens, policemen, and army servicemen'' continued Wednesday night in the Abkhazian capital of <LOCATION> Sukhumi </LOCATION>. Soviet news reports said <ORGANIZATION> Interior </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> troops and police were confiscating weapons from rioters, but <ORGANIZATION> Komsomolskaya </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pravda </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Youth </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> League </ORGANIZATION> newspaper, reported today that <LOCATION> Sukhumi </LOCATION> police had to return some firearms to fear-stricken residents. The paper said police were forced to `` give way to the demands of people tortured by fear and rumors, who surrounded the district <ORGANIZATION> Interior </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> building and demanded the return of their hunting weapons for self-defense.'' The violence has claimed at least 18 lives since it began Saturday in <LOCATION> Abkhazia </LOCATION>, a 3,320-mile autonomous region in the southern Soviet republic of <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Komsomolskaya </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pravda </ORGANIZATION> reported today that 339 people have been injured. Georgians outnum