<HEAD>D.C.'s Infant Mortality Rate More Than Double National Average</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: RETRANSMITTING to fix category code.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The infant mortality rate in the nation's capital jumped to more than twice the national average last year, largely due to an increase in drug abuse among pregnant women, city officials say The District of <LOCATION> Columbia </LOCATION> saw 23.2 infant deaths per 1,000 births in 1988, the highest level since 1980 and more than double the national average of 9.9 deaths per 1,000 births, the city reported Wednesday. The new statistics represented a substantial increase over the 1987 rate of 19.6 deaths per 1,000 births. `` It's as if ... we've been hit by a hurricane that government ca n't control,'' said <PERSON> Patricia </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Tompkins </PERSON>, chief of the <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Maternal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Child </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION>. `` There's a tremendous amount of drug abuse among women of childbearing age.'' <ORGANIZATION> Tomkins </ORGANIZATION> said the city expected an increase, but not one so dramatic. `` It was kind of a shock,'' she said. The district's rise in infant mortality followed several years of modest success in curbing what has long been identified as one of the district's biggest health problems. Until 1988, the infant mortality rate had been relatively stable for four years, and had declined slightly in 1987. <LOCATION> D.C. </LOCATION> Mayor <PERSON> Marion </PERSON> <PERSON> Barry </PERSON> has made infant mortality a major part of its health care agenda. But the city's efforts have been overwhelmed by the crack cocaine epidemic, which has swamped hospitals with the babies of drug addicts. Women who use drugs often give birth to infants with low birth weights who have an increased likelihood of dying before they reach their first birthdays.
