<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A panel instructed by <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> to name <LOCATION> Hollywood </LOCATION>'s 25 greatest movies went behind closed doors to debate the merits of films such as `` The Grapes of Wrath'' and `` Citizen <PERSON> Kane </PERSON>.'' Wednesday's meeting was closed to the public over the protests of reporters from <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION>, the <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Daily </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Variety </ORGANIZATION>, an observer said. <PERSON> Erich </PERSON> <PERSON> Schwartz </PERSON>, an attorney for the librarian of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> charged with overseeing the selections, said the meeting was conducted secretly to dispel public confusion about the panel's work and to promote `` spirited discussion.'' `` There was nothing Machiavellian in the decision to close the meeting,'' said <PERSON> Schwartz </PERSON>. `` My personal feeling is that they did n't want to hurt any filmmaker's feelings while discussing the merits of one picture over another,'' said <PERSON> Jane </PERSON> <PERSON> Galbraith </PERSON>, a film reviewer and reporter for <ORGANIZATION> Daily </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Variety </ORGANIZATION>. `` They did n't want to be associated with critical comments about people that they work with.'' The meeting had been billed as a public discussion of recommendations the board would make to the librarian of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> for the first 25 films to be protected under the National Film Preservation Act of 1988. The act, drafted in response to outcries about the practice of coloring old black-and-white movies, stipulates that a panel of experts select 25 titles each year for a national film register. Selected films can still be colored, but the act requires that they're labeled as having been altered without the participation of the original makers of the film. The <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Film </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Preservation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION>, composed of representatives of 13 film groups, began meeting in a public session at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> California </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>. Chairwoman <PERSON> Fay </PERSON> <PERSON> Kanin </PERSON>, a representative of the <ORGANIZATION> Academy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motion </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Picture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Arts </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sciences </ORGANIZATION>, moved to close the meeting to the public after almost 1 -LCB- hours. <PERSON> Schwartz </PERSON> said the board had already satisfied requirements under the act to hold two public meetings and was under no legal obligation to continue meeting in public session. Instead of reaching agreement on a list Wednesday, <PERSON> Schwartz </PERSON> said each board member would compose his or her own personal list and submit it to the librarian of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Billington </PERSON>. Then <PERSON> Billington </PERSON> will make the final decision, announcing the choices in September, he said. The move to a secret session was especially perplexing as board members had discussed the nominations publicly prior to the meeting. In preliminary polling, 57 movies were nominated by at least two of 13 members of the preservation board. The leader was `` The Grapes of Wrath'' with eight votes. `` Casablanca'' and `` It's a Wonderful Life'' each drew seven votes; `` The Best Years of Our Lives,' ` `` Citizen Kane'' and `` On the Waterfront'' all received six votes. `` They just made this decision at their luncheon today, and they did n't tell anybody about it,'' said <PERSON> Mary </PERSON> <PERSON> Tokita </PERSON>, a spokeswoman for the <ORGANIZATION> UCLA </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Arts </ORGANIZATION> who had volunteered to handle publicity for the board.
