<SECOND>PM-Japan-Gangsters,0543</SECOND>
<HEAD>Huge Crime Syndicate Holds Quiet Ceremony For New Boss</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ERIC TALMADGE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Police claimed a victory today as the huge <ORGANIZATION> Yamaguchi-gumi </ORGANIZATION> organized crime syndicate abandoned plans for an elaborate inauguration for its new boss, opting instead for a quiet gathering at its headquarters. `` Our pressure and hard work paid off,'' said a police official in <LOCATION> Kobe </LOCATION>, a port city in western <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> where the 21,000-member gang is based. He said police around the country had requested hotels and large banquet halls not to accept reservations from the gang, which, with no where else to go, finally had to hold the ceremony in a large room on the second floor of its headquarters building. The official, who requested anonymity, said about 300 police officers surrounded the building, located on a hill in an expensive residential area, as 105 gangsters attended the two-hour fete. He said there were no arrests. When new boss <PERSON> Yoshinori </PERSON> <PERSON> Watanabe </PERSON>'s predecessor, <PERSON> Masahisa </PERSON> <PERSON> Takenaka </PERSON>, was inauguarated in <LOCATION> Naruto </LOCATION> on the southern island of <ORGANIZATION> Shikoku </ORGANIZATION> in July 1984, about 1,000 police were mobilized. More than 300 gangsters, many dressed in black suits or kimono, attended, although no incidents were reported. In 1985, <PERSON> Takenaka </PERSON> was killed in a leadership dispute that divided the gang into two rival camps. More than two dozen deaths and 315 shootings made the ensuing conflict the bloodiest ever in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s underworld During today's ceremony, <PERSON> Watanabe </PERSON> is believed to have received three `` treasures'' symbolic of his post, a tradition mocking the three sacred treasures that have been passed down from emperor to emperor for centuries. `` We do n't expect anything to change under <PERSON> Watanabe </PERSON>,'' the officer said. `` And we will keep up our pressure on the gang.'' <PERSON> Watanabe </PERSON>, 48, heads the powerful Yama-ken gang, based in <LOCATION> Kobe </LOCATION>. The gang is the largest within the Yamaguchi-gumi, and claims a membership of 3,000. Police estimate there are nearly 90,000 gangsters, or yakuza, in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> and say nearly half are associated with the three biggest syndicates _ the <ORGANIZATION> Yamaguchi-gumi </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Sumiyoshi </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rengo </ORGANIZATION> and the Inagawa-kai. Leaders of the <LOCATION> Inagawa-kai </LOCATION>, based in the <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> area, attended today's ceremony, demonstrating their close relationship with the Yamaguchi-gumi. <PERSON> Watanabe </PERSON> is the fifth boss of the gang, which was founded by <PERSON> Harukichi </PERSON> <PERSON> Yamaguchi </PERSON> in 1915. When the gang was founded, it had only 50 members. Underworld syndicates often keep a high profile by posting signs outside their offices, and the Yamaguchi-gumi headquarters is a well-known <LOCATION> Kobe </LOCATION> landmark. Syndicates are involved in extortion, illicit gambling and the drug and sex trades. They also commonly operate in construction, real estate, money laundering and entertainment. Their activities are mainly limited to <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, but they are known to buy guns and drugs from the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Thailand </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION> for sale here. Police estimate the total underworld income at $ 15 billion annually. Gang members have complex `` family'' relations cemented by rituals, often patterned on <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s indigenous Shinto religion, where rice wine is sipped to seal vows of fidelity. <PERSON> Watanabe </PERSON> on May 18 completed his wine-sipping ceremony with the gang's top leaders. Later that month, he was convicted of assault and given a 10-month suspended sentence.
</TEXT>
