<HEAD>Relatives of Crash Victims Grieve in Airports</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-DC-10 Crash, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN BLAKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 In airports in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Denver </LOCATION>, people grieved over the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> DC-10 crash. In a <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION> airport, some who grieved before came to console. Flight 232, headed to <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION> from <LOCATION> Denver </LOCATION> via <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> crashed with 293 aboard Wednesday while attempting an emergency landing in <LOCATION> Sioux </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION>. More than half survived. Moments after hearing about the crash, four people who lost relatives in one of the world's worst airline disasters rushed to <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION> <LOCATION> International </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Airport </LOCATION> to offer consolation. <PERSON> Stan </PERSON> <PERSON> Maslowski </PERSON> and his wife, <PERSON> Norma </PERSON>, both of <LOCATION> Haddonfield </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.J. </LOCATION>, lost their 30-year-old daughter, <PERSON> Diane </PERSON>, when a terrorist's bomb blew up <ORGANIZATION> Pan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Am </ORGANIZATION> Flight 103 on Dec. 21, killing 259 aboard and 11 people in <LOCATION> Lockerbie </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Scotland </LOCATION>, where the wreckage fell. Two others joined the couple at the <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION> airport. `` The purpose of our visit is to comfort the families, to support those people who wonder if they're family members are alive,'' <PERSON> Maslowski </PERSON> said. On Wednesday, though, their message reached no relatives of those aboard the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> flight. <PERSON> Maslowski </PERSON> said <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> officials told him no one waiting for passengers had reported to the airport. `` It makes it all dredged up again,'' said <PERSON> Norma </PERSON> <PERSON> Maslowski </PERSON> of their mission. `` It's horrible.'' <PERSON> Maslowski </PERSON> said the relatives of the <ORGANIZATION> Pan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Am </ORGANIZATION> victims have formed a network of more than 400 people who are prepared to rush to airports to console anyone waiting for a plane that had crashed. In <LOCATION> Denver </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> employees escorted 25 to 30 visibly shaken relatives past ranks of reporters and television cameras. The media were not allowed into the VIP area. United officials at <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> O'Hare </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Airport </LOCATION> opened a lounge for families of those aboard the flight. One woman entered crying, her fingertips at her mouth. Two men leaving refused to speak with a reporter, one swearing as he brushed by. Outside the room, 20 police officers and <LOCATION> O'Hare </LOCATION> security guards stood by the entrance. Some at the <LOCATION> Denver </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> airports had news to celebrate. Rabbi <PERSON> Avrohom </PERSON> <PERSON> Brownstein </PERSON> and his wife burst out of the VIP room in <LOCATION> Denver </LOCATION> where relatives of passengers on the plane had gathered. They had just heard their 9-year-old son, <PERSON> Yisroel </PERSON>, had survived with a fractured arm and minor burns. `` He's OK. He always wanted to have a broken arm anyway. We just talked to him on the phone and he's OK,'' <PERSON> Brownstein </PERSON> said. United officials in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> told <PERSON> Arthur </PERSON> and <PERSON> Christine </PERSON> <PERSON> Bulmann </PERSON> of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lenox </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ill. </LOCATION>, that his sister, <PERSON> Susan </PERSON> <PERSON> Randa </PERSON>, and her young son, <PERSON> David </PERSON>, of <LOCATION> Boulder </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Colo. </LOCATION>, had only minor scratches from the crash. `` I think it's a miracle,'' <PERSON> Christine </PERSON> <PERSON> Bulmann </PERSON> said.
