<DATELINE>STOCKHOLM, Sweden (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A court today ended deliberations in the trial of a man accused of the 1986 killing of Prime Minister <PERSON> Olof </PERSON> <PERSON> Palme </PERSON> and ordered the defendant held in custody until the verdict is published next week. The announcement was a strong indication that <PERSON> Christer </PERSON> <PERSON> Pettersson </PERSON> had been found guilty of shooting Palme. Had the verdict been innocent, he would have been ordered released immediately. The <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>'s announcement, however, did not necessarily mean he would be sentenced on the charge of first-degree murder. If judged to be the killer, <PERSON> Pettersson </PERSON> could be sent for psychiatric examination with the possibility of committal in a closed mental institution. <PERSON> Pettersson </PERSON> was tried by a panel of two judges and six lay jurors, all with an equal say in determining the defendant's innocence or guilt. `` The deliberations are over,'' said court spokesman <PERSON> Bertil </PERSON> <PERSON> Hagberg </PERSON>. `` The defendant shall remain in custody.'' <PERSON> Pettersson </PERSON>, a 42-year-old with a history of drug and alcohol abuse, denied shooting <PERSON> Palme </PERSON>, and claimed he was 17 miles away at the time of the Feb. 28, 1986 shooting. The verdict will be published on July 27, the court said. The jury's final session lasted more than two hours. It was their fourth meeting since the four-week trial concluded July 10. A simple majority of the eight-member panel would be enough for a guilty verdict. A tie vote would mean acquittal. Prosecutor <PERSON> Anders </PERSON> <PERSON> Helin </PERSON> cautioned against drawing a firm conclusion about the verdict from the court's announcement, but said `` normally this would point to a guilty verdict.'' <PERSON> Helin </PERSON> said he assumed <PERSON> Pettersson </PERSON> would appeal a guilty verdict to the <ORGANIZATION> Superior </ORGANIZATION> <ORG