higher casualty toll, Hoss appeal to Arab leaders. Picks up 7th pvs, ```May
someone ...' EDITS thereafter to trim.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMMED SALAM</BYLINE>
<UNK>Associated Press Writer</UNK>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Howitzer shells and rockets rained on <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION>'s Moslem and <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION> sectors today in one of the fiercest overnight duels between Syrian and <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION> army gunners in 18 weeks of fighting. Police said four people were killed and 49 wounded. The shells hit residential buildings on both sides of <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION>'s dividing <ORGANIZATION> Green </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Line </ORGANIZATION>, starting hundreds of fires and covering the city with a blanket of rubble and glass shards Streets were full of cars reduced to smoldering piles of metal. Tongues of flame shot up in the sky and smoke billowed from blasted buildings. Fire brigades were unable to combat blazes due to a shortage of water caused by a power failure. Ambulances, their sirens wailing, sped through the streets to evacuate the latest casualties, which raised the overall toll to 424 killed and 1,741 wounded since the current round of fighting broke out March 8. Several Syrian artillery positions in <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION>'s seafront <PERSON> Ein </PERSON> <PERSON> Mreisseh </PERSON> boulevard took direct hits and a police spokesman said many Syrian soldiers were killed or wounded. `` We do n't have a breakdown because the Syrian command does not report its losses to us,'' said the spokesman, who can not be named under standing regulations. At least eight Syrian army trucks loaded with rocket ammunition and gasoline were gutted, according to a Lebanese eyewitness. One 155mm howitzer shell crashed at a road intersection across the street from the Italian Embassy in west <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> Wardieh </LOCATION> district, wrecking a cluster of chic boutiques and the city's most fashionable florist, <LOCATION> Florelle </LOCATION>. The barrage, according to police, reached an intensity of about 30 shells per minute at times. Police said at least 700 buildi