<BYLINE>By ANNIE HUANG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TAIPEI, Taiwan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Grenada </LOCATION> today established relations with <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION>, becoming the first nation to have relations with both the Nationalist government in <LOCATION> Taipei </LOCATION> and the communist government in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>. The move was seen as a defeat for communist Chinese foreign policy because it followed <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION>'s crackdown on pro-democracy demonstrations and because <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> asks countries that recognize it to break relations with <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Grenada </LOCATION>, the tiny island nation in the <LOCATION> Carribean </LOCATION>, established relations with the communist government in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> in 1985. There was no immediate reaction from <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Grenada </LOCATION>'s move today. <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION> also used to demand that countries break relations with <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> before establishing ties with <LOCATION> Taipei </LOCATION>. But in a break with the past, Vice Foreign Minister <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> King </PERSON> said <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION> did not ask <LOCATION> Grenada </LOCATION> to sever ties with <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> as a condition because `` this is not necessary.'' <PERSON> King </PERSON> said <LOCATION> Grenada </LOCATION> decided to recognize <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION> after the communists began their crackdown. `` They reviewed their <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> policy and they believed the establishment of official ties with us can help promote world peace and freedom,'' King told a news conference. The international standing of the Nationalists has waned since they lost a civil war to communist forces on the Chinese mainland in 1949. The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> rapprochement with <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> in the 1970s dealt a further blow to <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION>'s status. The number of countries with form