<HEAD>Protesters Bid Food, Blood, Toilet Seats For Home of Tax Resisters</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GREENFIELD, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The government acquired the home of a pair of tax resisters after the only bidders at an auction were protesters whose offers ranged from toilet seats to food for the poor. More than 300 people, many carrying banners and placards denouncing military spending, gathered outside the <ORGANIZATION> Internal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Revenue </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> office here Wednesday for the auction of the home of <PERSON> Randall </PERSON> <PERSON> Kehler </PERSON> and his wife, <PERSON> Betsy </PERSON> <PERSON> Corner </PERSON>. The couple have not paid federal taxes in 12 years to protest the federal government's military spending. <PERSON> Kehler </PERSON> is a founder of the Nuclear Freeze campaign and its first national chairman. One group of protesters offered $ 21,414 worth of food and donated services to the poor. Their canned goods were heaped on a truck next to the <ORGANIZATION> IRS </ORGANIZATION> office. <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Deters </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Montague </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> offered 10 toilet seats, which he asserted would meet the $ 5,100 minimum bid if priced according to <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Defense Department procurement standards. Other bids included a guided tour of <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> for Secretary of State <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Baker </PERSON>. All 90 offers were rejected because they did not constitute legal tender, said <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Ruttenberg </PERSON>, an <ORGANIZATION> IRS </ORGANIZATION> spokesman. The government acquired the home in the northwest <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> town of <LOCATION> Colrain </LOCATION> for the minimum bid of $ 5,100. The couple has six months to get their home back by paying $ 27,000 in taxes, <PERSON> Ruttenberg </PERSON> said. But <PERSON> Kehler </PERSON> said they would not pay. He also promised that he, his wife and their 9-year-old daughter would not comply with an eviction order. <PERSON> Kehler </PERSON> said he and his wife have filed returns and donated the money owed to local charities and peace groups. They have continued to pay state and local taxes, he said. <PERSON> Ruttenberg </PERSON> said the number of tax resisters protesting military spending has dropped to about 5,000 from about 22,000 in the early 1980s.
