<HEAD>Top Opposition Leader Arrested In Burma</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New thruout to UPDATE with arrest of opposition leader. No pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER ENG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Authorities put <LOCATION> Burma </LOCATION>'s top opposition leader, <PERSON> Aung </PERSON> <PERSON> San </PERSON> <PERSON> Suu </PERSON> <PERSON> Kyi </PERSON>, under house arrest today after a day of unrest in that country's capital, according to a Western embassy report. The arrest came after police beat protesters Wednesday during a holiday marking national independence. State radio said 44 other people were reported arrested during the protests. Troops of the military government of Gen. Saw <PERSON> Maung </PERSON> surrounded Ms. <PERSON> Suu </PERSON> <PERSON> Kyi </PERSON>'s house in a suburb of the capital, <LOCATION> Rangoon </LOCATION>, and kept her there, said a source who spoke on condition of anonymity. He got his information from a report of a Western embassy in <LOCATION> Rangoon </LOCATION> that he would not identify further. `` She tried to surrender herself to the military, but they refused and they forced her back inside,'' said the source. He said a diplomat and Tin Oo, co-leader of Ms. <PERSON> Suu </PERSON> <PERSON> Kyi </PERSON>'s National League for Democracy, went to see her, but they were turned away Other details were not immediately available. Operators said telephone and telex lines to <LOCATION> Rangoon </LOCATION> from <LOCATION> Bangkok </LOCATION> were out of order today. The source said the reason for the arrest of Ms. <PERSON> Suu </PERSON> <PERSON> Kyi </PERSON>, the daughter of a celebrated independence leader, was unclear. He said the government may have used the violence during Wednesday's Martyrs Day ceremonies as a pretext to move against her. He said her arrest may also be linked to those of three members of her party. Authorities accused the three of bombing a government oil refinery earlier this month in an attack that killed three people. Ms. <PERSON> Suu </PERSON> <PERSON> Kyi </PERSON> is the most vocal critic of the authoritarian government that has ruled under martial law since army commander <PERSON> Saw </PERSON> <PERSON> Maung </PERSON> seized power in a coup in September and killed hundreds of people to crush a nationwide campaign for democracy. Saw <PERSON> Maung </PERSON> has pledged to hold a general election by early next year, and Western diplomats in <LOCATION> Rangoon </LOCATION> say authorities have been increasingly concerned by Ms. <PERSON> Suu </PERSON> <PERSON> Kyi </PERSON>'s growing popularity. `` <PERSON> Aung </PERSON> <PERSON> San </PERSON> <PERSON> Suu </PERSON> <PERSON> Kyi </PERSON> has been looking for a confrontation. Now it's happened,'' the source in <LOCATION> Bangkok </LOCATION> said Ms. <PERSON> Suu </PERSON> <PERSON> Kyi </PERSON>, 44, had vowed to lead thousands of people on a march Wednesday to mark the day her father, <PERSON> Aung </PERSON> <PERSON> San </PERSON>, and other <LOCATION> Burmese </LOCATION> independence leaders were assassinated in 1947. She canceled the rally, however, to avoid bloodshed as troops flooded the streets of the capital and erected barricades. The soldiers `` blocked off all the roads and prepared literally a killing field for the people,'' said Ms. <PERSON> Suu </PERSON> <PERSON> Kyi </PERSON> in a telephone interview from <LOCATION> Bangkok </LOCATION> Wednesday before her reported arrest. Witnesses said troops scattered hundreds of student demonstrators who defied martial law. State-run radio reported 44 arrests. Ms. <PERSON> Suu </PERSON> <PERSON> Kyi </PERSON> said soldiers used sticks to beat some of the 3,000 student protesters in the capital's <LOCATION> Swegondine </LOCATION> district. A Western diplomat, also reached by telephone, said he saw soldiers chase a group of students down a side street, drag some of them out and hit them with sticks before putting 15 to 20 of them into a truck. State radio said Wednesday night more than 1,400 people gathered at seven areas of the city despite martial law. It said they chanted, carried anti-government banners and distributed protest literature while marching. A text of that broadcast was seen in <LOCATION> Bangkok </LOCATION> today. A heavily-guarded ceremony sponsored by the government was held at the Martyrs Mausoleum without incident Wednesday morning, though most opposition parties boycotted it. Also Wednesday, Briton <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Storey </PERSON>, chief correspondent in <LOCATION> Bangkok </LOCATION> for the <ORGANIZATION> Reuters </ORGANIZATION> news agency, said authorities expelled him from the country.
