 Typhoon <PERSON> Gordon </PERSON> left at least 17 people dead and more than 100 injured when it slammed into southern <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>, cutting communication lines and washing away roads and crops, the official <ORGANIZATION> China </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Daily </ORGANIZATION> reported today. The paper said 13 people were missing and that damages totaled about $ 27 million. The storm hit on Wednesday. Eight of the dead and 80 of the injured were in <LOCATION> Yangjiang </LOCATION>, one of the hardest hit areas in coastal <LOCATION> Guangdong </LOCATION> province, the paper said. About 250 fishing boats capsized, 22 bridges collapsed and 156 miles of highway were washed away, the report said. Eight other people died in Zhaoqing in central <LOCATION> Guangdong </LOCATION>, and one person was killed in the <ORGANIZATION> Zhuhai </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Special </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Zone </ORGANIZATION>, near <LOCATION> Macao </LOCATION>, where most of the coastal dikes were destroyed and 4,200 acres of sugar cane fields, rice paddies and fish ponds were flooded, the paper said. Thousands of people in the provincial capital of <LOCATION> Canton </LOCATION> were stranded and telecommunications were knocked out, it said. The nationally televised evening news on Wednesday showed footage of waves crashing over sea walls, flooded streets and buildings with only rooftops visible. The typhoon first hit the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION> early Sunday with winds of up to 116 mph, killing 32 people, injuring 43 and leaving almost 186,000 people homeless on the islands. It caused at least $ 30 million in damage, according to the Office of Civil Defense. <PERSON> Gordon </PERSON>'s raging winds hit <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION> on Tuesday, killing one person before moving on to <LOCATION> Guangdong </LOCATION> province. It was downgraded to a tropical storm Wednesday morning, t