<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Benjamin </PERSON> <PERSON> Tammuz </PERSON>, a prominent Russian-born Israeli author, sculptor and proponent of Jewish-Arab coexistence, has died at age 70. Israeli news reports said his death Wednesday was caused by cancer and that he had kept his illness secret from most of his friends. <PERSON> Tammuz </PERSON> was known as one of <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>'s foremost modern writers whose books contained humorous and introspective portrayals of <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>'s pioneer generation He published dozens of books, short stories and satirical columns in the prestigious Haaretz daily. Among the most popular is a humorous sketch of pioneer days called `` The Life of Elyakum.'' He was also among the leaders of the defunct <ORGANIZATION> Canaanite </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Movement </ORGANIZATION>, which left-wing poets and artists began before <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>'s founding in 1948. The movement sought a way of forging Jewish-Arab cooperation. The Canaanites wanted to build a new `` Hebrew'' nation, as opposed to a Jewish one, to circumvent conflict with the Arabs. The biblical name came from ancient <LOCATION> Canaan </LOCATION>, the promised land of the Israelites who subjugated it after their flight from <LOCATION> Egypt </LOCATION>. The movement never gained support in <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> and is now mostly credited for its important role in transforming biblical Hebrew into a modern language. In his last televised interview about a week ago, <PERSON> Tammuz </PERSON> suggested that the 19-month Palestinian uprising in the occupied territories had reinvigorated his Canaanite beliefs. <PERSON> Tammuz </PERSON> studied history at the <LOCATION> Sorbonne </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION> in 1950-51 and later edited `` Art in <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>,'' a survey of <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> art trends in the 1960s. He was a sculptor and participated in numerous group shows. He designed a monument to fallen Israeli pilots which is now at <LOCATION> Tel </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Aviv </LOCATION>'s Independence Park. <PERSON> Tammuz </PERSON> will be buried Thursday in Holon, a suburb of his <LOCATION> Tel </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Aviv </LOCATION> hometown.
