<HEAD>State Report Clears Utility in Rocket Fuel Plant Explosion</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRENDAN RILEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CARSON CITY, Nev. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A natural gas line beneath a rocket fuel plant destroyed in an explosion last year was under too much pressure but did n't cause the blast, state regulators have concluded. The state <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> investigative report into the <ORGANIZATION> Pacific </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Engineering </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Production </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> explosion in May 1988 also cited inadequate record-keeping and inspections by the gas supplier, <ORGANIZATION> Southwest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Gas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp </ORGANIZATION>. But the three `` probable noncompliances identified during the course of the investigation were not responsible for the Pepcon fire and explosions,'' the commission's staff reported Wednesday. The explosion killed two people, injured 326 and caused $ 73 million in damage. <PERSON> Pepcon </PERSON> sued <ORGANIZATION> Southwest </ORGANIZATION> for $ 30 million, claiming the utility's pipeline was primarily responsible, and has since relocated its plant in <LOCATION> Utah </LOCATION>. The report's finding runs counter to theories that a huge gas leak triggered the blast or that a small gas leak over a 2-week period before the explosion had saturated the ground and caused a fire that led to the explosion. A county fire department report has said the explosion was touched off by a welder's torch that ignited large quantities of ammonium perchlorate, a component used in solid rocket fuel. The state report, released on the condition that it not be used for any litigation, said commission engineers determined that <ORGANIZATION> Southwest </ORGANIZATION> was generally operating within federal pipeline safety rules. However, at the time of the explosion <ORGANIZATION> Southwest </ORGANIZATION>'s 16-inch gas supply line buried beneath the <LOCATION> Pepcon </LOCATION> plant was under 308 to 310 pounds per square inch of pressure, slightly above the 300-pound maximum, the report states. The report said the pressure `` was not considered by staff to be detrimental to the serviceability of the pipeline.'' The report also says <ORGANIZATION> Southwest </ORGANIZATION> was over the 15-month time limit for a pipe station inspection, but there was no evidence of a leak in the line. Southwest had n't opposed release of the commission report, saying it would vindicate the utility.
</TEXT>
