<HEAD>Scientists Brew Semiconductors From Yeast</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Scientists have discovered that a simple kind of yeast creates excellent specimens of a new kind of matter _ semiconducting crystals so small they behave somewhat like individual atoms or molecules. The yeast organisms produce the tiny crystals when exposed to cadmium, a highly toxic metal, in a process that apparently detoxifies the metal. Semiconducting crystals are the basis of chips that are used for all kinds of electronic devices. Studying the tiny yeast-generated crystals should help researchers understand how small transistors can be shrunk before they begin to take on the quantum properties of atoms and molecules, losing their normal semiconducting properties. A paper on the findings was published in the April 13 issue of the journal Nature by physicists at <ORGANIZATION> AT </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> T </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Laboratories </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Murray </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hill </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.J. </LOCATION>, and biochemists at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Utah </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Salt </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lake </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>. It was not until the <LOCATION> Utah </LOCATION> researchers contacted the <ORGANIZATION> Bell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Labs </ORGANIZATION> scientists that the two groups realized the yeast had created the first biological specimens of the kind of particles the physicists were probing.
</TEXT>
