to insert N.C. in dateline.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL NOWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHARLOTTE, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A former aide to <ORGANIZATION> PTL </ORGANIZATION> founder <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Bakker </PERSON> testified in court today that the evangelist gave him the authority to take large cash advances and use ministry credit cards. <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Taggart </PERSON> and his brother, <PERSON> James </PERSON>, are charged with evading $ 525,000 in federal income taxes while associated with <ORGANIZATION> PTL </ORGANIZATION>. Under questioning by defense lawyer <PERSON> Ben </PERSON> <PERSON> Cotten </PERSON>, <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Taggart </PERSON> said that as a vice president of the ministry, he had direct authority from <PERSON> Bakker </PERSON> to take large cash advances, sign <ORGANIZATION> PTL </ORGANIZATION> checks, use <ORGANIZATION> PTL </ORGANIZATION> credit cards and authorize bonuses for <ORGANIZATION> PTL </ORGANIZATION> employees. <PERSON> Taggart </PERSON> said he gained the authority when <PERSON> Bakker </PERSON> and his wife, <PERSON> Tammy </PERSON>, lured him back to the ministry after a brief absence he attributed to exhaustion. The cash advances, <PERSON> Taggart </PERSON> said, were used primarily for trips by the <ORGANIZATION> Bakkers </ORGANIZATION> on ministry business. He claimed that money used for personal expenses was reimbursed, but said, `` I always have been lax about documentation. It's never been a priority.'' <PERSON> Taggart </PERSON>'s testimony came a day after <PERSON> Bakker </PERSON> invoked his Fifth Amendment right against self-incrimination in refusing to answer questions by defense and prosecuting attorneys. <PERSON> Bakker </PERSON>'s 10-minute appearance in the federal courtroom was without the presence of the jury. `` When his trial comes about, there will be no taking of the Fifth Amendment and no refusal to answer any questions that the government cares to ask and to go into the entire matter in depth,'' said <PERSON> Bakker </PERSON> attorney <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> T. </PERSON> <PERSON> Davis </PERSON>. <PERSON> Bakker </PERSON> and former top <ORGANIZATION> PTL </ORGANIZATION> aide <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Dortch </PERSON> are scheduled to go on trial for conspiracy and wire and mail fraud on Aug. 28. After <PERSON> Bakker </PERSON> refused to answer questions, Judge <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Potter </PERSON> released the witness, saying, `` This court will not force him to testify.'' <PERSON> Cotten </PERSON> said he is barred from mentioning to the jury that <PERSON> Bakker </PERSON> ever appeared in court. <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Taggart </PERSON> took the stand Wednesday and described his association with <PERSON> Bakker </PERSON>. Both Taggarts were fired when <PERSON> Jerry </PERSON> <PERSON> Falwell </PERSON> took over at the television ministry following <PERSON> Bakker </PERSON>'s resignation in March 1987 following revelations of the <PERSON> Jessica </PERSON> <PERSON> Hahn </PERSON> sex-and-money scandal.
