<HEAD>Eds: Adds last two grafs with other members; also removes ``Indiana''
from summary line.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CONNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> today named a housewife with AIDS and a medical professor as his selections for the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> on Acquired Immune Deficiency Syndrome. Three Cabinet officers also will serve on the 15-member panel created by law last November to advise the president and <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> on AIDS policy for the next two years. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s choices are: _ <PERSON> Belinda </PERSON> <PERSON> Ann </PERSON> <PERSON> Mason </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION> with AIDS _ Dr <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Rogers </PERSON>, a professor of medicine at <ORGANIZATION> Cornell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION> and former president of the <ORGANIZATION> Robert </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Wood </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Johnson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foundation </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Princeton </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.J. </LOCATION>. Ms. <PERSON> Mason </PERSON>, 30, contracted AIDS from a blood transfusion she received while experiencing difficulties in the birth of her second child in 1987, according to <PERSON> Mike </PERSON> <PERSON> Merdian </PERSON>, executive director of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION> with AIDS She was then living in rural <LOCATION> Hartford </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ky. </LOCATION>, and experienced difficulties getting adequate medical treatment, <PERSON> Merdian </PERSON> said. Neighbors' fears also prompted her family to move, and she has been living most recently in <LOCATION> Owensboro </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ky. <