<HEAD>CBO Offers Tough Choices to Meet Federal Deficit Targets</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Greenspan Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MATT YANCEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Meeting deficit reduction targets in fiscal 1991 without a tax increase or a cutback in Social Security benefits would require a 10 percent across-the-board cut in federal spending, the <ORGANIZATION> Congressional </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Budget </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> said Tuesday. The $ 74 billion to $ 88 billion in spending cuts needed to meet the fiscal 1991 defict tartget of $ 64 billion without raising taxes would likely force the economy into a recession unless the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> further loosens its reins on inflation substantially, the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Budget </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> was told. `` The central bank would have to permit faster money growth and a substantial decline in interest rates to ... offset the direct depressing effect of actions taken to reduce the deficit,'' <ORGANIZATION> CBO </ORGANIZATION> Director <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Reischauer </PERSON> told the panel. <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Alan </PERSON> <PERSON> Greenspan </PERSON> told the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Banking </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> that he is willing to push interest rates lower to avoid a recession, but warned it is `` a difficult balancing act.'' `` Some day, some event will end the extraordinary sting of economic advances that has prevailed since late 1982,'' he said. <PERSON> Reischauer </PERSON> put the chances of the economy slipping into a recession during the next nine months `` in the 15 percent to 40 percent range.'' `` Retail sales have been disappointing in recent months ... -LRB- but -RRB- the weakness is at least partly offset by continued growth in personal income,'' he said. `` The stock market, which has always fallen before in previous recessions, continues to rise. And the recent decline in interest rates is likely eventually to help housing and spending on durable goods.'' But, like the <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> CBO </ORGANIZATION> is forecasting a more modest 2.4 percent rate of economic growth this year, slowing to 2 percent in 1990. The administration has predicted the economy will grow by 2.7 percent this year and 2.6 percent next after adjustments for inflation. The congressional forecasters also think inflation, interest rates and unemployment for all of this year and 1990 will higher than what the administration has forecast, but only slightly. With the economy slowing, it also predicts that civilian unemployment will rise from its current 5.3 percent to average 5.5 percent in 1990. The <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> committee's chairman, Rep. <PERSON> Leon </PERSON> <PERSON> Panetta </PERSON>, D-Calif., said the <ORGANIZATION> CBO </ORGANIZATION>'s economic growth projections have consistently been less optimistic `` and more accurate'' that those of the administration `` Despite the soft landing projected by both <ORGANIZATION> CBO </ORGANIZATION> and the administration,'' <PERSON> Panetta </PERSON> said, it will be impossible to meet 1991-93 deficit reductions targets of $ 64 billion, $ 28 billion and zero without a tax increase or cuts in `` non-means-tested entitlements'' such as Social Security. <PERSON> Reischauer </PERSON> said the <ORGANIZATION> CBO </ORGANIZATION> has reduced its estimate for the deficit for the current fiscal year that ends on Sept. 30 from $ 159 billion forecast last February to $ 150 billion. `` Although the 1989 deficit is almost certain to exceed the Balanced Budget Act target of $ 136 billion, it may not exceed the target by much more than $ 10 billion allowed in the law,'' he said. Although the congressional auditors have not yet incorporated their economic projections into budget estimates, <PERSON> Reischauer </PERSON> said the deficit outlook for 1990 is unlikely to change substantially from <ORGANIZATION> CBO </ORGANIZATION>'s forecast of $ 116.8 billion to $ 140.1 billion. The difference in those figues is whether <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> includes the immediate $ 50 billion cost of the savings and loan bailout in the deficit as Democrats want or finances it through 30-year private bonds as advocated by President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s S & amp; L bailout plan would actually reduce the deficit by $ 3 billion next year because the money collected through the bonds would count as revenues to the government.
