<HEAD>Burma Puts Opposition Leader Under House Arrest</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER ENG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Burma </LOCATION>'s military government put the main opposition leader under house arrest Thursday and soldiers sealed off her home in a <LOCATION> Rangoon </LOCATION> suburb, according to diplomatic reports from the Burmese capital. Hundreds of students had defied martial law with anti-government protests Wednesday even though the opposition leader, <PERSON> Aung </PERSON> <PERSON> San </PERSON> <PERSON> Suu </PERSON> <PERSON> Kyi </PERSON>, canceled a planned rally to avoid clashes with the large number of soldiers in the streets. <LOCATION> Burma </LOCATION>'s official radio reported 44 arrests. A source in <LOCATION> Bangkok </LOCATION>, citing a report from a Western embassy in the <LOCATION> Burmese </LOCATION> capital, said Ms. <PERSON> Suu </PERSON> <PERSON> Kyi </PERSON>'s `` compound was surrounded by troops'' and `` she tried to surrender herself to the military, but they refused and they forced her back inside.'' The source, speaking on condition of anonymity, said a diplomat and Tin Oo, co-leader of Ms. <PERSON> Suu </PERSON> <PERSON> Kyi </PERSON>'s <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> League </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democracy </ORGANIZATION>, were turned away when they tried to see her. No other details were available. Telephone and telex lines to <LOCATION> Rangoon </LOCATION> from <LOCATION> Bangkok </LOCATION> and other <LOCATION> Asian </LOCATION> cities were out of order Thursday. In <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> confirmed Ms. <PERSON> Suu </PERSON> <PERSON> Kyi </PERSON>, 44, was under house arrest and that soldiers were blocking access to her home. It said the arrest of opposition activists `` cast serious doubts'' on the government's stated intention of holding free elections next year. <LOCATION> Rangoon </LOCATION> radio did not mention Ms. <PERSON> Suu </PERSON> <PERSON> Kyi </PERSON> on Thursday, but said diplomats were being summoned to a meeting Friday with the government's <ORGANIZATION> Information </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>. It announced an amnesty for people tried on or before Sept. 18, 1988. Gen. Saw <PERSON> Maung </PERSON>, the army commander, seized power on that day and his soldiers killed hundreds of people demonstrating peacefully for democracy. Saw <PERSON> Maung </PERSON> signed the amnesty order, which commutes death sentences to life imprisonment, reduces life terms to 10 years and cuts other sentences by one-third. Prisoners with two years or less to serve will be released and criminal cases still being heard will be closed, with the exceptions of those involving high treason or violation of martial law, the order said. The <LOCATION> Bangkok </LOCATION> source said the reason for Ms. <PERSON> Suu </PERSON> <PERSON> Kyi </PERSON>'s arrest was not clear, but the government may have used violence during Wednesday's Martyrs Day ceremonies as a pretext to move against her. He said her arrest also might be linked to those of three members of her party accused of bombing a government oil refinery earlier this month. Three people were killed. Ms. <PERSON> Suu </PERSON> <PERSON> Kyi </PERSON>, whose father was an independence leader, is the military government's most vocal critic. Western diplomats say the authorities have been concerned about the growing popularity that attracts thousands of people to her rallies. `` <PERSON> Aung </PERSON> <PERSON> San </PERSON> <PERSON> Suu </PERSON> <PERSON> Kyi </PERSON> has been looking for a confrontation,'' the source in <LOCATION> Bangkok </LOCATION> said. `` Now it's happened.'' Ms. <PERSON> Suu </PERSON> <PERSON> Kyi </PERSON> had planned to lead thousands in a march Wednesday, the anniversary of the day her father, <PERSON> Aung </PERSON> <PERSON> San </PERSON>, and other <LOCATION> Burmese </LOCATION> independence leaders were assassinated in 1947. <LOCATION> Burma </LOCATION> became independent of <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> in January 1948. On Wednesday, Ms. <PERSON> Suu </PERSON> <PERSON> Kyi </PERSON> said she canceled the march because soldiers `` blocked off all the roads and prepared literally a killing field for the people.'' In a telephone interview from <LOCATION> Rangoon </LOCATION>, she also said soldiers had beaten some of about 3,000 students in the capital's <LOCATION> Swegondine </LOCATION> district. A Western diplomat, also reached by telephone, said he saw soldiers pursue students down a side street, drag some out and hit them with clubs, then put 15 or 20 into a truck.
