<HEAD>Platte, Klamath Top List Of Most Endangered Rivers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LES BLUMENTHAL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <LOCATION> Platte </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Colorado </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Nebraska </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Klamath </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Oregon </LOCATION> topped a list of the 10 most endangered rivers released by a national conservation group Thursday. Other rivers included the American in <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> Penobscot </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Maine </LOCATION>, the <PERSON> Payette </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Idaho </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> James </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> Little </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bighorn </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Wyoming </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bayou </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Arkansas </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Animas </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Colorado </LOCATION>. `` These rivers are national treasures, because of their free flowing nature, ecological qualities and recreational values,'' said <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kent </PERSON> <PERSON> Olson </PERSON>, president of <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rivers </ORGANIZATION>. `` Yet, these outstanding rivers _ and, often, their scenic landscapes _ face imminent, major threats from uneeded dams, water projects or adverse land development.'' <PERSON> Olson </PERSON> said his group released its annual list to `` call attention to the fact that they are in danger but are not dead, yet.'' The rivers were selected based on their national or regional significance and the `` degree and imminence'' of the threats they face. <PERSON> Olson </PERSON> said that six of the rivers on the list were threatened by hydroelectric projects and the others threatened by flood control and water supply projects and nearby land development. The group sai