<HEAD>Georgia Tech Microfilm Disappearance Part of Nationwide Theft</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EMILY BENTLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 One hundred reels of microfilm copies of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> patents have disappeared from the library at <ORGANIZATION> Georgie </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tech </ORGANIZATION>, and library officials say it appears to be part of a nationwide theft. A library worker noticed about three weeks ago that sections of the microfilm seemed to be missing, <PERSON> Miriam </PERSON> <PERSON> Drake </PERSON>, dean and director of libraries at <ORGANIZATION> Georgia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tech </ORGANIZATION>, said Tuesday. An inventory indicated 100 cartridges were gone. `` We discovered it, and then we heard very quickly that the same thing had happened at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Massachusetts </ORGANIZATION>. The patent office notified us immediately that this was going on,'' Ms. <PERSON> Drake </PERSON> said. In addition, 10 other universities that are depositories for copies of patent records have reported thefts, she said. Ms. <PERSON> Drake </PERSON> said that because it appears different blocks of the patent records from the past 20 years were taken from each university `` it appears they are amassing a 20-year run of patents.'' `` They did n't take everything in one year,'' Ms. <PERSON> Drake </PERSON> said. `` The dates they took from us were from 1971 to 1974 and 1977 to 1978. But in the 1971 period, they took 42 cartridges and only 10 of 1978.'' <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> O. </PERSON> <PERSON> Craig </PERSON>, a spokesman for the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Patent </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trademark </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION>, based in the <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> suburb of <LOCATION> Arlington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Va. </LOCATION>, said Wednesday, `` The matter is under investigation.'' The loss of the microfilms will not have any impact on the patents themselves beca