<HEAD>Concentration Camp Survivor to Reunite With American Liberators</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FRANK BAKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CONCORD, N.H. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Dick </PERSON> <PERSON> Fitzsimmons </PERSON> does n't how he'll react when he sees <PERSON> Vladimir </PERSON> <PERSON> Kutz </PERSON> of the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> for the first time in more than 44 years. But he knows the reunion Tuesday with the man he knew as a skinny teen-ager he helped save from a Nazi concentration camp will be a happy one. `` I never expected to see him again, and when I do, I probably wo n't be able to say a word,'' <PERSON> Fitzsimmons </PERSON> said. `` It all just does n't seem real.'' <PERSON> Fitzsimmons </PERSON> was an 18-year-old American infantryman serving in <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> when he met <PERSON> Kutz </PERSON>, 17, doing slave labor at a Nazi work camp at the end of World War II in March 1945. <PERSON> Kutz </PERSON> is scheduled to fly to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> from his <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> home to <LOCATION> Dover </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.H. </LOCATION>, for the reunion with <PERSON> Fitzsimmons </PERSON>, 63, a retired electrician in <LOCATION> Rutland </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Vt. </LOCATION>, and <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Riska </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Connecticut </LOCATION>. In August, <PERSON> Kutz </PERSON> is to meet two other men from the old 4th Infantry Division, <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Nystrom </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Harrisburg </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Pa. </LOCATION>, and <PERSON> Patrick </PERSON> <PERSON> Mealy </PERSON> of <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>. The five will have plenty to talk about because it's likely none of them them would have lived to see the end of the war if they had never met. The young prisoner returned the favor of his freedom by warning the Americans of a German ambush. The Americans were ready and `` fought right through them,'' <PERSON> Fitzsimmons </PERSON> remembers. The reunion was arranged by <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Barr </PERSON>, vice president