<DATELINE>PROKOPYEVSK, U.S.S.R. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Coal miners walked off their jobs in five more regions, but the Siberian strikers who started the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>'s worst labor unrest in decades were told Thursday to return to work by dawn Friday. `` We have agreed to interrupt the strike, not to end it,'' said <PERSON> Vyacheslav </PERSON> <PERSON> G. </PERSON> <PERSON> Akulov </PERSON>, a strike committee member in <LOCATION> Prokopyevsk </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Siberia </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> Kuznetsk </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Coal </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Basin </LOCATION>. The strike committee asked the estimated 150,000 strikers in the region to return to the pits at dawn Friday after a government and <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> commission agreed to give them greater control over their industry, <PERSON> Akulov </PERSON> said. The commission also agreed to improve the miners' food, housing and working conditions. President <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> has said the concessions granted the miners in the <LOCATION> Kuznetsk </LOCATION> region will apply to all miners nationwide. State-run TV repeated that promise Thursday night in an apparent effort to end the country's worst labor unrest since the 1920s. Some Siberian miners have already returned to work. <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> said nine out of 11 mining centers were operating, and <LOCATION> Prokopyevsk </LOCATION>'s central Victory Square was empty Thursday night after nearly two weeks of rallies and demonstrations by thousands of strikers But the strike spread in other areas as miners raised demands similar to those of the <LOCATION> Kuznetsk </LOCATION> strikers, who began the walkout 10 days ago. Miners in the northern town of <LOCATION> Vorkuta </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> Don </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> city of <LOCATION> Rostov </LOCATION> and the Ukrainian industrial center of <LOCATION> D