<HEAD>Ministers Agree to Forming Pan-African Defense Force</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By REID G. MILLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ADDIS ABABA, Ethiopia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 African foreign ministers agreed in principle Thursday to form a pan-African military force to help black states resist incursions by <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>. The Organization of African Unity's council of ministers adopted a recommendation calling for a joint defense force but put off its creation pending a study on how it would be funded. The 50-member <ORGANIZATION> OAU </ORGANIZATION> has been plagued by financial problems throughout its 26-year history. Many members are badly behind on their annual dues. The organization has considered assembling a similar force in the past, but the idea has never passed the conceptual stage. <PERSON> Sylvestre </PERSON> <PERSON> Nganzimana </PERSON>, an <ORGANIZATION> OAU </ORGANIZATION> assistant secretary, said the proposed force would be made up of military units from members nations which could be called up as a unified force. `` What is envisioned is a force that would assist the frontline states, which have suffered incursions and destabilization by <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>,'' he said. `` It would also work closely with national liberation organizations and act as a peacekeeping and observer force.'' The financial study was not due to be completed until next year. The <ORGANIZATION> OAU </ORGANIZATION>'s defense commission, which brought the recommendation to the council, noted in its report that the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> estimates the cost of keeping one of its typical peacekeeping forces in the field for six months at about $ 150 million. The frontline states comprise <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Botswana </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mozambique </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Tanzania </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Zambia </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Zimbabwe </LOCATION>. The foreign ministers were meeting in <LOCATION> Ethiopia </LOCATION>'s capital city this week to draw up an agenda for a conference of <ORGANIZATION> OAU </ORGANIZATION> heads of state. The meeting opens Monday.
