<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A second White House guard has been placed on administrative leave while the <ORGANIZATION> Secret </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> investigates possible violations involving a late-night tour last year, a spokeswoman said Thursday. <PERSON> Jane </PERSON> <PERSON> Vezeris </PERSON> refused to identify the second uniformed guard who worked with Officer <PERSON> Reginald </PERSON> <PERSON> deGueldre </PERSON>, the guard who has acknowledged giving lobbyist <PERSON> Craig </PERSON> <PERSON> Spence </PERSON> and his friends a private White House tour in July 1988. DeGueldre, who also told <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Washington </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> he accepted an $ 8,000 gold Rolex watch from <LOCATION> Spence </LOCATION>, was placed on administrative leave last week pending the outcome of the internal investigation. <PERSON> Spence </PERSON> has been linked to a homosexual call boy ring that is under investigation by <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Attorney <PERSON> Jay </PERSON> <PERSON> Stephens </PERSON> for possible credit card fraud. <PERSON> Vezeris </PERSON> said the agency is looking into whether any procedures were violated by allowing <PERSON> Spence </PERSON> on a private tour of the White House and whether anything improper behavior, such as the acceptance of gratuities, occurred. She did not know when the investigation would be finished.
