<HEAD>U.S. Loses World Court Case Over Plant Closure</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL VERSCHUUR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>THE HAGUE, Netherlands (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> on Thursday said the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> has no right to compensation from the Italian government for <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION>'s seizure of an American-owned plant 21 years ago. The five-judge panel ruled 4-1 that <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION> did not breach the 1948 Treaty of Friendship, <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Navigation </ORGANIZATION>, as alleged by <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, when it seized the <PERSON> Elettronica </PERSON> <PERSON> Sicula </PERSON>, or ELSI, plant in <LOCATION> Palermo </LOCATION> in 1968. It also voted 4-1 to deny compensation to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Stephen </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Schwebel </PERSON>, the court's only <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> judge, opposed the decision. <ORGANIZATION> ELSI </ORGANIZATION> was a cathode-ray tube factory wholly owned by <ORGANIZATION> Raytheon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, a major defense contractor, and by another <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> company, <ORGANIZATION> Machlett </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Laboratories </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>. <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION> contended the mayor of <LOCATION> Palermo </LOCATION> seized the company to safeguard the jobs of about 900 factory workers after the owners announced plans to liquidate the firm According to the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> complaint, the company was then sold to a subsidiary of a conglomerate owned by the Italian government `` at a price far less than market value,'' and <ORGANIZATION> Raytheon </ORGANIZATION> was never compensated. No specific compensation amounts were demanded in court, but <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> sources have claimed privately that <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> damages in the case were more than $ 6 million. The court, officially known as the <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION>, is the legal arm of the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION>. It has no enforcement powers and depends on voluntary adherence to its decisions. In court, the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> complained that a ruling on the case by an Italian court was delayed 16 months after the seizure until <ORGANIZATION> ELSI </ORGANIZATION> was sold. The judges said <ORGANIZATION> ELSI </ORGANIZATION> was on a `` course to bankruptcy'' even before it was seized. `` What really deprived <ORGANIZATION> Raytheon </ORGANIZATION> and <PERSON> Machlett </PERSON> as shareholders of their right to dispose of <ORGANIZATION> ELSI </ORGANIZATION>'s ... property was not the requisition but the precarious financial state of <ORGANIZATION> ELSI </ORGANIZATION> ultimately leading inescapably to bankruptcy,'' they said. Voting in favor were the court's Argentinian president, <PERSON> Jose </PERSON> <PERSON> Maria </PERSON> <PERSON> Ruda </PERSON>, as well as judges <PERSON> Roberto </PERSON> <PERSON> Ago </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Shigeru </PERSON> <PERSON> Oda </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> and Sir <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Jennings </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Schwebel </PERSON> said in a separate document attached to the ruling that <ORGANIZATION> ELSI </ORGANIZATION>'s seizure was an `` unreasonable and capricious'' measure that `` deprived <ORGANIZATION> Raytheon </ORGANIZATION> of its right to control and manage and, hence, liquidate ELSI.'' The ELSI case was filed in February 1987 after years of diplomatic bargaining failed to resolve the issue. In 1986, the <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> denounced U.S.-sponsored military action against <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> support for the anti-Sandinista forces known as Contras. Earlier that year, in an apparent anticipation of the adverse decision, <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> withdrew its recognition of the unlimited jurisdiction of the court but said it would continue to accept jurisdiction in some cases, such as the one involving <PERSON> Elettronica </PERSON> <PERSON> Sicula </PERSON>.
