<HEAD>Taggart Says He Was Lax About PTL Money Documentation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL NOWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHARLOTTE, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Bakker </PERSON>'s former personal aide testified Thursday in his federal tax evasion trial he did n't have any way to prove that cash advances he took while at the <ORGANIZATION> PTL </ORGANIZATION> ministry were for business use. <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Taggart </PERSON> said under cross-examination by prosecutor <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Brown </PERSON> that proper record keeping would have helped determine whether sums of money he drew from <ORGANIZATION> PTL </ORGANIZATION> accounts were taxable or not. <PERSON> Taggart </PERSON>, 32, and his brother, <PERSON> James </PERSON>, are charged with evading $ 525,000 in income taxes after taking nearly $ 1.2 million in <ORGANIZATION> PTL </ORGANIZATION> money for their own use during a four-year period beginning in 1984. Under questioning by defense lawyer <PERSON> Ben </PERSON> <PERSON> Cotten </PERSON>, <PERSON> Taggart </PERSON> said that as a vice president of the ministry, he had direct authority from <PERSON> Bakker </PERSON> to take large cash advances, sign <ORGANIZATION> PTL </ORGANIZATION> checks, use <ORGANIZATION> PTL </ORGANIZATION> credit cards and authorize bonuses for <ORGANIZATION> PTL </ORGANIZATION> employees. <PERSON> Taggart </PERSON> said he left <ORGANIZATION> PTL </ORGANIZATION> in early 1983 because of exhaustion and job burnout. He said <PERSON> Bakker </PERSON> and his wife, <PERSON> Tammy </PERSON>, called him numerous times with generous offers to entice him to return. `` He told me ` <PERSON> David </PERSON>, you've killed yourself for the ministry for $ 25,000 a year -LRB- as assistant music director from 1978 to 1980 and from 1980 to 1983 as <PERSON> Bakker </PERSON>'s personal assistant -RRB-. Now the ministry is in a different position and I'm willing to pay you $ 100,000 a year,'' <PERSON> Taggart </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Taggart </PERSON> said he recalled telling <PERSON> Bakker </PERSON>, `` I want access to the same resources that you have. But I also want to control my money. I do n't want a house or a car to be given to me.'' <PERSON> Taggart </PERSON> said that on his return, he had authority to take large cash advances, which he said were used primarily for trips by the <ORGANIZATION> Bakkers </ORGANIZATION> on ministry business. He said he needed large amounts of cash on hand at all times. `` Many times on a trip I would advance <PERSON> Tammy </PERSON> <PERSON> Bakker </PERSON> some cash and she would reimburse it,'' he said. That was true of dozens of other members of the <ORGANIZATION> Bakkers </ORGANIZATION>' entourage, he said. <PERSON> Taggart </PERSON>'s brother <PERSON> James </PERSON> testified Wednesday that as <ORGANIZATION> PTL </ORGANIZATION>'s interior designer he was an artist who left the business dealings to his brother `` I always have been lax about documentation. It's never been a priority,'' <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Taggart </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Taggart </PERSON>'s testimony came a day after <PERSON> Bakker </PERSON> invoked the Fifth Amendment in refusing to answer questions in the trial. His 10-minute appearance was with the jury not present. <PERSON> Bakker </PERSON> and former top <ORGANIZATION> PTL </ORGANIZATION> aide <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Dortch </PERSON> are scheduled to go on trial Aug. 28 on conspiracy and wire and mail fraud charges.
