<HEAD>House Panel Holds Hearing on Joint Newspapers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROSE ANN ROBERTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Legislation allowing rival newspapers to publish under a Joint Operating Agreement fails to save daily newspapers and should be repealed, the editor of a <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION> weekly told a <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> panel Thursday. `` It has encouraged concentration of newspaper ownership, peculiar competitive practices and lessened the vigor and quality of newspapering,'' <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION> editor <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> Wendover </PERSON> told the <ORGANIZATION> Judiciary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> panel. However, <PERSON> Jerry </PERSON> <PERSON> Friedheim </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Newspaper </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Publishers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, testified that the act `` helped the marketplace evolve and prosper.'' Rep. <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Brooks </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Texas </LOCATION>, called the hearing 19 years after <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> approved the Newspaper Preservation Act, which allows newspapers in the same city to merge business operations when one of the papers is in danger of failing. Newsgathering operations remain separate. `` In 1970, the act was hailed as a necessary means of preventing daily newspapers from falling victim to fierce market forces,'' <PERSON> Brooks </PERSON> said. `` Yet, since passage of the act, some estimate that over 200 papers have ceased operation.'' <LOCATION> Wendover </LOCATION>, editor and publisher of the weekly <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Community </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Crier </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Plymouth-Canton </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mich. </LOCATION>, testified on behalf of <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Citizens </LOCATION> for an <ORGANIZATION> Independent </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION>. That group, made up of 1,400 readers, advertisers and employees of <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Detroit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Detroit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Free </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION>, filed a lawsuit in August to block a JOA between the two papers. <ORGANIZATION> Gannett </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, which owns The News, and <ORGANIZATION> Knight-Ridder </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, owner of the <ORGANIZATION> Free </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION>, say the <ORGANIZATION> JOA </ORGANIZATION> is needed to allow the Free Press to survive The <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> will hear arguments on the case this fall. There are 18 active JOAs in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. `` The principle of a free press can not be maintained when the biggest newspaper chains enjoy unregulated monopoly status,'' Wendover said, calling on <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> to repeal the act. Harsh criticism came from <PERSON> Bruce </PERSON> <PERSON> B. </PERSON> <PERSON> Brugmann </PERSON>, editor and publisher of the 70,000 circulation weekly <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bay </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Guardian </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Brugmann </PERSON> also testified against the act when it was being considered in 1969. `` Never have so many given so much to so few for no good reason at all,'' <PERSON> Brugmann </PERSON> said, charging that the only people to benefit from JOAs are publishers. The <ORGANIZATION> JOA </ORGANIZATION> between the two <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION> dailies, the Examiner and the <ORGANIZATION> Chronicle </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Brugmann </PERSON> said, has led to less competitive journalism. Also critical of the act was <PERSON> Louis </PERSON> <PERSON> Mleczko </PERSON>, a reporter for <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Detroit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> and president of Local 22 of The Newspaper Guild of <LOCATION> Detroit </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Mleczko </PERSON>, who is opposed to the proposed <ORGANIZATION> Detroit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> JOA </ORGANIZATION>, said <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> should repeal the act and force giant chains to compete. `` Newspapers are more than just businesses, only concerned with the bottom line. They are a public trust,'' <PERSON> Mleczko </PERSON> said. `` The Robber Barons live. It's time for <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> to break up the trusts again.'' <PERSON> Brooks </PERSON> said his Economic and <ORGANIZATION> Commercial </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Law </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Subcommittee </ORGANIZATION> would study the testimony and decide whether further hearings are needed.
