<HEAD>Italian Duplicates First Cross-Channel Flight by Bleriot</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CALAIS, France (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 An Italian pilot flying a homemade replica of the <ORGANIZATION> Bleriot </ORGANIZATION> 11 that made the first air crossing of the English Channel 80 years ago duplicated the event Wednesday. <PERSON> Zanardo </PERSON> <PERSON> Juan </PERSON> <PERSON> Carlo </PERSON> took off from <LOCATION> Calais </LOCATION> airport at 5:25 p.m. in the plane that took him 2,500 hours of work to build. Fifty minutes later, he landed at the airport at <LOCATION> Manston </LOCATION> in southern <LOCATION> England </LOCATION>. The 48-year-old aviation enthusiast duplicated the journey of french aviation pioneer <PERSON> Louis </PERSON> <PERSON> Bleriot </PERSON>, who made the same trip on July 25, 1909. The latter-day version was accompanied across the Channel by six other planes: four Pipers and two Tiger Moths. The flight was organized by a group of Italian amateur aviation buffs.
