<HEAD>Nevada's Income Growth Paces the Nation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN D. McCLAIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Nevada </LOCATION>'s income growth, driven by the state's tourism and mining industries, outpaced other states during the year ending last March, while income growth in <LOCATION> Wyoming </LOCATION> trailed the rest of the country, the government reported Thursday The <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said said that non-farm incomes rose 9.4 percent nationally in the 12 months ending March 30. But the national average masked disparities among states and regions of the country. <LOCATION> Nevada </LOCATION> paced the country with a non-farm income increase of 15 percent, the department said. <LOCATION> Nevada </LOCATION>'s income growth was fueld by the hotel and resort construction demands of its tourism industry and a healthy mining industry, according to department analyst <PERSON> Rudolph </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> DePass </PERSON>. <LOCATION> Nevada </LOCATION> was followed by <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> whose non-farm income was up 12.1 percent; <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>, up 10.7 percent; <LOCATION> Vermont </LOCATION>, up 10.5 percent, and <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION>, up 10.5 percent. With inflation rising at an annual rate of 5.9 percent, the figures showed those states stayed well ahead of the increase in prices. Other states did not fare so well. Last-ranked <LOCATION> Wyoming </LOCATION> saw non-farm income growth rise only 5.7 percent, pulled down by declining construction and services industry, <PERSON> DePass </PERSON> said. Other states at the bottom-end of the rankings were <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION>, up 6.3 percent; <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Dakota </LOCATION>, up 6.4 percent; <LOCATION> Oklahoma </LOCATION>, up 6.9 percent, and <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION>, up 7.2 percent. By region, the Far West led the nation with an overall income growth of 10.5 percent, followed by the Southeast, 9.9 percent; and <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> England </LOCATION>, 9.6 percent. Other regions and their income growth rates were: Great Lakes, 9 percent; <LOCATION> Mideast </LOCATION>, 8.9 percent; <LOCATION> Plains </LOCATION>, 8.8 percent; <ORGANIZATION> Southwest </ORGANIZATION>, 8.6 percent, and <LOCATION> Rocky </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mountains </LOCATION>, 8.2 percent. <PERSON> DePass </PERSON> said differences in non-farm income growth between coastal and interior regions continued to grow smaller from the first quarter of 1988 to the first quarter of 1989, although coastal growth continued to outpace the inland areas. The <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> focuses on changes in non-farm income as a better indication of a region's prosperity because of the often erratic nature of farm incomes.
