<FIRST>r e AM-APArts:BadHemingway     07-20 0859</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-AP Arts: Bad Hemingway,0879</SECOND>
<HEAD>Parodying Hemingway in All Ernest-Ness</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Stands as a 1st Ld-Writethru to b0436, to CORRECT Hemingway's
birthday to July 21 sted July 28. Story is now released for spot use.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GENEVA COLLINS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 If <PERSON> Ernest </PERSON> <PERSON> Hemingway </PERSON> _ that aficionado of big guns, feisty bulls, lusty reds and really short sentences _ were alive today, the pugnacious Papa would be spoiling for a fight. The object of his disaffection would be `` The Best of Bad Hemingway'' -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> Harcourt </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Brace </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Jovanovich </ORGANIZATION>, $ 7.95 -RRB-, a compilation of the best entries to a now-defunct annual competition of Hemingway parodies. The ersatz <PERSON> Ernest </PERSON> contest was sponsored by <ORGANIZATION> Harry </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bar </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Grill </ORGANIZATION>, whose ingenious milking of an extremely tenuous <LOCATION> Hemingway </LOCATION> connection deserves induction into the Publicists' Hall of Fame. <PERSON> Hemingway </PERSON>, who would have been 90 on July 21, was no stranger to parody. His second novel, `` The Torrents of Spring,'' was a cruel mimickry of <PERSON> Sherwood </PERSON> <PERSON> Anderson </PERSON>, an early mentor <PERSON> Hemingway </PERSON> thought was washed up. But when his own prose became well enough known to be parodied, <PERSON> Hemingway </PERSON> was hardly a sport. `` The parody is the last refuge of the frustrated writer,'' he said after E.B. White spoofed him with a piece called `` Across the Street and Into the Grill.'' `` The greater the work of literature, the easier the parody. The step up from writing parodies is writing on the wall above the urinal.'' All of the Ernie-wannabees in this collection are long on puns and short on commas. Among the titles: `` The Snooze of Kilimanjaro,'' `` In Another Contra,'' `` Hills Like White Heffalumps,'' `` The Old Man and the Seal,'' `` A Clean Well-Sighted Ace,'' `` A Lean Well-Tighted Space'' and `` A Clean Well-Lighted Race.'' When author <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Plimpton </PERSON>, who wrote the introduction to the book, was asked in a recent interview to select a favorite entry, he mentioned <PERSON> Daniel </PERSON> <PERSON> Hardy </PERSON>'s `` The Last Good Martini,'' which mangles more than a half-dozen Hemingway titles in its few short paragraphs: `` ` Do you want to order dinner?' said <PERSON> Nick </PERSON>. ` They still serve the big two-parted liver.''' And later: `` ` Do you remember <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Tell </PERSON>?' `` ` Yes,' said <PERSON> Francis </PERSON>. ` He was a swell bowler. For whom does Tell bowl now?''' <PERSON> Plimpton </PERSON> also mentioned the parody by <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> <PERSON> Ewing </PERSON>, `` The Question Hung in the Air'': `` He knew what they must do on this day. It was a month with no R. `` ` Come,' he said. ` It is the day of the running of the oysters.''' <PERSON> Plimpton </PERSON> explains in his introduction that the parody contest was dreamed up in 1978 by an advertising man named <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Keye </PERSON> for <ORGANIZATION> Harry </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bar </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Grill </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Century </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>, near <LOCATION> Beverly </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hills </LOCATION>. The American <PERSON> Harry </PERSON>'s was a replica of <PERSON> Harry </PERSON>'s Bar in <LOCATION> Florence </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Keye </PERSON> knew <PERSON> Hemingway </PERSON> never went to the <PERSON> Harry </PERSON>'s in <LOCATION> Florence </LOCATION> but was a devotee of the original <PERSON> Harry </PERSON>'s Bar in <LOCATION> Venice </LOCATION> and often featured it in his stories. His copy promoting the competition warned contestants that they would have to face `` The White Bull That Is Paper With No Words on It.'' All entries had to be limited to one type-written page and had to mention <PERSON> Harry </PERSON>'s Bar _ favorably. The winner was flown to <LOCATION> Florence </LOCATION> for dinner at the other <PERSON> Harry </PERSON>'s -LRB- lodging was not included -RRB-. The thousands of entries that poured in took the contest organizers by surprise, and the contest grew bigger every year, with celebrity judges such as <PERSON> Plimpton </PERSON>, novelist <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Wambaugh </PERSON>, science fiction writer <PERSON> Ray </PERSON> <PERSON> Bradbury </PERSON> and <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Hemingway </PERSON>, the author's son. Television crews gathered for the reading of the winning entry. <PERSON> Harry </PERSON>'s decided to end the competition after a decade because it was devoting more time to running it than its restaurants. <PERSON> Plimpton </PERSON> was asked what he looked for when he judged the entries. `` It has to be funny; it has to echo the style of author. I think the skill in copying the primary source would be utmust, then the imagination in developing the idea,'' he said by telephone from his office at the <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION> Review, of which he is editor. In later years the entries were pre-screened and the judges read only the best entries. `` The Best of Bad Hemingway'' is rounded out by spoofs of the author by well-known writers, including <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Scott </PERSON> <PERSON> Fitzgerald </PERSON>, <PERSON> Raymond </PERSON> <PERSON> Chandler </PERSON> and <PERSON> Plimpton </PERSON> himself, whose `` The Snows of Studiofiftyfour'' is a skillful mutation of <PERSON> Hemingway </PERSON>'s writing style and a Truman Capote-esque sensibility. <PERSON> Gary </PERSON> <PERSON> Piepenbrink </PERSON>, who edited the collection for <ORGANIZATION> Harcourt </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Brace </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Jovanovich </ORGANIZATION>, said he thought the book was fairly evenly divided between those who parodied <PERSON> Hemingway </PERSON> because they loved him and those who did it because they reviled him. <PERSON> Hemingway </PERSON>, who was awarded the Nobel Prize in literature in 1954, put a shotgun in his mouth and committed suicide in 1961. `` He's a literary force that everyone will have reckoned with somehow,'' said <PERSON> Piepenbrink </PERSON> in a telephone interview from his <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Diego </LOCATION> office. `` His stature is not to be challenged. His place is secure in modern literature. `` I do n't think the collection diminishes <PERSON> Hemingway </PERSON>,'' said <PERSON> Piepenbrink </PERSON>, who reveres the author. `` Some of the parodies are pretty cruel, but he can take it. A lesser writer could n't endure all these punches.''
