<FIRST>u a AM-TanningReport Bjt   07-20 0582</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Tanning Report, Bjt,0597</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tanning Linked to Host of Ills, New Report Says</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release at 5:30 p.m. EDT.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRENDA C. COLEMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Getting a tan in order to improve your looks raises your risk of skin cancer, wrinkles, eye damage and changes in the skin's immune system, a new report says. No health benefits are known from cosmetic tanning, except that `` tanned skin may have positive psychological value by creating an enhanced image of personal worth,'' said the report by the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>. The price can be high _ premature wrinkles, dryness and leathery skin; a heightened risk of skin cancer; damage to the eyes, and genetic changes that may compromise the skin's ability to fight invaders, the report said. `` Despite the hazards, many people can not be dissuaded from sunbathing or using artificial tanning devices,'' said the report, written by the Chicago-based <ORGANIZATION> AMA </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> on </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Scientific </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Affairs </ORGANIZATION> and published in Friday's Journal of the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>. The council recommended these guidelines for people who insist on tanning: _ Minimize exposure to ultraviolet radiation, the component of sunlight that causes tanning and burning, by staying out of the sun between 10 a.m and 2 p.m. and wearing a hat and protective clothing _ Beware of surfaces such as sand, snow, ice and concrete that reflect sunlight and can intensify the effects of the sun's rays by 10 percent to 50 percent _ Use a sunscreen, with a sun protection factor of at least 15 for skin that burns easily or tans only gradually, or higher at greater elevations or for other intensive exposures A person wearing a sunscreen with a protection factor of 15 would get the same amount of radiation exposure after 15 hours in the sun as he would in one hour if he were wearing no sunscreen. _ Keep babies out of the sun as much as possible and apply sunscreen to older youngsters who are to be outdoors for long periods _ Avoid tanning machines Exposure to their radiation may increase the risk of skin cancer, even though most modern machines use the `` safer'' form of ultraviolet light, called UV-A, rather than the more dangerous form, UV-B. People with extremely fair skin or severe reactions to sunlight should never use such booths, it said. If tanning equipment is used, people who tan moderately well should limit their exposures to 30 to 50 half-hour sessions per year or less, use a properly calibrated device with a timer, keep a record of exposures, wear protective goggles and make sure an attendant is nearby in case of an emergency, the report said. <PERSON> Becca </PERSON> <PERSON> Essman </PERSON>, executive director of the <ORGANIZATION> Suntanning </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Education </ORGANIZATION>, an industry group, reacted to the report by saying that tanning parlor operators have already responded to medical concerns about radiation. `` Tanning is a part of life that probably will never go away,'' she said in a telephone interview from the association's headquarters in <LOCATION> Frederick </LOCATION>, Md `` And we think indoor tanning facilities give people in general an opportunity to not burn, to avoid the overexposure.'' The association's 1,500 member facilities make up about one-quarter of the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> indoor tanning industry, Ms. <PERSON> Essman </PERSON> said. The group has drafted a code of ethics, developed a training program for parlor operators and promotes safety measures, she said. The Council on Scientific Affairs is a 15-member panel of doctors and other health specialists whose job is to compile the latest scientific information on topics of interest to the <ORGANIZATION> AMA </ORGANIZATION>.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890720-0166 </DOCNO>
