<FIRST>r a AM-PrisonSuicides     07-20 0609</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Prison Suicides,0627</SECOND>
<HEAD>Study: Suicide Second Leading Cause of Death Among Maryland Immates</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release at 5:30 p.m. EDT. Time set by source</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By IRIS CHANG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Suicide is the second-leading cause of death among <LOCATION> Maryland </LOCATION> prison inmates, according to federal researchers who suggest that convicts be examined for mental health problems before incarceration. Scientists from the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Rockville </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Md. </LOCATION>, found that mentally disturbed inmates were at the highest risk of committing suicide. White, male prisoners ages 15 to 34 had a greater risk of killing themselves than the general prison population, the researchers said in Friday's edition of the Journal of the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>. Prisoners in that age group also tended to kill themselves twice as often as people of the same age in <LOCATION> Maryland </LOCATION>'s general population, the researchers wrote. `` I think the situation of prisoners in <LOCATION> Maryland </LOCATION> is the same as that in many states,'' said <PERSON> Greg </PERSON> <PERSON> Shipley </PERSON>, a spokesman for the <LOCATION> Maryland </LOCATION> Division for Correction. `` They are faced with long prison sentences and a loss of hope that puts them in a very depressed state.'' Dr. <PERSON> Marcel </PERSON> <PERSON> Salive </PERSON> from the center and fellow scientists studied 206 deaths of male convicts in <LOCATION> Maryland </LOCATION> state prisons between 1979 to 1987 and found 37 were by suicide, second only to heart disease, which killed 48 inmates. The researchers noted that their results could not be applied to the nation's prison population, estimated at about 500,000, because suicide rates vary from prison to prison and the type of prison population. <PERSON> Salive </PERSON> said the absence of suicides among women inmates might be explained by the fact that women make up only 3.5 percent of the <LOCATION> Maryland </LOCATION> prison population. The researchers said psychotic or psychiatrically disturbed inmates are at the highest risk. The researchers suggested that convicts be evaluated for mental health problems before incarceration. In addition, `` We should train the staff to be more watchful of pre-suicidal behavior, such as people who get depressed or isolate themselves or have attempted it in the past,'' <PERSON> Salive </PERSON> said in a telephone interview. Of the prison suicides, 32 inmates hanged themselves, two slashed themselves, two overdosed on drugs and one fell to his death. White prisoners are twice as likely as blacks to commit suicide, the researchers said. They also confirmed previous studies that found inmates who serve a life sentence are more likely to commit suicide than other prisoners. Most studies of inmate suicides have been done in local jails, which house newly arrested people as well as convicts, the authors said. Prisons hold only those convicted and sentenced. Suicide is the leading cause of death in jails and is nine times more common in jail populations than in the general population, said <PERSON> Lindsay </PERSON> <PERSON> Hayes </PERSON>, an assistant director for the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> on </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institutes </ORGANIZATION> and Alternatives, a private, <LOCATION> Alexandria </LOCATION>, Va.-based group seeking better jail conditions. Suicides are less common in prisons than jails, <PERSON> Hayes </PERSON> said. Because only convicted felons are sent to prison, `` they've been through the crisis of jail and they are hardened, more experienced, and less fearful of the unknown,'' he said. <PERSON> Shipley </PERSON> said <LOCATION> Maryland </LOCATION> prison officials are trying to fight the suicide problem by installing in some cells collapsible clothing racks that will not support the weight of a body. In addition to removing pipes and clothes and towel racks or making them collapsible, corrections systems can help prevent inmate suicide by making tearable prison clothing, sheets and blankets that can not support a body, <PERSON> Hayes </PERSON> said. `` I do n't like gimmicks, though,'' <PERSON> Hayes </PERSON> said. `` I prefer counseling and increased monitoring. Suicides are best prevented by other human beings.''
</TEXT>
