<HEAD>House Bill Would Fund Birth Control/Fertility Research</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH MESCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Two congresswomen, saying they want to reclaim the `` middle ground'' in the abortion debate, Thursday introduced a bill to fund birth control and fertility research. Reps. <PERSON> Patricia </PERSON> <PERSON> Schroeder </PERSON>, D-Colo., and <PERSON> Olympia </PERSON> <PERSON> Snowe </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Maine </LOCATION>, said they are trying to broaden the abortion-rights base and seize control of the debate from abortion foes by attracting people from both sides of the issue as well as the undecided `` This is a comfort zone for people who do n't want to line up for or against abortion,'' <PERSON> Schroeder </PERSON> said. `` We're not going to sidetrack the debate on abortion,'' Snow said, but the congresswomen want to broaden it to address the conditions that lead to the need for abortion. The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>'s ruling earlier this month giving the states broader authority to limit women's rights to terminate their pregnancies has thrown the abortion debate into the state legislatures and governors' offices. Abortion-rights advocates and opponents have been bracing to steer the issue in their states. `` We've got to start reclaiming that middle ground'' to broaden the pro-choice base and reach out to people who may be uncomfortable in either camp on abortion but who support the need for better contraception, <PERSON> Schroeder </PERSON> said. With more than 3 million unintended pregnancies in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> each year, more attention has to be focused on preventing pregnancies, they said. Additionally, one out of six <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> couples is infertile or can not conceive within one year of deciding to have a child, they said. `` Clearly, we need to encourage birth control and fertility research,'' <PERSON> Schroeder </PERSON> said. Currently, the federal government is spending about $ 9 million annually on contraceptive research, she said. The bill would fund three birth control research centers and two fertility research centers that would do clinical research and development as well as develop education programs and distribute medical information. The centers would receive $ 20 million in fiscal year 1990, the same amount in 1991, $ 12 million in fiscal 1992, $ 12.5 million in fiscal 1993 and $ 13 million for fiscal 1994. The bill would also authorize a loan repayment program for graduate students or health professionals who conduct birth control or fertility research.
