<HEAD>Virginia Approves Private Toll Highway</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEAN McNAIR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NORFOLK, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The state's transportation board on Thursday approved plans for a private toll highway that the builder said would be the first in the country in 30 years. The <ORGANIZATION> Commonwealth </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> voted unanimously to approve the <ORGANIZATION> Toll </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Road </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION>'s proposal to build a 15-mile, $ 155 million extension of the <LOCATION> Dulles </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Toll </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Road </LOCATION> in traffic-clogged northern <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION>. The vote came after intense negotiations between the state and the corporation, which is headed by <PERSON> Ralph </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Stanley </PERSON>, former chief of the federal <ORGANIZATION> Urban </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mass </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION>. `` We've got a lot to be proud of,'' said <PERSON> Byron </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Waldman </PERSON>, northern <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION>'s representative on the board. `` We're willing to look at creative and new ways to meet our state's needs.'' The company still must seek approval from the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corporation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>, which will regulate the amount of tolls. The company has said tolls would start at $ 1.50. <PERSON> Stanley </PERSON> said he hopes the <ORGANIZATION> SCC </ORGANIZATION> will act as soon as possible and construction can begin by December. He said the highway should be finished by the end of 1991, about 15 months ahead of when the state could complete the project. `` We could n't be more pleased, particularly with a unanimous vote,'' <PERSON> Stanley </PERSON> said. `` I do n't minimize the historic nature of it,'' he said. `` I think it's a whole new era of funding for not just highway projects but infrastructure through the state.'' <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Woodwell </PERSON>, a representative of the <ORGANIZATION> Toll </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Road </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, said land for the project is largely being donated by developers and other landowners on the assumption the road will increase the value of land near it. The company is still negotiating with some small individual owners, and may have to buy some parcels. The land donations are one of the main reasons the company will be able to build the road so much faster than the state, <PERSON> Woodwell </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Stanley </PERSON> said the road would be the first private toll highway built in the country in more than 30 years. `` There are, I would say, at least 30 states I know who are going to be very interested in what happened here today,'' he said. The <ORGANIZATION> Virginia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assembly </ORGANIZATION> passed legislation in 1988 allowing private companies to fund and build roads in the state. <PERSON> Stanley </PERSON> said he could foresee more private funding of roads, bridges and wastewater treatment plants, particularly in small communities. State transportation officials acknowledged that the private company could build the road faster and at a lower initial cost, but they said it would cost far more in the long run because the company must pay higher interest rates than the state. That would increase tolls, they said. <PERSON> Ray </PERSON> <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Pethtel </PERSON>, the board's commissioner, said the public's overwhelming support for the private road outweighed such concerns
</TEXT>
