 An unexpected visit by a group of Soviet students and professors sent <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Houston </ORGANIZATION> officials scrambling to line up social and educational events. `` Yes, we are embarrassed. We certainly do n't make a habit of treating international visitors this way,'' said <PERSON> Willie </PERSON> <PERSON> Munson </PERSON>, the university's student life director. The six members of the Soviet group from <ORGANIZATION> Leningrad </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> arrived Tuesday at <LOCATION> Houston </LOCATION>'s Intercontinental Airport eager to start their `` exchange program.'' But nobody expected them. After waiting a few hours at the airport, the group was picked up by officials from the university's housing department. `` We are so pleased to have somebody meet us and feed us. The people are very pleasant,'' said <PERSON> Elena </PERSON> <PERSON> Krasnova </PERSON>, 31, a teacher at the <LOCATION> Leningrad </LOCATION> university. <PERSON> Ali </PERSON> <PERSON> Annan </PERSON>, a former students' association president in <LOCATION> Houston </LOCATION>, had corresponded with <LOCATION> Leningrad </LOCATION> administrators for two years. In May, he wrote a letter suggesting that the summer would be an ideal time to visit. The Soviets received that letter last week, obtained their visas and caught the first available plane. They also say they mailed a letter to <PERSON> Annan </PERSON> telling them about their trip, but he has yet to receive it. `` I was shocked,'' said <PERSON> Annan </PERSON>, a May graduate. `` The worst few moments of my life were then. I ... asked myself if I could be dreaming.'' University officials said they are making the best of the situation. `` They're a very nice group of people, very bright,'' interim school President <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Magner </PERSON> said. `` It's their first trip outside of <LOCATION> Russia </LOCATION>. We intend to give them a very pleasant and productive visit.'' The impromptu plans for the Soviets include trips to the Johnson Space Center, Astroworld and the port city of <LOCATION> Galveston </LOCATION>. The group is scheduled to go sailing and spend time on a ranch, as well as visit university laboratories and classes.
