No pickup</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMMED SALAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Christians and Syrians fought artillery battles Thursday that rained 30 shells a minute on the city and sent thousands of residents fleeing in panic. Police said 13 people were killed and 88 wounded. `` Someone call the fire brigade! We want an ambulance too!'' a woman screamed from the 11-story <PERSON> Kaaki </PERSON> building in west <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION>, whose top three floors were burning. `` Telephone lines are down!'' a man answered from a nearby building. `` Have faith in God! We're coming to help you!'' Two 107mm rockets hit <PERSON> Fawzi </PERSON> <PERSON> Rida </PERSON>'s apartment on the 10th floor before dawn. `` I stretched a hand to open the door, but there was no door,'' he said. `` We have nothing left but the night clothes we are wearing.'' Police said 433 people have been killed and 1,780 wounded in the 18 weeks of artillery warfare between Gen. <PERSON> Michel </PERSON> <PERSON> Aoun </PERSON>'s <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION> army units and an alliance of Syrian soldiers and Moslem militias. Thursday's shelling was some of the heaviest in the long battle. Tongues of flame shot into the sky over <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION>. Blasted buildings burned out of control. A police spokesman said damage in Moslem west <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION> was much worse than in the Christian eastern sector. He reported a heavy flow of civilians from both sides of the city toward safer areas in <LOCATION> south </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> Bekaa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> valley </LOCATION> in the east and the mountains northeast of <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION>. `` Thousands of cars packed with families headed south from west <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION>,'' the spokesman said. The evacuees used a lull in shelling at midday Thursday to leave the city, `` carrying whatever personal effects and household items they could save,'' he said. <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> photo editor <PERSON> Zouheir </PERSON> <PERSON> Saade </PERSON> said shells fell near his fifth-floor apartment in west <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION>'s seaside <LOCATION> Raouche </LOCATION> district. `` Our building does n't have a bomb shelter,'' he said. `` The only precautionary measure I could take was to distribute my four sons each in a different room. I thought that was the only possible way to keep some of them alive in case the apartment was hit.'' Firefighters were hampered because a power blackout caused a water shortage. A source at the fire department said two fire engines used sea water to extinguish some fires overnight. The police spokesman said several Syrian soldiers were killed when <PERSON> Aoun </PERSON>'s artillery pounded their bases and artillery emplacements in west <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION>, but police said they had no precise information because the Syrians do not report their losses to <LOCATION> Lebanese </LOCATION> authorities. An estimated 40,000 Syrian soldiers are in <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION> under an <ORGANIZATION> Arab </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> League </ORGANIZATION> peacekeeping mandate granted in 1976, a year after <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>'s sectarian civil war began <PERSON> Aoun </PERSON> calls them an army of occupation and has vowed to drive them out. The police spokesman said <PERSON> Samir </PERSON> <PERSON> Geagea </PERSON>'s right-wing Lebanese Forces, the main Christian militia, joined <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION> army forces in shelling west <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION>. `` <PERSON> Aoun </PERSON>'s gunners targeted mainly Syrian positions,'' he said. `` <PERSON> Geagea </PERSON>'s men rocketed residential areas in west <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION>.'' Acting Prime Minister <PERSON> Salim </PERSON> <PERSON> Hoss </PERSON>, who heads a Moslem government vying for power with the <PERSON> Aoun </PERSON>'s <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cabinet </ORGANIZATION>, pleaded with leaders of <LOCATION> Saudi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arabia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Morocco </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Algeria </LOCATION> to speed up Arab League efforts for a cease-fire. A spokesman for <PERSON> Aoun </PERSON>'s command claimed the Syrians started the battle by shelling the Christian-held coast north of <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION> to prevent three ships loaded with food from landing. The Syrians bombard the coast regularly to keep supply ships away from Christian ports.
