<FIRST>r w AM-Wolves     07-20 0558</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Wolves,540</SECOND>
<HEAD>Parks Chief Opposes Wolf Bill</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DIANE DUSTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The director of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Park </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> said Thursday he opposes legislation being considered by the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> that would speed the return of wolves to the <LOCATION> Yellowstone </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Park </LOCATION> area. <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Ridenour </PERSON>, newly appointed parks director, called a bill introduced by Rep. <PERSON> Wayne </PERSON> <PERSON> Owens </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Utah </LOCATION>, `` clearly premature.'' Sponsors believe the administration is moving too slowly to restore the only indigenous species still missing from the <LOCATION> Yellowstone </LOCATION> area. But the measure has other members growling. Rep. <PERSON> Ron </PERSON> <PERSON> Marlenee </PERSON>, R-Mont., called the bill `` blatantly anti-sportsman'' because wolves kill elk sought by hunters `` This is a meddlesome bill ... an effort to extend the borders of <ORGANIZATION> Yellowstone </ORGANIZATION>,'' Rep. <PERSON> Don </PERSON> <PERSON> Young </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Alaska </LOCATION>, told fellow members of the national parks subcommittee of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Interior </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>. Young called wolf proponents `` romantic'' and said they should see the wolf for what it is, `` without any doubt, second to man in his ability as a predator against the clove-footed animal.'' Rep. <PERSON> Larry </PERSON> <PERSON> Craig </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Idaho </LOCATION>, said livestock owners will kill the wolves in defense of their animals `` and I would support that.'' <PERSON> Ridenour </PERSON> said the park service goal is to return the area to its natural state as far as possible. He said the <ORGANIZATION> Interior </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>, of which the park service is a part, is conducting studies to determine: _ If the wolf population can be controlled once it is returned _ The effects of the wolves on prey within the park and big game hunting outside it _ The effect on grizzly bears He said the studies would probably be finished by early in the next fiscal year, which begins Oct. 1, and no environmental impact statement should be prepared before then. <PERSON> Owens </PERSON>' bill calls for an environmental impact statement and action by the <ORGANIZATION> interior </ORGANIZATION> secretary after the statement is complete. <PERSON> Ridenour </PERSON> said the wording of the bill would make it difficult for the secretary to make any decision other than returning the wolves to the park. <PERSON> Ridenour </PERSON> urged the subcommittee chairman, Rep. <PERSON> Bruce </PERSON> <PERSON> Vento </PERSON>, D-Minn., to `` let the scientists do their studies; let the wildlife advocates, ranchers, park visitors, state and local officials, and members of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> comment on the findings; and then let us make a policy which is driven by our stewardship responsibility. <PERSON> Vento </PERSON> asked, `` Can you give me assurances that there will be no attempt to short circuit'' the process? He said the administration already has delayed planned re-introduction of wolves by two years. <PERSON> Ridenour </PERSON> said he was trying to avoid a `` headlong rush'' and said he had an open mind on the subject. Dr. <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Mech </PERSON>, a world-renowned wolf expert with the Fish and <ORGANIZATION> Wildlife </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>, told the subcommittee each wolf eats the equivalent of three adult elk cows a year, which should not endanger the population of about 35,000 elk in the <LOCATION> Yellowstone </LOCATION> area. <PERSON> Mech </PERSON> said the elk that died last year of bad weather would have been the likely prey of wolves. If 10 breeding pairs of wolves were established in <LOCATION> Yellowstone </LOCATION>, about 500 could be living there by the turn of the century. He said enough prey, including animals other than elk, exists in the region to support the wolves without disrupting the ecosystem. While admitting that wolves sometimes venture out of the forest to prey on domestic livestock, he said it was unusual.
