<HEAD>Aspin Wants ``Cold Turkey'' Freeze on Funds for Stealth</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDs:Updates with 12 new grafs to add Bush lobbying effort</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSANNE M. SCHAFER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Military Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Armed </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Les </PERSON> <PERSON> Aspin </PERSON>, said Thursday he wants a `` cold turkey'' freeze on funds for the stealth bomber, and President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> stepped up his lobbying effort for the radar-evading plane and other defense systems. <PERSON> Aspin </PERSON>, D-Wis., said <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> needs more information on the costly stealth bomber, as the B-2 plane is known `` The problem this year is ... we do n't really know what we got,'' he told reporters. <PERSON> Aspin </PERSON> said he wants to give opponents of the plane, at $ 530 million a copy the most expensive aircraft ever produced, a chance to kill the program. But if <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> does n't want to do that, it needs more information about the program before moving forward, he added. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> on Thursday called <PERSON> Aspin </PERSON> and other members of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Armed </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> and Appropriations committees to the White House. He pressed them to back his budget proposals for the B-2, as well as the strategic defense initiative, the MX missile and the Midgetman missile. The <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> are scheduled to vote next week on those programs and a package of <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> cuts the administration proposed to meet the $ 10 billion reduction agreed on by <ORGANIZATION> Congressional </ORGANIZATION> negotiators and the White House for the 1990 defense authorization bills. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> told the group he is fully committed to that package and the weapons systems as essential to the nation's deterrent capability and to the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> strategy at the arms reduction talks ongoing in <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION>, according to Press Secretary <PERSON> Marlin </PERSON> <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON>. Given the amount of congressional hesitation, especially regarding the administration's insistence on not cutting the B-2 program, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> wanted to re-emphasize his policy reasons for those programs, <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> was to host another meeting Friday to lobby those committee members who could not make the Thursday session. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> is emphatic that the plane `` represents the future of bomber aviation,'' and is needed despite its expense, the spokesman said. <PERSON> Aspin </PERSON> told reporters after the meeting that he could not predict which way <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> would go on the <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> spending bill next week. At the <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION>, a spokesman for <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> Dick </PERSON> <PERSON> Cheney </PERSON> said <PERSON> Aspin </PERSON>'s B-2 plan would not meet with his approval. `` Any delay in the program will only make it more expensive,'' said <PERSON> Pete </PERSON> <PERSON> Williams </PERSON>. `` He'd be opposed to such a scenario.'' <PERSON> Cheney </PERSON> reiterated the importance of the B-2 bomber in a meeting with <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> Republicans, who are divided on the issue. Supporters of the plane were cheered when it made its first test flight Monday. The <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> hopes to buy 132 planes at a cost of about $ 70 billion. In fiscal 1990, the <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> has proposed spending $ 4.7 billion for the B-2, but last month the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> armed services panel cut $ 800 million from the budget. Money for the plane is expected to be the most controversial item next week when the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> consider the Pentagon budget bill. Reps. <PERSON> Ron </PERSON> <PERSON> Dellums </PERSON>, D-Calif., <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Kasich </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Ohio </LOCATION>, and <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Rowland </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Conn </LOCATION>., have proposed stopping production after the 13 planes now in the pipeline are If their effort fails, <PERSON> Aspin </PERSON> said, he intends to propose funding production of only two bombers in 1990 and 1991, when the administration wants eight bombers. His amendment would meet the full request for research and development work over that period. `` I say, give the opponents of the B-2 an up-or-down vote. If the <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> is willing to step up to this issue this year, I say let's do it,'' <PERSON> Aspin </PERSON> said. He called his amendment `` a cold turkey fence of the procurement money until <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> acts again.'' <PERSON> Aspin </PERSON> said his plan `` shuts down the program, but it gives the administration a chance to come up with another program that's politically more acceptable _ financially. He said he could not predict how his colleagues will vote on the issue because there has never been a public debate on the once-secret program. <PERSON> Aspin </PERSON> added he wants the <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> to `` come up with a cheaper program'' by seeking fewer planes. `` I do n't know anybody who thinks they're going to get 132 planes,'' <PERSON> Aspin </PERSON> said.
