<HEAD>Key Burmese Opposition Leader Emerged Less Than a Year Ago</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Burma</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BRUNNSTROM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Aung </PERSON> <PERSON> San </PERSON> <PERSON> Suu </PERSON> <PERSON> Kyi </PERSON>, who was placed under house arrest by Burmese military authorities Thursday, appeared on the political stage less than a year ago to become <LOCATION> Burma </LOCATION>'s leading voice for democracy. The daughter of <LOCATION> Burma </LOCATION>'s assassinated independence hero, <PERSON> Aung </PERSON> <PERSON> San </PERSON>, she returned to <LOCATION> Rangoon </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Burma </LOCATION>'s capital, from her home in <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> in April 1988 to care for her ailing mother. She found herself in the midst of an unprecedented nationwide campaign to end authoritarianism. She sided with student protesters and stayed with them after the September military coup in which troops of Army Commander Gen. Saw <PERSON> Maung </PERSON> crushed dissent by killing hundreds of people. Her campaign rallies commonly draw thousands of people, and Western diplomats say authorities are concerned she could win a general election scheduled for early next year. The slight frame of Ms. <PERSON> Suu </PERSON> <PERSON> Kyi </PERSON>, 44, belies a steely political will that brushes off military intimidation and veiled threats against her life. She had no political experience before last year. Many Burmese attribute her widespread support to her unprecedented denunciation of the military and strongman <PERSON> Ne </PERSON> <PERSON> Win </PERSON>, whom she charges is still pulling the strings although he officially retired last year after 26 years of autocratic rule. Her first appearance on the Burmese political scene was on Aug. 15 last year, when she attempted to mediate between the protesting students and the army by writing an open letter to then President <PERSON> Maung </PERSON> <PERSON> Maung </PERSON>. But when she spoke outside <LOCATION> Rangoon </LOCATION>'s glittering Shwedagon Pagoda on Aug. 26, the height of the pro-democracy movement, she drew what may have been the largest crowd ever seen in <LOCATION> Rangoon </LOCATION>. An estimated 1 million people packed the streets to hear her call for democracy and an end to one-party rule. Demonstrators camped in the streets for days to see her. After brutal clampdowns on dissent that killed thousands, the army crushed open street protest after Sept 18. Ms. <PERSON> Suu </PERSON> <PERSON> Kyi </PERSON> subsequenty emerged as the most prominent of the Burmese opposition leaders. Her popularity has increased steadily and she has drawn large crowds during political campaign tours throughout the country this year. In December, crowds filled the streets of <LOCATION> Rangoon </LOCATION> for the funeral of her mother, <PERSON> Kyin </PERSON> <PERSON> Gyi </PERSON>, who was <LOCATION> Burma </LOCATION>'s first female ambassador. Her party, the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> League </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democracy </ORGANIZATION>, is the largest political opposition group and claims over 700,000 members in <LOCATION> Rangoon </LOCATION> alone. Over the past month she has openly defied martial law regulations, which forbid open air political rallies and gatherings of more than five persons. Her speeches in <LOCATION> Rangoon </LOCATION> have drawn crowds of up to 15,000 despite the persistent presence of armed troops. <PERSON> Suu </PERSON> <PERSON> Kyi </PERSON> was born in <LOCATION> Rangoon </LOCATION> in 1945 and married British academic <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Aris </PERSON> in 1972. Her two sons traveled recently to <LOCATION> Rangoon </LOCATION>. She went to school in <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> where her mother was <LOCATION> Burma </LOCATION>'s first female ambassador. She won a scholarship to <LOCATION> Oxford </LOCATION> in 1967 and obtained an honors degree in politics, philosophy and economics. She later worked at the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> and in the early 1980s researched the life of her father and the origins of <LOCATION> Burmese </LOCATION> nationalism at <ORGANIZATION> Kyodo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>. She has written two books, a guide to <LOCATION> Burma </LOCATION> for children and a short biography of her father.
