ATION>'s position regarding certain classified information which may substantially complicate the trial,'' <PERSON> Walsh </PERSON>'s office said in a court filing earlier this week which provided the first indication that the <PERSON> Fernandez </PERSON> case might be in trouble In that filing, <PERSON> Walsh </PERSON> suggested that instead of the trial starting Monday as scheduled, a hearing be held that day on matters concerning classified information. On hursday, <PERSON> Runkel </PERSON> said he did not know whether exercising any of the options the department has would put <PERSON> Walsh </PERSON> in the position of having to seek dismissal of the charges against <PERSON> Fernandez </PERSON>. If classified information is too sensitive to declassify but is needed for a criminal trial, the <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> may move that a summary of the secret information be presented in court instead. If the court denies the motijon, the attorney general may file an affidavit objecting to disclosure of the classified information. The court must then order that the information not be disclosed, a step which can lead to dismissal of the criminal case. <PERSON> Fernandez </PERSON> was questioned by the <ORGANIZATION> Tower </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> CIA </ORGANIZATION> inspector general's office in 1987, which led to charges against him. The indictment says that he falsely told the <ORGANIZATION> CIA </ORGANIZATION> inspector general's office that a secret airstrip construction project that was to be part of the Contra supply network was initiated by the Costa Rican government. In congressional tetsimony which can not be used against him at his trial, <PERSON> Fernandez </PERSON> admitted that <PERSON> North </PERSON> and the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> government initiated the project. <PERSON> Fernandez </PERSON> falsely told the <ORGANIZATION> Tower </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> that he did not know for a fact that <PERSON> North </PERSON> was assisting the Contra resupply operation, according to the indictment. <PERSON> Fernandez </PERSON> is accused in a bill of particulars filed by prosecutors of making 19 additional statements that were so misleading that they obstructed the <ORGANIZATION> Tower </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> CIA </ORGANIZATION> inspector general office's inquiries into the Iran-Contra scandal.
