<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The congressman who introduced <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Lucas </PERSON> at a <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> hearing on <PERSON> Lucas </PERSON>' nomination to be the government's chief civil rights enforcer abruptly took back his support Thursday and the chairman of the committee in charge said he might vote against <PERSON> Lucas </PERSON> Rep. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Conyers </PERSON>, D-Mich., returning to the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Judiciary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> hearing room where he had strongly urged <PERSON> Lucas </PERSON>' confirmation a day earlier, said, `` It is with a slightly heavy heart I come to withdraw my endorsement of <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Lucas </PERSON> <PERSON> Conyers </PERSON> said he made the decision after being `` frankly astounded'' when <PERSON> Lucas </PERSON> told the panel that a series of recent <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> decisions on civil rights did not undermine enforcement of anti-discrimination laws. `` We are in a crisis in the civil rights movement,'' said <PERSON> Conyers </PERSON>, who, like <PERSON> Lucas </PERSON>, is black. `` If you ca n't figure out these cases are seriously cutting back very modest progress that we made, then there is no point waiting for you to become the assistant attorney general of the civil rights division for me to argue it with you then,'' <PERSON> Conyers </PERSON> said. He stopped short of urging the panel to reject the nomination, suggesting the committee should give <PERSON> Lucas </PERSON> the benefit of the doubt and perhaps a chance for on-the-job training. The committee chairman, Sen. <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Biden </PERSON>, D-Del., said at the hearing, `` I was inclined to vote for him until yesterday. But now, `` I'm inclined to vote against him.'' `` My doubt about this man does n't relate to his lack of experience,'' <PE