<FIRST>r i AM-UN-Senegal-Mauritania     07-20 0344</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-UN-Senegal-Mauritania,0358</SECOND>
<HEAD>Senegal Says Mauritania Expelled 26,000 Blacks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Senegal </LOCATION> Thursday accused <LOCATION> Mauritania </LOCATION> of deporting 26,000 of its black nationals following racial violence that left between 250 and 400 dead in the two countries. `` It is to be feared that not a single black Mauritanian will be unaffected by the measures,'' <LOCATION> Senegal </LOCATION>'s acting foreign minister said in letter to the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> security council. <PERSON> Kane </PERSON> <PERSON> Kharass </PERSON>, from <LOCATION> Mauritania </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> mission said, `` There is no such policy in my country.'' Tensions between the black Senegalese and the fairer-skinned, <PERSON> Arab </PERSON> and Berber Mauritanians have long historical and racial roots, but a confrontation in April and May began as a minor border incident. Tens of thousands of Mauritanians and Senegalese were repatriated in a U.N.-sponsored airlift. To reduce tensions, both nations sent home workers from the other country after the violent clashes, which left between 250 and 400 people dead, <PERSON> Kharass </PERSON> said. He denied <LOCATION> Mauritania </LOCATION> was expelling any of its own citizens. But Medoune Fall, <LOCATION> Senegal </LOCATION>'s acting foreign minister, said, `` Beginning in mid-May, the Mauritanian government took steps to expel its black nationals belonging to ethnic groups also found in <LOCATION> Senegal </LOCATION>. `` In just a few weeks, the operation has affected 26,000 individuals, who have been driven from their own country solely by reason of their ethnic origin,'' Fall said. Those deported to <LOCATION> Senegal </LOCATION> were arriving completely stripped of property, he said. Between July 16 and 18 alone, 2,000 blacks were deported, <PERSON> Fall </PERSON> said. Fall said the deportations would increase tensions between the two countries. <LOCATION> Mauritania </LOCATION> was the last nation in the world to officially abolish slavery, in 1980. Most slaves were black, while the traders and owners were usually Arabs or Berbers. Hard economic times have worsened ethnic tensions between the two nations as hundreds of thousands of people have crossed the border seeking work in the other country. <LOCATION> Senegal </LOCATION> estimates that up to 50,000 Senegalese, mainly seasonal workers, lived in <LOCATION> Mauritania </LOCATION> before the latest clashes broke out. About 500,000 Mauritanians, most of them tradesmen, live in <LOCATION> Senegal </LOCATION>.
