<HEAD>Senate Committee Deadlocked On Drought Relief</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PHILIP BRASHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> failed to reach agreement Thursday on a <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> plan to provide $ 1 billion in relief for farmers who are losing crops to this summer's drought and flooding. <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Patrick </PERSON> <PERSON> Leahy </PERSON>, D-Vt., postponed a vote on the package until next week after <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> senators argued the measure covers too many crops and costs too much <PERSON> Leahy </PERSON> said he did not want to risk a vote on the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> floor without bipartisan support. `` Drought and disaster is n't a partisan issue and relief should n't be either,'' <PERSON> Leahy </PERSON> said. The <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration has threatened to veto a drought-relief bill passed by the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> last month that is estimated to cost $ 1.3 billion and cover more than 500 crops, from corn to cherries. Senate Democrats, agreeing the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> measure is too expensive, proposed to scale it back by $ 300 million by reducing the payments to farmers and tightening qualifications for the program. The administration wants to limit the bill to $ 870 million, but Democrats say the government can afford an additional $ 200 million, if some of the payments to farmers come from this year's budget instead of next year's. The deep division within the committee became evident earlier in the day when the panel voted 10-9 along party lines to kill an $ 800 million <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> proposal that would have targeted a greater share of the drought assistance to crops that are in the government's price support program _ wheat, corn, rice and cotton. `` Where money is limited we must set priorities,'' said <LOCATION> Indiana </LOCATION> Sen. <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Lugar </PERSON>, the committee's ranking Republican. Sen. <PERSON> Thad </PERSON> <PERSON> Cochran </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> Republican whose state's rice and cotton crops have been devastated by flooding, said the Democratic plan would spread the aid so thin `` there's going to be precious little benefit to anybody.'' Senate Republican Leader <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Dole </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Kansas </LOCATION>, where the winter wheat crop was cut back sharply by drought, said the <ORGANIZATION> GOP </ORGANIZATION> plan would mean an extra 15 cents a bushel for wheat and an additional 21 cents a bushel for corn. <PERSON> Dole </PERSON> argues that winter-wheat farmers should get first crack at drought relief since much of the savings in the farm program that is being used to pay for drought relief is the result of a smaller wheat crop. `` Where does the money come from? It comes from program crops,'' <PERSON> Dole </PERSON> said. `` If we're going to cover non-program crops, we should find the money elsewhere.'' The Republican plan would have provided relief to wheat, corn, rice and cotton on the same basis as the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> bill and the 1988 drought legislation; other crops could have received assistance if the money was available in the federal budget. <PERSON> Dole </PERSON> acknowledged for the first time today that losses have occurred in at least one other crop _ namely spring wheat in <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Dakota </LOCATION>, where drought-related crop losses already are estimated at $ 660 million. Sen. <PERSON> Kent </PERSON> <PERSON> Conrad </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-N.D. </LOCATION>, who is concerned about getting relief for sunflowers and other non-program crops in his state, said the <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> proposal was modest and more fair. `` Nobody's going to get a windfall out of this,'' he said. `` An act of God,'' said Sen. <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Pryor </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Ark </LOCATION>., `` does n't distinguish between program and non-program crops
