<HEAD>Senate Panel Approves Assault Weapons Bill</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Judiciary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, going against heavy pressure from gun owners' organizations, Thursday narrowly approved a three-year ban on sales of nine military-style assault weapons. `` It's designed to deny drug dealers the use of these types of weapons,'' said Sen. <PERSON> Dennis </PERSON> <PERSON> DeConcini </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Ariz </LOCATION>., following 7-6 approval at a hectic session ending with a gun lobbyist complaining about a senator's decision not to vote The measure would ban nine varieties of semiautomatic assault weapons, five already covered by the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration's import ban and four others produced domestically. The bill also would provide for up to 10 years of additional prison time for those convicted of crimes involving firearms. The measure would automatically go off the books in three years under a `` sunset'' provision. Critics of the measure called it too restrictive, although it was modest in comparison with a flurry of bills that went into the hopper in February following a mass slaying in a <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> schoolyard with a semi-automatic assault rifle. `` I think it does a great deal of damage to the right of the people to keep and bear arms,'' Sen. <PERSON> Orrin </PERSON> <PERSON> Hatch </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Utah </LOCATION>, told the committee. Sen. <PERSON> Howard </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Metzenbaum </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Ohio </LOCATION>, said the bill headed in the right direction but should be stronger in banning assault weapons. `` Frankly it is a letdown to the law enforcement groups in <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>,'' <PERSON> Metzenbaum </PERSON> said. At the start of the meeting, Sen. <PERSON> Arlen </PERSON> <PERSON> Specter </PERSON>, R-Pa., told the committee he would not be able to attend because he was tied down with evidence hearings in the impeachment trial of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Alcee </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Hastings </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION>, accused of plotting to obtain a $ 150,000 bribe He then left. When it came time to vote an hour later, however, there was a question as to whether the committee should wait for Specter. The Hastings hearing was taking place in a room about a three-minute walk away. `` The problem is he's on the <PERSON> Hastings </PERSON> matter and I know he takes that very, very seriously,'' <PERSON> Hatch </PERSON> said. Because of the razor-thin margin, senators held open the roll call for 10 minutes or more in case <PERSON> Specter </PERSON> might want to vote. A minute after the vote was announced, the <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION> senator arrived but told <ORGANIZATION> Judiciary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Biden </PERSON>, D-Del., he would need time to study any changes made in the legislation <PERSON> Biden </PERSON> banged the gavel and adjourned the meeting. The chairman and <PERSON> Specter </PERSON> were both quickly out the door, but Sen. <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Grassley </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Iowa </LOCATION>, told reporters that `` as a matter of courtesy they could have given him five or six minutes to study the bill.'' <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rifle </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> lobbyist <PERSON> Wayne </PERSON> <PERSON> LaPierre </PERSON>, however, told reporters he had been with <PERSON> Specter </PERSON> `` at the <PERSON> Hastings </PERSON> hearing, in the back of the room,'' urging him to come to the <ORGANIZATION> Judiciary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> meeting to vote against <PERSON> DeConcini </PERSON>'s bill. `` Basically,'' <PERSON> LaPierre </PERSON> said, `` Specter just decided to be absent.'' The lobbyist said he still expected the <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION> senator to be on the side of gunowner groups when the measure comes to the floor. Earlier, Sen. <PERSON> Strom </PERSON> <PERSON> Thurmond </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-S.C. </LOCATION>, and Republican followers sought to substitute the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration's omnibus crime control bill for the gun measure, but that effort failed 8-5. <PERSON> Thurmond </PERSON> warned that strong anticrime measures are needed and cited the case of a <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION> man convicted of murder a decade ago. `` He has n't been electrocuted yet,'' <PERSON> Thurmond </PERSON> said. `` People are are losing respect for criminal justice procedures.'' <PERSON> Biden </PERSON> said crime-control measures are needed but not before President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> implements broad powers granted him in last year's drug bill He said the administration has been authorized to hire 225 new <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> agents but has not done so. `` I do n't doubt the president's sincerity,'' <PERSON> Biden </PERSON> said. `` I just do n't think he's tough enough.''
