<HEAD>Senate Panel Votes For $225 Million</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> Appropriations subcommittee voted Thursday to spend $ 225 million to begin construction of the `` super collider'' particle accelerator. The chairman called the collider project the most important scientific effort in the nation. But the chairman, Sen. <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON> <PERSON> Johnston </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-La </LOCATION>., said an amendment may be introduced in the full <ORGANIZATION> Appropriations </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> that would hold up the $ 4.4 billion project until foreign governments agree to participate <PERSON> Johnston </PERSON>, head of the <ORGANIZATION> Appropriations </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>'s energy and water development subcommittee and also of the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Natural </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Resources </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, said he would oppose such a condition. `` There's sentiment in our committee to adopt report language which will, in effect, say do n't give away the great technological contracts to the Japanese or to any other participant,'' <PERSON> Johnston </PERSON> said. Committee reports are not binding, but the reports are very influential in guiding administration decisions. Explaining his support of the collider, planned for a site 30 miles south of <LOCATION> Dallas </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Johnston </PERSON> said, `` It unlocks the secret of what we're made of, what the universe is made of, what energy and matter and all of the basic stuff of the universe is made of and it's exciting.'' He said he has `` limited enthusiasm'' for enlisting other countries to share the cost: `` I think this research is so important we ought to do it in this country if we can and not farm it out to have somebody else build the most important technological parts of it.'' While President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> had sought $ 250 million for the fiscal year beginning Oct. 1, <PERSON> Johnston </PERSON> said budget constraints forced him to settle on $ 225 million. The House has voted $ 200 million, and if the project survives, the two Houses will have to agree on an amount.
