<SECOND>AM-Anarchy Convention,0511</SECOND>
<HEAD>Orderly Start, But `Mainstream Media' Banned</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Yng in 7th graf is cq</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The fourth annual anarchists' convention got off to an orderly start Thursday as participants signed up for workshops including `` Fighting Against the War on Drugs'' and `` Slaying Christ.'' More than 1,000 people are attending the six-day event. `` My vision is to live where we can remove ourselves more from the world and be self-sufficient,'' said <PERSON> Karry </PERSON> <PERSON> Koon </PERSON>, a nursery school teacher from <LOCATION> McVeytown </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Pa. </LOCATION> `` Very few of the people I work with know that I'm an anarchist,'' she added. Attendees were greeted by a sign reading `` Bring your own bowl, spoon, cup.'' They included poets, musicians, teachers, drifters, clerks, parents, scholars and children. When asked who organized the meeting, the answer _ over and over again _ was, `` No one and everyone.'' `` Everything is consensus,'' said <PERSON> Yng </PERSON> <PERSON> Tom </PERSON>, a musician who works at the Bound Together anarchist bookstore in <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> Haight-Ashbury </LOCATION> neighborhood Anarchists generally believe that every form of regulation or government is immoral and restraint of one person by another is evil. Despite that tenet, the `` mainstream media'' were banned by the anarchists, who discussed the issue during a general assembly before the convention got under way. `` We decided you guys just are n't going to give us a fair shake, so we're not going to let any of you in,'' said one young woman, who appeared to be guarding the entrance to the auditorium where the conference was held. She and a companion refused to identify themselves and were unswayed by arguments that a selective-media policy contradicts the principles of anarchy. Other contradictions to a classical definition of anarchy were admitted without embarrassment. <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Somers </PERSON>, a clarinet player in a symphony, brought a 10-year-old boy to the event. `` We're definitely against a lot of authoritarian trips,'' said <PERSON> Somers </PERSON>, adding as he pointed at the child, `` He does n't go to school ... And no sugar.'' As for the sugar mandate, <PERSON> Somers </PERSON> added he `` would n't impose authority on anyone _ except for kids.'' For those not steeped in this particular brand of anarchy, there was a `` Anarchy 101'' workshop, one of 16 seminars on Thursday. A written guide described it this way, with anarchist punctuation: `` just what is this anarchy stuff anyway? are you the guys with black pointy hats who shoot people and blow things up? if we had anarchy who would pick up the garbage?'' A workshop on the animal liberation movement read: `` woof. woof. woof. baaaaa. neigh chirp. chirp. squeek squeek. meow. mooo. discussions on veganism, vivisection, fur and leather, ecological connections and more.'' Among seminars on spirituality was `` Slaying Christ,'' which discussed methods of ridding the world of so-called patriarchal religions. Anarchist ideals were summed up by a poem posted on the wall by activist <PERSON> Dave </PERSON> <PERSON> Whitaker </PERSON>: `` Take what you need, Give what you can, When you can, However you can, In other words, Lend a hand.''
