<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 A bird in the engine of a <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> jet forced the pilot to make an unscheduled landing in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> on Thursday, and a <ORGANIZATION> Northwest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> plane developed engine trouble and had to return to <LOCATION> Detroit </LOCATION>, officials said. In <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION>, a <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> 727 returned to <LOCATION> Newark </LOCATION> <LOCATION> International </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Airport </LOCATION> after a faulty cockpit indicator alerted the pilot to engine power failure, and a <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> helicopter developed engine trouble and was forced to land in the <LOCATION> Atlantic </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ocean </LOCATION> about 10 miles off <LOCATION> Ponte </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Vedra </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Beach </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Fla. </LOCATION>. No injuries were reported in any of the incidents The slew of mishaps came one day after the fiery crash of <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> Flight 232. At least 76 people were killed, and up to 43 others were missing and believed dead. In <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>, the DC-10 en route from <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION> made an unscheduled landing at <LOCATION> O'Hare </LOCATION> <LOCATION> International </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Airport </LOCATION> after at least one bird was sucked into one of the engines. The 265 passengers and 10 crew members on Flight 23 were later transferred to another airplane and continued their flight, <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Russell </PERSON> <PERSON> Mack </PERSON> said. `` The airplane was leaving <LOCATION> JFK </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Airport </LOCATION>, was climbing out after takeoff, when either a bird or several birds were ingested into the No. 1 engine, which is on the left side of the airplane,'' <PERSON> Mack </PERSON> said. `` The engine experienced some vibration and the captain shut the engine down, and then proceeded to ... O'Hare ... where he landed normally and safely.'' Earlier in the day, one of the three engines on the <ORGANIZATION> Northwest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> 727 developed a compressor problem, and the pilot returned the jet to <LOCATION> Detroit </LOCATION> Metropolitan Airport, said <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Gibbons </PERSON>, spokesman for the <PERSON> Eagan </PERSON>, Minn.-based airline. `` We had the emergency equipment standing by as a precaution,'' he said. Flight 492 was carrying 146 passengers from <LOCATION> Detroit </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, who were transferred to another aircraft. In <LOCATION> Newark </LOCATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> 727 made a precautionary return after a faulty cockpit indicator alerted the pilot to engine power failure. <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION> Flight 850, with 137 passengers and six crew members, left <LOCATION> Newark </LOCATION> about 11 a.m. destined for <LOCATION> Bermuda </LOCATION>, said <PERSON> Dave </PERSON> <PERSON> Messing </PERSON>, a spokesman for Houston-based <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION>. `` There was no loss of power in the engine,'' Messing said. `` The indication turned out to be faulty.'' The faulty indicator was replaced and the plane took off again at 4:40 p.m., <PERSON> Messing </PERSON> said. In <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>, the pilot of the SH-3 Sea King helicopter, Lt. <PERSON> Henry </PERSON> <PERSON> G. </PERSON> <PERSON> Bridgham </PERSON>, 30, of <LOCATION> Monterey </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>, had to use the aircraft's other engine to taxi the amphibious helicopter ashore, said <PERSON> Nick </PERSON> <PERSON> Young </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> spokesman
</TEXT>
