<FIRST>r a PM-DigestBriefs     07-20 0881</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Digest Briefs,0919</SECOND>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Elected to the newly powerful presidency by a single vote in parliament, Gen. <PERSON> Wojciech </PERSON> <PERSON> Jaruzelski </PERSON> now faces the daunting challenge of trying to salvage a crippled economy as new strikes break out. Because some lawmakers in his ruling Communist coalition voted against <PERSON> Jaruzelski </PERSON>, a boycott of Wednesday's balloting by a number of Solidarity legislators may have made the difference. The ruling coalition commands a 54 percent majority in the two-chamber parliament, where a simple majority was needed for election, but some hard-line Communists are resisting <PERSON> Jaruzelski </PERSON>'s road of compromise Most if not all Solidarity deputies and senators who participated apparently denied <PERSON> Jaruzelski </PERSON> their votes.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Miners' strikes have spread to three more of the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>'s coalfields, <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> reported today. The official news agency said coal miners in <LOCATION> Vorkuta </LOCATION> in the far north, the <LOCATION> Don </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> city of <LOCATION> Rostov </LOCATION> in southwestern <LOCATION> Russia </LOCATION> and the Ukrainian industrial center of <LOCATION> Dnepropetrovsk </LOCATION> walked out. It said their demands were similar to those of striking miners in the <LOCATION> Kuznetsk </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Donetsk </LOCATION> coal basins, who are seeking greater local control over their industries and better wages and living conditions. <LOCATION> Kuznetsk </LOCATION>, in western <LOCATION> Siberia </LOCATION>, and <LOCATION> Donetsk </LOCATION>, in the <LOCATION> Ukraine </LOCATION>, are the country's two leading coal basins and the strikes, which began 10 days ago, amount to the country's worst labor unrest since the turbulent 1920s.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Nineteen cities likely would be given 10 years to fix their ozone pollution problems, while severely polluted <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Houston </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> would have two decades, according to a draft of President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s clean air bill. The multibillion-dollar cleanup plan would set four new categories for cities with ozone problems _ severe, serious, moderate or marginal _ and require the most polluted communities to use the most stringent remedies. The <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> obtained a draft of the proposal, and then applied the latest available <ORGANIZATION> Environmental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Protection </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> air monitoring data to determine which cities would fall into the two most serious ozone pollution categories. There could be some changes when new air quality information becomes available, probably next month, but <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> officials said the number of switches should be small.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> faces more criminal probes of its nuclear weapons plants _ and mounting public pressure to close them _ unless it controls their environmental and safety problems, federal auditors say. In a report highly critical of department management, the auditors said urgent action is needed to ensure that environmental laws are obeyed and the public is reassured that the government can reliably and safely run the weapons plants. The report dated July 14 was made public Wednesday by a <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> panel as a senior <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> official disclosed that a special group of experts from outside the department had been dispatched to a weapons plant in <LOCATION> Colorado </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Leo </PERSON> <PERSON> Duffy </PERSON>, a special assistant to Energy Secretary <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Watkins </PERSON>, said in testimony prepared for a <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> subcommittee that the experts will attempt to verify the origin of a manmade radioactive element discovered at the Rocky Flats plant near <LOCATION> Denver </LOCATION>. The plant processes plutonium for weapons manufacturing.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The White House and key senators are working on a compromise that would restrict <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> contacts with officials of the <ORGANIZATION> Palestine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> directly linked to terrorist attacks on Americans. But they were unable Wednesday to persuade hard-line critics of the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> dialogue with <PERSON> Yasser </PERSON> <PERSON> Arafat </PERSON>'s organization to give up their attempt to impose even tighter restrictions. `` At this point, it's a wide-open ball game,'' a congressional source said. Sen. <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> <PERSON> Helms </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-N.C. </LOCATION>, a key sponsor of curbs, was insisting that President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> be required to certify that the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> was not dealing with masterminds and perpetrators of terrorist acts. Several other senators lined up with him.
