<FIRST>a a PM-BusinessMirror Adv20   07-20 0634</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Business Mirror, Adv 20 ,0652</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv20</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release PMs Thursday, July 20</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eldercare Is Here</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN CUNNIFF</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Analyst</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Child-care became an important employee benefit when a bulge of youngsters worked its way through the population. It still is, but now Americans are growing older, and elder-care is on the way. It is coming not simply because of demographic dictate; business efficiency might have even more to do with the development. Whatever, a growing number of companies concerned with their own future are considering it. Basic to their thinking is the realization that nearly one-fourth of a typical employer's workforce already provides adult care-giving services _ for a parent, grandparent or spouse. Generally, such services are provided directly and personally at home. Many of the corporate employees who provide these services hold critical positions, and as a result their work performance is sometimes less than efficient. Their inability to meet the highest standards often is related to the strain of their dual reponsibilities. The problem, therefore, becomes a concern of corporate management. <PERSON> Janice </PERSON> <PERSON> Stanger </PERSON>, who holds a doctorate in gerontology, recently completed a study for <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Mercer </PERSON> <PERSON> Meidinger </PERSON> <PERSON> Hansen </PERSON>, an international adviser on employee benefits. She found sound reasons for considering elder-care. She observes that with more and more women entering the workforce, the number of employees with at-home responsibilities is hardly likely to decline. These employees often are in their 30s and 40s, which means that not only do they have valuable experience but also years of further service to offer. Already, she suggests, there is evidence that the home-work conflict may interfere with their performance. It shows up, she says, in such behavior as missing work, turning down overtime and training, and even quitting. The corporation's role, she says, has two aspects: Long-term care insurance to pay for medical and associated support services, and special assistance to those workers with responsibilities for an older adult. Her definition of elder-care refers primarily to the second aspect, and has as its goal `` to improve the productivity and the health and quality of life of employed care-givers.'' And, you might add, the company too. The benefit helps the worker cope with three things that make taking care of elders difficult. First, she points out, the frail elderly often have interrelated needs that involve medicine, finance, and social and psychological factors. Next, the care of the elderly often involves conflicting opinions and wishes of a number of individuals _ the patient, spouse, siblings, children. Most of the care-givers can use help in resolving these conflicts. Finally, existing community resources consist of a maze of federal, state and local public programs, private non-profit agencies and for-profit providers. The red tape can be overwhelming. The elder-care program as she envisions it can be indirect and direct. The indirect programs involve personnel policies or benefits which are potentially of value to all employees, such as flextime, personal leaves and job sharing. Direct programs include information, including printed materials, lectures and other sources; and referral programs to specific agencies, nursing homes and other resources. In addition, they might include support groups and counseling, and even access to an adult day-care center for the older relative. Reimbursement programs also might be used to subsidize the cost of respite care. All this sounds expensive, as most benefits are, not just in themselves but as a growing percentage of business costs. But, according to the report, the cost of an elder-care program is usually `` modest and clearly defined.'' At a time when employers are resisting additional benefits and even taking away some benefits granted earlier, <PERSON> Stanger </PERSON> believes they have something to gain with elder-care, because it addresses so specific a need. She calls it an opportunity for them.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv PMs Thursday, July 20.</NOTE>
