<DOCNO> AP890720-0218 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-20-89 0948EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a a PM-MarchingCobras Adv27   07-20 0832</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Marching Cobras, Adv 27,0850</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv27</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release Thurs PMs, July 27, and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Award-Winning Drill Team Helps Inner-City Members</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By AMANDA DAVIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KANSAS CITY, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The children who swing their hips, bob their heads and fling their knees and elbows up and out to throbbing drumbeats have left crowds wide-eyed from <LOCATION> Kansas </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> to the nation's capital and beyond. The Marching Cobras, an award-winning drill team, also leave a mark on the members, many of them from poor, inner-city homes with one parent. `` For one, you get a chance to travel and do all sorts of things, and another, it keeps you out of trouble,'' said <PERSON> Aaron </PERSON> <PERSON> Byrd </PERSON>, 15, a Cobra for five years. `` I think I might be on the street and in trouble if I was n't in the group. ... There are no down sides to being in the Cobras.'' `` I've made a lot of friends in the Cobras,'' said <PERSON> A'yanna </PERSON> <PERSON> Gilmore </PERSON>, 14, who has been in the drill team three years. `` And it makes you learn independence, and responsibility for your uniform, your performance and everything.'' <PERSON> Willie </PERSON> <PERSON> Smith </PERSON>, drillmaster for 20 years, said it's virtually impossible to understand what the Cobras are without seeing their flashy uniforms and intricate routines, elbows and knees pumping 1 -LCB- times for every drumbeat. As much a part of <LOCATION> Kansas </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> as its fountains, the Cobras average 300 invitations a year and accept 100 to 200. They performed 117 times last year, including what <PERSON> Smith </PERSON> called a `` dream come true,'' for President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>. `` He kind of pepped up when we started,'' <PERSON> Smith </PERSON> said. `` I really wanted to go grab him and get him to dance, but the security men, we could n't go past this line, or that line. But he would have liked it.'' The Cobras made their first overseas trip in February, to <LOCATION> Nice </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>, where they competed in the City of Carnivals Festival. They won awards in three categories, including best international drill team. `` We saw <PERSON> Monte </PERSON> <PERSON> Carlo </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Cannes </LOCATION>, stayed in the best hotels, ate the best meals,'' <PERSON> Smith </PERSON> said. `` I'd never get to do that by myself. And here are these kids going to a place they never even heard of.'' For the members, being in the Cobras is `` their big chance,'' he said. `` When we went to <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>, we found out that some of the kids have never been to the airport, they've never been to the -LRB- Country Club -RRB- Plaza,'' an affluent <LOCATION> Kansas </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> restaurant and shopping area. The Cobras began in 1969 when <PERSON> Smith </PERSON> coached a group of seventh-grade boys to dance in a talent show. That group evolved into a drill team and eventually became the <LOCATION> Kansas </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> Marching Cobras _ so named after a school librarian watching from a third-floor window said it looked like a snake. Whites are n't excluded but all the members, who range in age from 8 to 18, are black, <PERSON> Smith </PERSON> said. `` I do n't think there's too many whites who want to come to the inner city to practice.'' Money problems nearly ended the Cobras in 1986, but the team affiliated with the <ORGANIZATION> Boys </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Girls </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Club </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Kansas </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, which eased the money crunch, <PERSON> Smith </PERSON> said. `` Until we came to the boys and girls clubs, we raised the money ourselves. Bake sales, car washes, raffles. `` But in some ways we were happier when we were scuffing it. The kids now are getting spoiled. They know they get the uniform, so they do n't take care of it like they did before. If the parents paid $ 70 or $ 80 for it, it would be taken care of.'' The glitzy uniforms cost $ 150 - $ 175 each, so only 85 Cobras can be in uniform at any time The colors vary each year. Also each year, two Cobras are honored as the mascot and senior imperial. The mascot wears a rubber cobra headpiece and leads the group. `` The person who wears the cobra headpiece is the most outstanding member,'' <PERSON> Smith </PERSON> said. `` They have to compete for it. An 11-year-old dreams of wearing the mascot head. It's prestigious and it's an honor.'' The Cobras are based at the Boys and <ORGANIZATION> Girls </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Club </ORGANIZATION>. The windowless brown brick building squats in the inner city, clusters of children lounging outside. Cars stop on the street, disgorging more children. Practice is three times a week. <PERSON> Smith </PERSON>'s office exhibits honors from past performances. Plaques, trophies, photographs and letters cover the walls. A box of awards sits in a corner. After 20 years, <PERSON> Smith </PERSON> is more than drillmaster, and many members call him `` Dad.'' They knock on his door to tell him of problems or ask advice. Being on the team keeps them off the street, which has always been his goal. `` Children have changed. The kids are n't as interested in extracurricular activities. We need to spend even more time with them now than before, because they spend more time on the streets now. And the streets are worse.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Thurs PMs, July 27</NOTE>
