<HEAD>For Release Mon PMS July 24 or Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>English-Speaking Caribbean Islands Seek to Unite</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserGraphic</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSANA HAYWARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ST. GEORGE'S, Grenada (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The idea of merging the <LOCATION> Caribbean </LOCATION>'s smallest English-speaking islands into a single nation or federation has been around for half a century with little ever coming of it But now that a major trading partner, <LOCATION> Western </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, is moving toward economic integration, the fervor of unity advocates has increased. Prime Minister <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Mitchell </PERSON> of <PERSON> St. </PERSON> <PERSON> Vincent </PERSON> and the <ORGANIZATION> Grenadines </ORGANIZATION>, a leader of the most promising attempt at political union since the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Indies </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Federation </LOCATION> collapsed nearly 30 years ago, maintains the eastern <LOCATION> Caribbean </LOCATION> faces economic disaster if it does n't unite by the time the 12 nations of the <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Community </ORGANIZATION> form a single market by the end of 1992. Mostly at stake are <LOCATION> Caribbean </LOCATION> bananas. <PERSON> Mitchell </PERSON>, attending a recent regional meeting on <LOCATION> Grenada </LOCATION>, said that without political unity, individual islands wo n't have the political power to protect their banana sales in <LOCATION> England </LOCATION> after the European trade barriers fall. `` Who will respect you when you go to <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> representing a ministate? How much time will they have for you?'' <PERSON> Mitchell </PERSON> said in a recent interview. `` We do n't need unity to survive. We need it to get our voice heard in the international community.'' `` I'm bone-tired of trying to convince people,'' he added. `` I think we've lost the momentum in spite of how urgently it's needed.'' <PERSON> Vaughn </PERSON> <PERSON> Lewis </PERSON>, secretary-general of the Organization of <LOCATION> Eastern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Caribbean </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, said, `` If you go to <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> and say you represent a chain of islands, the impact is greater than if you say you represent one. The <LOCATION> Caribbean </LOCATION> benefits today from preferential trade access for its agricultural products into the <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION>. Under current agreements, <LOCATION> Caribbean </LOCATION> bananas are protected in <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>, which does not import bananas from other regions. <LOCATION> Caribbean </LOCATION> bananas grow on small farms and are more expensive than those mass-produced in Central and <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>. With the dismantling of <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION> trade barriers, <LOCATION> Caribbean </LOCATION> bananas will have to compete in an open market. British consumers then could be expected to buy the cheaper Central and <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> bananas and the <LOCATION> Caribbean </LOCATION>'s $ 175 million annual market would collapse. The <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Indies </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Federation </LOCATION> was founded in 1958 as the first attempt at political integration but disintegrated four years later when <LOCATION> Jamaica </LOCATION> withdrew. <PERSON> Mitchell </PERSON>, supported by Prime Minister <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Compton </PERSON> of <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lucia </LOCATION>, renewed the unity drive at the 1987 summit meeting of the Organization of <LOCATION> Eastern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Caribbean </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, a regional sub-grouping within the <LOCATION> Caribbean </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Community </LOCATION> and Common Market. The idea of creating a single country or a regional federation of states by mid-1989 out of the eastern <LOCATION> Caribbean </LOCATION> islands of <LOCATION> Antigua </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kitts-Nevis </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Montserrat </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Dominica </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Grenada </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lucia </LOCATION> and <PERSON> St. </PERSON> <PERSON> Vincent </PERSON> was approved in principle. But <LOCATION> Antigua </LOCATION> withdrew almost immediately and was followed later by <LOCATION> Montserrat </LOCATION> and <PERSON> St. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kitts-Nevis </PERSON>. <PERSON> Mitchell </PERSON> and <PERSON> Compton </PERSON> still favor political union of the remaining four, known as the <LOCATION> Windward </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Islands </LOCATION>. The eastern <LOCATION> Caribbean </LOCATION> islands share a central bank, common currency and high court. All are small and relatively undeveloped with a combined English-speaking population of 400,000. In land mass, the largest is <LOCATION> Dominica </LOCATION> with 289 square miles and the smallest is <LOCATION> Montserrat </LOCATION>, the only remaining British colony of the group, with just 39 square miles. Geographically, they resemble a 450-mile kite tail stretching from <LOCATION> Puerto </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rico </LOCATION> in the north to <LOCATION> Trinidad </LOCATION> in the south. Their populations range from 12,000 in <LOCATION> Montserrat </LOCATION> to 119,000 in <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lucia </LOCATION>. Detractors say a political marriage is unrealistic; each island is as unique as any nation, regardless of size. They say economic integration, not political, is what is needed. `` We go to the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> and fight tooth-and-nail to portray small island states as having special characteristics and requiring special treatment. We can not ignore this reality in our forums,'' Prime Minister <PERSON> Kenneth </PERSON> <PERSON> Simmonds </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> St. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Kitts-Nevis </ORGANIZATION> said in an interview. `` We already go to <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> as a team speaking for the region,'' he said. `` The <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION> is not a national front, it's a regional front. The process should be the same for us.'' The Windwards export 220,000 tons of bananas a year to <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>, accounting for two-thirds of the bananas consumed in <LOCATION> England </LOCATION>. The four islands plan to hold a political union referendum after parliamentary elections, still unscheduled, are held in <LOCATION> Grenada </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Dominica </LOCATION>. The <LOCATION> Caribbean </LOCATION> Community, an organization of 13 English-speaking states that includes the <ORGANIZATION> Windwards </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Leewards </ORGANIZATION>, already has taken steps to form a common market. `` At present there is little immediate prospect for political unity,'' Prime Minister <PERSON> Herbert </PERSON> <PERSON> Blaize </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Grenada </LOCATION> said in welcoming heads of government to a recent meeting here. `` But we continue to knock at the door for closer cooperation and cry fervently for economic integration.'' <LOCATION> Caribbean </LOCATION> leaders say economic unity is imperative if they are to survive the trading blocs being formed around the world, including the recent <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> trade agreement. Prime Minister <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Manley </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Jamaica </LOCATION> has called it `` the only way a group of small countries can survive.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Mon PMs July 24</NOTE>
