<FIRST>a i PM-KhabarovskReacts Adv25   07-20 0505</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Khabarovsk Reacts, Adv 25,0514</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv25</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Tues PMs July 25 or Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Reserve Troops in Far East Assail Sakharov for Afghanistan Charge</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Vladivostok Notes, b0294</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL PUTZEL ^Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KHABAROVSK, U.S.S.R. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Thousands of miles from <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>, the name <PERSON> Andrei </PERSON> <PERSON> Sakharov </PERSON> kindles fire in the hearts of young men still smarting from the wounds of the Soviet adventure in <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>. In a riverside square in this century-old Siberian city, a platoon of <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> veterans staged a bit of street theater one evening recently to demonstrate their reserve group's combat training, play some popular songs _ and take a swipe at the Nobel Peace laureate regarded as the founder of the Soviet human rights movement. Between numbers played by a military band in fatigue uniforms, an announcer told the few hundred people in the audience, `` We all remember how academician <PERSON> Sakharov </PERSON> insulted us at the <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Deputies </ORGANIZATION>.'' <PERSON> Sakharov </PERSON> was heckled during the parliamentary session in June and lambasted by a parade of speakers who accused him of blaspheming the military in an interview in <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> earlier in the year in which he was quoted as saying Soviet pilots killed soldiers they could not save from being captured by Afghan rebels. The 68-year-old physicist and now a <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> deputy endured almost seven years in exile in the closed city of Gorky for his outspoken opposition to the Soviet military intervention that began in December 1979. He told the <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> he would not retract his charge, pending the outcome of an investigation by Soviet authorities. The emotional, nationally broadcast attack on <PERSON> Sakharov </PERSON> reverberated weeks later in this Far Eastern city built on the banks of the great <LOCATION> Amur </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> to protect against <LOCATION> Chinese </LOCATION> invasion 4,400 miles from <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>. The reservists loaded their assault rifles and machine guns with blanks and climbed atop an armored personnel carrier that bore a red banner proclaiming, `` <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> _ in my heart forever.'' With police motioning the crowd to make way, a squad of troops ambled up the street and was gunned down by mock <ORGANIZATION> Mujahadeen </ORGANIZATION> rebels lying in ambush by the side of the road. Guns blazing, the armored personnel carrier sped to the rescue, and the `` wounded'' <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> soldiers were hastily loaded into an ambulance truck that escaped in a hail of fire, its driver nearly grazing the crowd in a hair-raising demonstration of evasive driving tactics. The chatter of machine guns and ear-splitting roar of artillery rocked the night as first the truck was halted by fire, then the personnel carrier was captured by rebels and recaptured by the Soviets. The <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> men risked their lives over and over until they finally succeeded in hauling their wounded to safety. The last Soviet troops pulled out of <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> on Feb. 15 after more than nine years of fighting, but as the street drama in <LOCATION> Khabarovsk </LOCATION> illustrated, the withdrawal was no instant cure for what President <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> once called his nation's `` bleeding wound.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Tues PMs July 25</NOTE>
