<FIRST>s a BC-PersonalFile-Sheehy Adv23   07-20 1018</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Personal File-Sheehy, Adv 23,1051</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv23</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, July 23, and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>BAT Chairman Faces Takeover Threat for a Change</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Also on financial wires.</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By COTTEN TIMBERLAKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Patrick </PERSON> <PERSON> Sheehy </PERSON> has spent his entire professional life with <ORGANIZATION> BAT </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industries </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> PLC </ORGANIZATION>, and as chairman of the tobacco giant he's led a $ 7.2 billion takeover spree into businesses ranging from insurance to department stores. Now the 58-year-old chairman is finding out what it's like on the receiving end of a bid: an unsolicited $ 21 billion, debt-financed takeover offer from a trio led by swashbuckling investor Sir <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Goldsmith </PERSON>. `` I suppose it's definitely ironic,'' <PERSON> Sheehy </PERSON> said. `` My reaction to the bid was one of surprise, initially, not that we thought that we were invulnerable. But I mean I certainly thought that this type of raid was unlikely.'' The <PERSON> Goldsmith </PERSON> offer, financed largely with borrowed money, would be the second biggest ever if successful, after the record $ 25 billion <ORGANIZATION> RJR </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nabisco </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> takeover by the <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> investment firm <ORGANIZATION> Kohlberg </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Kravis </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Roberts </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; Co. In an interview, <PERSON> Sheehy </PERSON> described <PERSON> Goldsmith </PERSON> and partners as avaricious financiers, whose plan to break up BAT and sell pieces to help pay for a takeover is `` just naked asset stripping.'' In contrast, <PERSON> Sheehy </PERSON> said, BAT's acquisitions of other companies have been friendly, with the notable exception of a $ 5.2 billion takeover of <ORGANIZATION> Farmers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Insurance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> earlier this year. Even in that case, <PERSON> Sheehy </PERSON> said, the takeover was a strategic, long-term investment. <PERSON> Sheehy </PERSON> is a large man with graying hair, blue eyes and florid face, who began working for BAT nearly 40 years ago when it was still known as British <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tobacco </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co </ORGANIZATION>. He became chairman in 1982. The BAT battle may boil down to a struggle between <PERSON> Goldsmith </PERSON>, renowned for profitable forays for other companies, and <PERSON> Sheehy </PERSON>, a modest but intensely determined one-company man who knows how a takeover strategist thinks. <PERSON> Sheehy </PERSON>'s defense so far has been to raise the alarms, and to hope that the takeover bid will get stuck in a regulatory quagmire. BAT will ask <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s Office of Fair Trading to refer the matter to the <ORGANIZATION> Monopolies </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mergers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> to decide whether the bid violates the public interest, <PERSON> Sheehy </PERSON> said. `` We are certainly using our political friends to try and bring pressure to bear,'' he said. <PERSON> Sheehy </PERSON> also predicted the governments of other countries where BAT operates will raise concern about <PERSON> Goldsmith </PERSON>'s bid, particularly in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, where regulatory authorities will want detailed plans on how a takeover would affect Farmers, one of the nation's biggest insurers. <PERSON> Goldsmith </PERSON> and his two partners, British banker <PERSON> Jacob </PERSON> <PERSON> Rothschild </PERSON> and Australian entrepreneur <PERSON> Kerry </PERSON> <PERSON> Packer </PERSON>, have attacked <PERSON> Sheehy </PERSON>'s strategy of diversifying into financial services and retailing The trio's newly formed firm, <ORGANIZATION> Hoylake </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Investments </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> PLC </ORGANIZATION>, which announced the takeover offer July 11, said it intends to sell everything except BAT's tobacco business. `` We are clearly fighting it on our record,'' <PERSON> Sheehy </PERSON> said. `` Our record, quite contrary to what <LOCATION> Hoylake </LOCATION> claims, has been, we think, outstanding.'' Since <PERSON> Sheehy </PERSON> took BAT's helm, earnings per share have grown 18.5 percent per year, compared with a British company average of 11.5 percent, he said. Put another way, the chairman said, $ 160 invested in the company in April 1981 today are worth $ 1,829. BAT's earnings rose 21 percent to $ 1.5 billion last year on a 3 percent revenue gain to $ 28 billion. The company owns a range of well-known products and services, including <PERSON> Benson </PERSON> and <PERSON> Hedges </PERSON>, <PERSON> Kent </PERSON> and Kool cigarettes; <ORGANIZATION> Saks </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fifth </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Avenue </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Marshall </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Field </LOCATION>'s and Argos stores; <ORGANIZATION> Eagle </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Star </ORGANIZATION> insurance products; Allied Dunbar financial services; and <LOCATION> Appleton </LOCATION> and <PERSON> Wiggins </PERSON> <PERSON> Teape </PERSON> paper. <PERSON> Sheehy </PERSON>, son of a colonial civil servant, was born in <LOCATION> Burma </LOCATION> in 1930. He was sent to school in <LOCATION> Australia </LOCATION> during World War II, attended <ORGANIZATION> Ampleforth </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION>, a boys boarding school in <LOCATION> Yorkshire </LOCATION>, in northeast <LOCATION> England </LOCATION>, and then served in the Irish Guards, rising to second lieutenant. Skipping a university education, <PERSON> Sheehy </PERSON> joined <ORGANIZATION> British </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tobacco </ORGANIZATION> in 1950 at age 20 as a management trainee. He was posted to <LOCATION> Nigeria </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ghana </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ethiopia </LOCATION> and finally to the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Indies </LOCATION>, where he was general manager. In 1962, he returned to <ORGANIZATION> BAT </ORGANIZATION>'s <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> headquarters as a marketing adviser, but five years later he was off again, this time as general manager in the <LOCATION> Netherlands </LOCATION>. Some postings were better than others. `` I had three and a half years in <LOCATION> Ethiopia </LOCATION>. It was a time I often was wondering whether I was going to spend all my life there and did n't want to,'' he said. Living half his life abroad `` made me fairly adaptable, fairly resilient, fairly self-reliant, with a wide range of interests,'' <PERSON> Sheehy </PERSON> said. Although he has never worked for any company except BAT, he said, `` I'd like to think I have n't had one career but I've had several careers, in different countries, in different businesses.'' <PERSON> Sheehy </PERSON> rose through BAT's management hierarchy quickly, joining the board of directors at age 39. His salary as chairman is low by <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> standards, at about $ 720,000 a year. Asked to describe his style, <PERSON> Sheehy </PERSON> said: `` I like to think that I listen to other people and then take a decision and try and get involved in ensuring that it's implemented, not by telling people exactly what to do, but by encouraging them and guiding them.'' What does he think his 310,000 employee worldwide say about him? `` Probably things unprintable,'' <PERSON> Sheehy </PERSON> said. `` I used to say that about my bosses.'' Married and the father of two, <PERSON> Sheehy </PERSON> lives in west <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, owns an English country home, and admits an addiction to golf. His handicap is somewhere between 10 and 20, he says, adding, `` depends who I'm playing.'' In this latest boardroom game, <PERSON> Sheehy </PERSON> has a lot at stake personally, although he insists he is n't acting to protect his own job. `` I have n't actually got much more than a couple of years before I retire so its not as devastating a thing as if I was 40 or something like that,'' he said. `` I can say goodbye.''
