<FIRST>a a BC-EXP--What'sNew-Stings Adv24   07-20 0429</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-EXP--What's New-Stings, Adv 24,0437</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv24</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release Monday, July 24, and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>More May Suffer From Sting Allergies Than Thought</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By IRIS CHANG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Five to 10 times more people may be allergic to insect stings than previously thought, according to a new study. `` It's amazing how many people have suffered from this and never told their doctors about it,'' said <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Golden </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Johns </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hopkins </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>, one of the researchers who tested 269 people and studied their medical histories. Past studies showed that only about one in 200 people have a history of dangerous or fatal allergic reactions to stings, but the new study showed the figure is closer to three or four in 100, said <PERSON> Lawrence </PERSON> <PERSON> Lichtenstein </PERSON>, who led the research published in the Journal of the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>. At least 50 Americans a year die from severe allergic reactions to insect stings, and their death is the first sign of their allergy, he said. Typically, people stung by bees, wasps or ants will have a local reaction, a small swelling. A more severe case would be a large local reaction, swelling a patch of skin. But a `` systemic'' allergic reaction affects the entire body. It can mean either swelling all over the body, shortness of breath, or a drop in blood pressure, or all three, and can result in serious illness or death. In the study, 269 factory workers were given skin tests with bee and yellow jacket venom, and filled out questionnaires on their allergic histories. Fifteen percent of those who reported no history of allergic reactions reacted positively to the skin test. `` That is of special interest since most fatal sting reactions occur in individuals who had never experienced an allergic sting reaction,'' the researchers wrote. The researchers also took blood to check for allergy-causing antibodies. More than 26 percent of the workers showed the potential to develop a systemic allergy. Each of those 70 had a 20 percent chance of developing a dangerous or fatal systemic reaction to an insect bit, <PERSON> Lichtenstein </PERSON> said. He urged people who have had severe reactions to enter venom immunotherapy, in which small doses of venom are injected into the bloodstream to build up the patient's immunity. The treatment is almost 100 percent effective, <PERSON> Golden </PERSON> said. Nine out of 10 patients who suffer from systemic reactions do not realize they are in life-threatening danger, he said. `` They get up from a serious reaction and think its a fluke and that it will never happen again.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for July 24</NOTE>
</DOC>
