<DOCNO> AP890720-0227 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-20-89 0221EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-BusinessHighlights     07-20 0872</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Business Highlights,0913</SECOND>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Consumer prices rose a modest 0.2 percent in June, the smallest advance since early last year, the government said in a report that bolstered the view that inflationary pressures are beginning to ease. The slowdown reported Wednesday in the Consumer Price Index reflected the fact that energy and food costs, which had been shooting upward this year, finally moderated last month. Stock prices responded to the upbeat news with a strong rally that carried the market to new highs since the crash of October 1987. The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials jumped 39.65 points to 2,584.41.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
