<HEAD>World Bank Makes Billion-Dollar Profit; Cuts Loan Fee</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> says it met its goal of a billion-dollar profit in its latest fiscal year, allowing it to cut a loan fee and resume a suspended aid program for the world's poorest countries A top bank official also repeated Wednesday that <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> is first in line for a new <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> debt-reduction program, followed by <LOCATION> Venezuela </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Costa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rica </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION>. Debt reduction for those nations depends on their reaching agreements with commercial bank creditors, said <PERSON> Ernest </PERSON> <PERSON> Stern </PERSON>, the <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION>'s senior vice president for finance. `` That's more or less a complete list. That does n't mean others will not follow in the next six months,'' he said at a <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> press conference. Borrowers will save about $ 200 million a year under a cut announced Wednesday in the <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION>'s commitment fee, which is charged to borrowers on the portion of authorized loans they have not yet received, <PERSON> Stern </PERSON> said. The bank will resume contributing $ 100 million of its profit to a program that makes `` soft'' loans to the very poorest countries, which are generally not able to make interest payments, spokesman <PERSON> Sheldon </PERSON> <PERSON> Rappaport </PERSON> said. In a switch, this year's contribution will go for debt reduction, the bank said. The annual contribution was suspended last year when the <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> needed to devote its profit to building up the reserves backing its loans. Loans to the poorest countries through the bank's <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Development </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> are stretched out over 40 years and carry an interest rate of less than 1 percent. Most of the IDA's roughly $ 5 billion in annual lending comes from government contributions. The Washington-based <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> said its profit in the fiscal year ended June 30 totaled $ 1.094 billion, up from $ 1.004 billion a year earlier. <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> has made a profit of $ 1 billion a year each of the last five years. It plows the money back into further lending. The organization was founded in 1945 to make loans to developing countries and has 151 member countries. After several years of being low on reserves, the bank built its reserve-to-loan ratio to 10.2 percent last year, within its target range of 10 percent to 11 percent. The bank revealed Wednesday that its board had adopted a financial management system in February that will reduce the risk from wide swings in currency exchange rates. By the end of June 1990, borrowers will be required to make loan payments with a fixed combination of currencies, about evenly split between dollars, Japanese yen and West German marks. The fixed ratio will make it easier for borrowers to plan their repayments, the bank said. <PERSON> Stern </PERSON> said the bank will try to match the mix of currencies in its loan portfolio with the mix of currencies in its reserves. In the last few years the dollar's decline shrank the size of its reserves in comparison to its loans, which were heavy in other currencies. In its annual income statement, the bank said its return on assets came to 1.09 percent, up from 0.98 percent the year before. The bank said it borrowed $ 9.3 billion in 17 currencies last year, at an average cost of 7.73 percent and an average life of 7.8 years. Although government-supported, the <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> gets about 90 percent of its funding for loans from private investors.
</TEXT>
