<HEAD>Senators Propose Additional Help for Disabled Americans</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A bipartisan group of senators has introduced legislation to allow disabled Americans receiving Social Security disability benefits to return to the workforce without losing their medical coverage. Chief sponsor Sen. <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> <PERSON> Riegle </PERSON>, D-Mich., said Wednesday that many recipients of Social Security Disability Insurance currently avoid returning to work because they lose their benefits, including Medicare coverage, if they earn more than $ 300 a month after a trial work period Under the legislation, disabled people who returned to work would remain eligible for <ORGANIZATION> Medicare </ORGANIZATION>, and some would pay for the coverage on a sliding fee scale linked to their earnings. Currently, <ORGANIZATION> Medicare </ORGANIZATION> is unavailable to these individuals at any price. `` Those people who want to work should have the opportunity to do so,'' <PERSON> Riegle </PERSON> said. `` A disabled person should not be punished by taking away much needed medical benefits.'' The legislation, whose chief co-sponsor is <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> Minority Leader <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Dole </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Kansas </LOCATION>, would cover about 4 million disabled workers nationwide. A similar bill has been introduced in the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> by Rep. <PERSON> Steve </PERSON> <PERSON> Bartlett </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Texas </LOCATION>. Costs of the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> legislation have been estimated at $ 120 million over five years, but that does not take into effect the contributions to the economy that would be made by those who went back to work. The bill is a followup to legislation enacted last session that extended similar work incentives to recipients of Supplemental Security Income, a separate program that provides a minimal income floor to the nation's aged, disabled and blind.
