<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> can not adequately enforce federal antitrust laws because of budget cuts that have reduced funding and staffing, an <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bar </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> panel said in a report. The 15-member panel's report, released Wednesday, also called on <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration officials to end `` rhetoric'' that some existing antitrust laws are outdated and should n't be enforced. `` ... the task force members uniformly believe that the antitrust division's core mission _ to preserve competitive markets _ can not be carried out at the current reduced levels of staffing and resources,'' says the 59-page report. The report was submitted to the bar association's antitrust section and was not considered as representing the position of the section or the association. It was released in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> by <PERSON> Irving </PERSON> <PERSON> Scher </PERSON>, chairman of the bar association's antitrust section, which monitors and recommends changes in antitrust law. <PERSON> Scher </PERSON> said copies of the report were sent to Attorney General <PERSON> Dick </PERSON> <PERSON> Thornburgh </PERSON> and the recently appointed antitrust division head, <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Rill </PERSON>. The <ORGANIZATION> ABA </ORGANIZATION> antitrust section was likely to approve the report and refer it to the full association, <PERSON> Scher </PERSON> said. Asked for his reaction to the report, <PERSON> Rill </PERSON> said, `` On balance, it's positive. `` It confirms the enforcement priorities of the division _ criminal enforcement and merger enforcement,'' <PERSON> Rill </PERSON> said. He said the report `` makes some useful suggestions regarding structural and competition analysis that can be brought into play in deregulation and still somewhat regulated industries.'' While <PERSON> Rill </PERSON> said the report `` probably is a bit off the mark in suggesting that the merger guidelines have not been fully enforced,'' he said, `` it does represent a public perception'' that the antitrust division has not enforced those guidelines. Noting his brief tenure, <PERSON> Rill </PERSON> said he has not made any final assessment as to whether the division has enough manpower and money to do its job. The division has about 500 people, he said, including 230 attorneys and 40 economists. Under 1982 and 1984 modifications in federal antitrust laws, many constraints against mergers in a range of industries were eased as the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration endorsed allowing market forces to regulate competition. `` Although it was important to highlight the excesses of prior enforcement policies and substantive antitrust doctrines, the task force believes that further reliance on this rhetoric will undermine self-policing and voluntary compliance with the law,'' the panel stated. It added that `` diminished support for antitrust enforcement has allowed the talent and other resources of the division to shrink, as its mission was lost in the ` non-action' enforcement rhetoric of the times.'' Panel member <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> McGrath </PERSON>, a former assistant attorney general for antitrust, disagreed with the contention that criticism of exisiting laws had undercut enforcement policies. He and various other panel members also dissented from several key criticisms contained in the report. The panel said that under the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration's deregulatory philosophy enforcement of actions other than bid-rigging and price-fixing have become `` extremely rare. It said that during the 1980s, when merger activity skyrocketed, antitrust division resources devoted to merger enforcement actions declined and the <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> allowed a significant number of mergers it did not statistically define as competitive. While supporting overall changes in antitrust laws, the panel recommended a `` more vigorous and visible merger enforcement program'' and said antitrust laws should not be relaxed further. It also called for more criminal price-fixing investigations. In pressing for increased funding, the group said the antitrust division staff had been reduced by 50 percent in the last eight years and many of its most experienced lawyers had left. It said support for antitrust division lawyers appeared to be at an `` all-time low.'' The panel included three former assistant attorneys general in charge of the antitrust division, former senior staff members, private antitrust attorneys, scholars and economists. <PERSON> Rill </PERSON> said some of the report's criticism `` is misdirected. The suggestion that the division is using some set of standards other than the merger guidelines simply is n't the case.'' <PERSON> Rill </PERSON> rejected the report's contention that criminal enforcement of antitrust laws had been aimed mostly at small companies instead of regional or national ones.
