<HEAD>Contract Costs Mean Loss for Northrop</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Northrop </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> lost $ 78.1 million in its second quarter despite an earnings increase because of additional costs it must bear on secret research and development contracts, the defense contractor reported. <ORGANIZATION> Northrop </ORGANIZATION> announced Wednesday that sales were $ 1.4 billion for the quarter, up 4 percent from the same period in 1988. However, the firm had a net loss of $ 78.1 million compared with a profit of $ 21.9 million, or 47 cents a share, for the 1988 period. The loss was caused by $ 150 million in estimated additional costs to complete a classified long-term, fixed-price contract. <ORGANIZATION> Northrop </ORGANIZATION> said the contract was unrelated to its B-2 stealth bomber program, which has suffered cost overruns. For the first half of 1989, <ORGANIZATION> Northrop </ORGANIZATION> had a net loss of $ 68.4 million on virtually flat sales of $ 2.68 billion, compared with a profit of $ 161.5 million, or $ 3.44 per share, for the same period last year.
