<HEAD>New Fashion Magazine Settles Down to Hard Work of Making It</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CATHERINE CROCKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The glittering coming-out party for <PERSON> Mirabella </PERSON>, the new women's <ORGANIZATION> fashion </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> magazine </ORGANIZATION>, is history. The upbeat reviews have been written, and the gossip columnists have turned their attention elsewhere. Now begins the waiting game. Will the upscale fashion and lifestyle guide for the well-educated woman be a lasting hit? Or will it join the heap of new magazines that fold after only a few years? `` It's going very well. I think wonderfully well,'' <PERSON> Grace </PERSON> <PERSON> Mirabella </PERSON>, the monthly's editor and namesake, said Wednesday. All 600,000 copies of the premier issue in June sold out, she said. But this veteran of the competitive, crowded world of magazines knows success can be fleeting. `` I'm anxiety-ridden,'' she says. And the sales figures for the July issue _ 70 to 75 percent of 600,000 copies are expected to sell _ could be interpreted as cautionary. But <PERSON> Julie </PERSON> <PERSON> Lewit-Nirenberg </PERSON>, the magazine's publisher, noted that summer is traditionally a slow time in the magazine business and that the first issue sold for $ 1 compared to the hefty $ 2.95 that the buyer must now fork out. She also said the number of advertising pages dropped from 123 in June to 85 in July and 50 in August. But the picture is rosy for the September issue, which just closed for printing with 149 advertising pages, she added. Ms. <PERSON> Mirabella </PERSON> described the pitfalls to avoid if the magazine is to succeed. `` We have to keep our eye on the reader we think we have _ where her head is and how she sees us. The reader we have is an intelligent reader, selective in her view and selective in her eye.'' By targeting a narrowly defined audience of well-educated, older and affluent women, <PERSON> Mirabella </PERSON> has a chance of surviving in the crowded fashion magazine market, said <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Ostrow </PERSON>, worldwide media director of <PERSON> Foote </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Cone </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Belding </ORGANIZATION>, a <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> ad agency. But a good six months will have to pass before any meaningful judgment can be made on the publication, said <PERSON> Nancy </PERSON> <PERSON> Smith </PERSON>, senior vice president of media services at <ORGANIZATION> Young </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rubicam </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, another <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> ad agency. `` <PERSON> Grace </PERSON> <PERSON> Mirabella </PERSON> is a well-known personality. And the launching of the magazine was very gossiping and jet-setting,'' she noted. `` Once that dies out, then you are going to see what you are dealing with. It's still too early to tell.'' Ms. <PERSON> Smith </PERSON> said the money and backing of communications magnate <PERSON> Rupert </PERSON> <PERSON> Murdoch </PERSON> bode well for <PERSON> Mirabella </PERSON>, as does the fact that Ms. <PERSON> Mirabella </PERSON> is the creative force behind it. `` She is an extremely talented woman who has demonstrated her strength before. I would be very optimistic about the long-term success.'' Ms. <PERSON> Mirabella </PERSON> was editor in chief of <LOCATION> Vogue </LOCATION> for 17 years before she was abruptly dismissed in June 1988 by S.I. <PERSON> Newhouse </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, the head of magazine publisher <PERSON> Conde </PERSON> <PERSON> Nast </PERSON>. In November, <PERSON> Murdoch </PERSON> approached her about presiding over a monthly bearing her name. In six months Ms. <PERSON> Mirabella </PERSON> not only assembled a staff but produced a new magazine. Despite its goals, the glossy, oversized publication has some features that can hardly be considered intelligent reading material. One article in the June issue lists the favorite lipstick color of actress <PERSON> Joan </PERSON> <PERSON> Collins </PERSON>, designer <PERSON> Caroline </PERSON> <PERSON> Herrera </PERSON> and jewelry designer <PERSON> Paloma </PERSON> <PERSON> Picasso </PERSON>. But its tone is more subtle than many other fashion magazines _ both in its fashion coverage and its features. And Ms. <PERSON> Mirabella </PERSON> and her staff pride themselves on the fact that the monthly is almost half text. `` It's a smart and intelligent magazine for women interested in style and fashion but like a little more protein in reading matter, not just a sugar high,'' Ms. <PERSON> Lewit-Nirenberg </PERSON> said.
