ize of their fleets,'' he <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION>, a non-union carrier that emerged from bankruptcy reorganization in 1986, and <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> were among only three major <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> airlines that did not have new planes on order. Troubled <ORGANIZATION> Pan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Am </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> is now the only one in that category. The agreement with <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> allows <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION> to substitute a portion of its order for <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION>'s 737-400s or 737-500s, which have different seating capacities, allowing for greater flexibility as the airline's needs change in the coming years, <PERSON> Corr </PERSON> said.
