<HEAD>Chrysler: Trucks 'R' Us</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 For the time being, <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>. Chairman <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> <PERSON> Iacocca </PERSON> says, the nation's No 3 automaker is more of a truckmaker than a carmaker. `` If you call minivans trucks, it looks that way because in the last 40 days in total, we've sold one car for every truck,'' <PERSON> Iacocca </PERSON> said in an interview this week. `` Other companies are n't quite in that position,'' he said, `` but that's just because of -LRB- Jeep -RRB- Cherokee strength and minivan strength.'' Auto industry analysts say the struggling company's emphasis on the profitable Jeeps and minivans may be the best tonic. `` Right now, it's a truckmaker that also makes cars,'' said auto analyst <PERSON> Ronald </PERSON> <PERSON> Glantz </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Montgomery </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION>. `` I think it's an intelligent decision on <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION>'s part because trucks make more money that cars.'' <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> is expected to announce Monday that its second-quarter earnings were near or slightly lower than those during the same time last year. This time around, the company will be relying more on the dollars generated by trucks than in the past. <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION>, through its Dodge Caravan and <ORGANIZATION> Plymouth </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Voyager </ORGANIZATION>, holds 56 percent of the minivan market in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. It pioneered the popular vehicles back in 1983 and has held most of the market since. Through the first half of this year _ and for the first time in history _ <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> sold more domestically made light trucks than cars. Together, those vehicles make up more than 90 percent of the company's fleet. Trough June 30 this year, the company sold 0.97 cars for each truck. A year ago at the same time, the ratio was 1.14 cars per truck. The gap was wider in the first half of 1987, as the company sold 1.56 cars per truck. <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motors </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>'s car sales have run slightly more than twice the rate of its truck sales, and <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> sells better than 1.5 cars for every truck. Despite the dominance of truck sales at <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Iacocca </PERSON> said the company is very much in the carmaking business. `` We ca n't become just a truck company,'' he said. `` We've got good car programs. First of all, our luxury cars are in pretty good shape because they're not too big. `` Then we have an all new platform coming in late'92,'' he said. `` That's a billion-dollar effort at a new mid-size group of cars and they're coming along nicely. `` The one that's tough is we do n't have an -LRB- Dodge -RRB- Omni replacement at the moment. Our smallest car really is the P-car, the <ORGANIZATION> Plymouth </ORGANIZATION> Sundance-Dodge Shadow.'' <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> is n't letting today's truck business take care of tomorrow. There will be more competition in the segment beginning in the next few months as the new <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION> minivans come to the market and as foreign companies, including <ORGANIZATION> Mazda </ORGANIZATION>, introduce more versions. A growing number of companies also are offering sport-utility vehicles like <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION>'s Jeep line. But <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> is n't standing still. The company has broken ground for a new assembly plant in <LOCATION> Detroit </LOCATION> that will make a Jeep model code-named the `` ZJ.'' Earlier this year, <PERSON> Iacocca </PERSON> announced that <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> and the French automaker <ORGANIZATION> Renault </ORGANIZATION> would join forces to make a smaller sport-utility vehicle named the `` JJ.'' Both of those products are to be introduced in the early 1990s and mean the company will have more truck production capacity than it does now. Anyone watching <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION>'s profits knows the company these days is making money from minivans and Jeeps. `` People look at the car side and wonder if they are at a competitive disadvantage to <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motors </ORGANIZATION>,'' said analyst <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Brady </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Oppenheimer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. `` That's hopefully just a temporary condition. `` But clearly, now you can make an excellent case if you want to classify it as a truckmaker,'' he said. `` Over the next couple of years, you'd have to say the show belongs mostly to the truck side of the operation.''
