<HEAD>Time Releases Brief in Delaware Supreme Coury Appeal</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOYCE M. ROSENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Time </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, maintaining its board has the right to decide the company's long-term strategy, has asked the <ORGANIZATION> Delaware </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> to uphold a lower court decision allowing the media giant to proceed with its $ 14 billion tender offer for <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communications </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>. Time made the request in a brief filed Wednesday with the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>, two days after <ORGANIZATION> Paramount </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communications </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> asked the court to overturn the ruling by <ORGANIZATION> Chancery </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> Judge <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> T. </PERSON> <PERSON> Allen </PERSON> and block the planned <ORGANIZATION> Time-Warner </ORGANIZATION> merger Paramount is trying to buy Time in a hostile $ 12.2 billion tender offer. <PERSON> Allen </PERSON> ruled last week the proposed <ORGANIZATION> Time-Warner </ORGANIZATION> merger resulted from <ORGANIZATION> Time </ORGANIZATION>'s long-term business strategy and that <ORGANIZATION> Paramount </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Time </ORGANIZATION> shareholders, who are also trying to stop the merger, had not proved they possessed a right to interfere with the transaction. Paramount claimed in its brief that <PERSON> Allen </PERSON>'s decision would allow <ORGANIZATION> Time </ORGANIZATION> to proceed although the merger _ and <ORGANIZATION> Time </ORGANIZATION>'s long-term strategy _ would cost <ORGANIZATION> Time </ORGANIZATION> shareholders the financial benefits of the $ 200-a-share Paramount bid. Time responded that the state <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> itself noted, in a 1985 case involving <ORGANIZATION> Unocal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> and takeover strategist <PERSON> T. </PERSON> <PERSON> Boone </PERSON> <PERSON> Pickens </PERSON>, that `` there is substantial evidence that director resistance to hostile bids, even at a premium over market price, tends in the long run to enhance market prices.'' The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> also has stated that `` ` a board of directors is not a passive instrumentality' even in matters of fundamental corporate change,'' and that directors are allowed and even obligated to take steps to protect shareholder interests in the face of a tender offer, <ORGANIZATION> Time </ORGANIZATION> contended. <LOCATION> Delaware </LOCATION>'s highest court will hear the case Monday, and the justices could rule at any time after arguments are concluded. Time's $ 70-a-share tender offer for <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION> is scheduled to expire at 5 p.m. Monday. Paramount charged in its brief that <PERSON> Allen </PERSON> used improperly used standards for director actions set in the Unocal case, but <ORGANIZATION> Time </ORGANIZATION> said the judge's decision was `` unquestionably the product of an orderly and logical deductive process.'' Time said further there was support for the board's actions in a case arising from the takeover battle for <ORGANIZATION> Macmillan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> last year. The case allowed a board to use several criteria in refusing to entertain offers that threaten corporate policy, including a firm's long-term plans, <ORGANIZATION> Time </ORGANIZATION> said Nothing in the <PERSON> Macmillan </PERSON> decision `` suggests that these criteria _ particularly ` long-term strategic' plans _ become inoperative in the face of an all-cash, all-shares tender offer,'' Time said. Time stock closed up $ 1.37 -LCB- a share to close at $ 139.37 -LCB- in <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGAN