<FIRST>s f BC-AirAuditor Adv23   07-20 0859</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Air Auditor, Adv 23,0888</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv23</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release Sunday July 23 and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Increasing Travel Costs Targeted by Accounting Firm</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto planned</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HERBERT G. McCANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Business-trip costs can send corporate travel managers through the roof, but a big accounting firm says its new computer software package can help put employees on the road for less. New York-based Price Waterhouse is marketing Air Auditor, an <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION> personal computer compatible software program that keeps track of the schedules and air fares offered by domestic airlines. <PERSON> Alan </PERSON> <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Miles </PERSON>, manager of Price Waterhouse's <ORGANIZATION> Travel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Management </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Consulting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION>, says the $ 1,500-Air Auditor package can be used to plan an employee's itinerary or confirm the lowest fare. The software also can control future travel costs when information on the company's travel policies are stored in Air Auditor's database. Class of service, connecting flights, ground transporation, airline preference and other information can be evaluated by the software to give a company the lowest possible cost for any travel itinerary, <PERSON> Miles </PERSON> said. Although in use only a few months, Air Auditor is getting good reviews. `` I think it's doing fine,'' said <PERSON> Nancy </PERSON> <PERSON> Rowley </PERSON>, operations manager of <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> West </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, a regional <ORGANIZATION> Bell </ORGANIZATION> company headquartered in <LOCATION> Denver </LOCATION>. `` It is another tool for us to keep corporate travel costs down.'' Price Waterhouse estimates <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> corporations spent about $ 100 billion last year on travel and entertainment, with about 40 percent on air tickets alone. The accounting firm hopes confusion caused by daily changes in airline fares will increase demand for software it says could reduce corporate travel costs by as much as 25 percent. Under development for three years, Air Auditor originally was created by <ORGANIZATION> Airplan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> System </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, a small <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> software firm. Price Waterhouse worked with the company to refine the program before <PERSON> Airplan </PERSON> was acquired by <ORGANIZATION> System </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> One </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> , </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, an airline reservation system owned by <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> `` Let's say you're flying from <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> and you want to leave around 5 p.m. Air Auditor will show what flights and fares are available and rank those flights and fares to how well they meet company travel policy,'' <PERSON> Miles </PERSON> said. `` It is the same information a travel agent would look at. The computer deciphers it for you so you do n't have to be a trained travel agent to use it.'' Miles said corporate ignorance has created problems selling the software. `` Most companies are like we once were,'' he said. `` They do n't know how much is being spent on travel, so they do n't know what can be saved. Price Waterhouse estimated three years ago it was spending $ 35 million a year on travel but later discovered the actual cost exceeded $ 42 million. Part of the reason, <PERSON> Miles </PERSON> said, was `` we had a hundred different offices using 500 different travel agencies.'' He said the company instituted a travel policy that used only one travel agent and required `` the lowest logical fare,'' forcing employees to travel economy class. But the company also put a value on the traveler's time. `` We wo n't look for a cheap fare that would have the traveler spending three hours in <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION> waiting for a connection,'' he said. `` This year we hope to reduce travel expenses by $ 6 million to $ 7 million.'' Travel agents are n't offended having their customers looking over their shoulders with Air Auditor. `` These systems are developed to meet a need,'' said <PERSON> Stephanie </PERSON> <PERSON> Maxson </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Society </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Travel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agents </ORGANIZATION>, a trade association in <LOCATION> Alexandria </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Va. </LOCATION> `` Corporations are asking for more information about fares.'' Ms. <PERSON> Maxson </PERSON> said it's common for agents to be questioned about why they did n't take advantage of a special promotion. `` A lot of corporate travel officers do n't read the fine print,'' she said. `` The program will help them wade through all the restrictions.'' Ms. <PERSON> Rowley </PERSON> noted that <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> West </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communiciations </ORGANIZATION> spends about $ 25 million on corporate travel. `` It does n't exclude us from using other means of reducing travel costs,'' she said. `` It is just another tool.'' She said that in checking fares through Air Auditor, the company has discovered only a few instances where the travel agent failed to find the cheapest fare. But she said the software is still useful. `` I do n't know if we will ever get to the point of not using it,'' she said. `` It is an ongoing tool to verify that our employees are getting the lowest fares.'' Air Auditor also is used by some airport authorities to determine whether the fares offered by airlines are competitive with other airports within driving distance. <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Miller </PERSON>, assistant director of the <ORGANIZATION> Greater </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Peoria </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airport </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Authority </ORGANIZATION>, says he wants to ensure that fares offered by airlines serving <LOCATION> Peoria </LOCATION>'s airport are competitive to those offered in <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Louis </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>. `` When prices get out of line, we contact the airlines and tell them we noted that fares might be higher in a particular market,'' said <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Miller </PERSON>, assistant director of the <ORGANIZATION> Greater </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Peoria </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airport </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Authority </ORGANIZATION>, who worries about competition from the airports in <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Louis </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>. `` We ask for explanation, and if it is not satisfactory ask that they be lowered.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End adv for Sunday July 23</NOTE>
