<HEAD>Brunswick to Cut 4,000 Jobs Nationwide</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Brunswick </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> says it will cut the jobs of 4,000 workers _ about 20 percent of its employees _ from its troubled marine operations because of a sharp drop in demand for pleasure boats and engines. Workers will be laid off at more than 30 plants in 28 states, <ORGANIZATION> Brunswick </ORGANIZATION> said Wednesday, announcing an expected 75 percent plunge in second-quarter earnings from record results of $ 68.3 million, or 78 cents a share, in the same quarter a year earlier. The biggest cuts will be at the Skokie-based company's largest facility, a Mercury Marine engine plant in <LOCATION> Fond </LOCATION> <LOCATION> du </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lac </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Wis. </LOCATION>, where 300 workers will be let go, the company said. About 300 were laid off there earlier this year. Projections for the quarter would mark it as the second consecutive period of sinking profits at <LOCATION> Brunswick </LOCATION> because of problems in the marine group, comprised of <ORGANIZATION> Sea </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ray </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Marine </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Mercury </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Marine </ORGANIZATION> and Mercury Powerboat divisions. Profits dived 68 percent in the first quarter to $ 17 million. At the time, the company blamed higher costs of materials, and industry observers cited assembly problems and the practice of selling boats and engines as a unit rather than separately. Chairman <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Reichert </PERSON> said the slumping consumer demand in the second quarter was `` virtually unprecedented'' after record sales in the first quarter. Given the buildup in dealer inventories and the end of the normal selling season, the company said it ca n't predict when and at what level there might be callbacks of laid-off workers. Layoffs are to take place over the next two months. <ORGANIZATION> Brunswick </ORGANIZATION>'s rival, suburban Waukegan-based <ORGANIZATION> Outboard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Marine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, also reported dismal results at the beginning of the month. It projected a 50 percent drop in its third-quarter earnings, blaming its results on decreased demand.
