<HEAD>Report on Employment in EEC Shows Surprising Rise in Jobs</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Community </ORGANIZATION>'s first annual report on employment in the 12-nation trade bloc released Thursday showed a rise of 2.5 million jobs since 1987 instead of a predicted drop of 500,000. EEC Commissioner for Social Affairs, <PERSON> Vasso </PERSON> <PERSON> Papandreou </PERSON>, said that forecasts made by the <PERSON> Cecchini </PERSON> report on the impact of the <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION>'s plans to create a single, borderless market by Dec. 31, 1992 had been `` wrong. But Ms. <PERSON> Papandreou </PERSON> said `` despite the improvements there is still a problem of underemployment'' in the Community. She added that opportunities to find jobs vary substantially from area to area and that employers were slow to recognize that the quality of products in the <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION> was `` linked with the quality of the labor market.'' The report showed that the rate of employment in the <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION> _ that is, the number of people who have a job divided by the number of people of working age _ had dropped to less than 60 percent from 64 percent 20 years ago Ms. <PERSON> Papandreou </PERSON> said this was `` substantially below that in other industrialized parts of the world, the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> and the Scandinavian countries'' where the employment rate is over 70 percent. The report is to be used to set employment policy guidelines and was written, according to Ms. <PERSON> Papandreou </PERSON>, in clear and simple language so that it would be `` widely read by all those concerned with employment at national, regional and local levels in the member states.''
</TEXT>
