<HEAD>Japanese Company To Stop Making Black Doll</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Adds 2 grafs after last pvs, ``In January...'' with background
on minority population in Japan. No pickup.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A Japanese toymaker said today it will stop selling a black inflatable doll with big round eyes and a grass skirt, but the company denied it was acting because critics called the doll racist. <PERSON> Shusuke </PERSON> <PERSON> Kubota </PERSON>, a spokesman for <ORGANIZATION> Takara </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, said it also was discontinuing the use of the doll, named `` Dakko-chan,'' as its corporate symbol. Takara, which also makes `` Transformer'' robots that can be bent and twisted into other objects, is the second Japanese company in less than 10 days to say it is abandoning symbols that critics have called derogatory to blacks. Last week, <ORGANIZATION> Calpis </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Food </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industry </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> said it was discontinuing a 65-year-old trademark portraying a top-hatted black man sipping a drink through a straw because some customers had found it objectionable. But <PERSON> Kubota </PERSON> said <PERSON> Takara </PERSON>'s decision to discontinue `` Dakko-chan'' had no connection with racial issues. `` It's not a black. It represents a Japanese child whose skin has darkened from being out in the sun all summer long,'' he said. Takara has sold 2.4 million of the round-faced dolls, which can cling to an arm or leg and wink as they move, since they were introduced in 1960 and became a big hit, <PERSON> Kubota </PERSON> said. He said <PERSON> Takara </PERSON> had been planning to eliminate the doll for some time but did n't have a hit product to replace it with. That changed with the recent worldwide success of its `` Flower Rock'' toys, <PERSON> Kubota </PERSON> said. The toy consists of a fake flower that wears sunglasses and moves in its pot when music is played nearby. The new toy has been popular among adults as well as children, <PERSON> Kubota </PERSON> said. The mass-circulation newspaper <ORGANIZATION> Mainichi </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Shimbun </ORGANIZATION> said <PERSON> Takara </PERSON> apparently was concerned that criticism of the black doll in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> might hurt `` Flower Rock'' sales. In August 1988, <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Congressional </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Black </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Caucus </ORGANIZATION> criticized <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> for mannequins and dolls which the caucus said stereotyped and degraded blacks by exaggerating their physical features. A department store in <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> removed two black mannequins with distorted features, including huge lips, and <ORGANIZATION> Sanrio </ORGANIZATION>, a major gift manufacturer, stopped producing three dolls with black features. In October, <ORGANIZATION> Kanebo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ltd. </ORGANIZATION> stopped making a brand of chewing gum bearing a face with big round eyes and big lips after receiving a protest from the <ORGANIZATION> African </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, an anti-apartheid group. In January, a Japanese publisher said it would no longer publish `` Little Black Sambo'' books, one of the best-selling children's books in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> for more than 30 years, because of racist connotations <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> has only about 50,000 non-Asian foreign residents among its 120 million population. Government officials, particularly before World War II, frequently emphasized the country's unity and relative racial purity.
