<HEAD>July Soybeans Plummet In Contract's Final Day</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Grain and soybean futures prices were mostly lower in early trading today on the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> with the contract for July delivery of soybeans plummeting on its final day of trading. The July soybean contract, which is at the center of a dispute over a possible market-cornering attempt _ was off 35 -LCB- cents at $ 6.92 a bushel in the first hour of trading. The contract expires at noon Central time. Analysts said thin trading conditions have made the July contract extremely volatile. Traders have been exiting the July soybean market since July 12, following the <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION>'s emergency order requiring them to limit their holdings in the July contract. Some said it appeared that the Italian grain concern <ORGANIZATION> Ferruzzi </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Finanziaria </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> S.p.A. </ORGANIZATION>, the reputed target of the exchange's unusual order, was switching its large position in the July contract into the August contract, possibly setting up another confrontation with the exchange. `` I would n't be surprised if that were probably the case but I have no knowledge that that is the case,'' said <PERSON> Dale </PERSON> <PERSON> Gustafson </PERSON>, an analyst with <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Burnham </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lambert </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc </ORGANIZATION>. In early trading, wheat was unchanged to 2 -RCB- cents lower with the contract for delivery in July at $ 3.87 -RCB- a bushel; corn was -LCB- cent to 2 -RCB- cents lower with July at $ 2.52 a bushel; oats were 3 cents to 4 -LCB- cents lower with July at $ 1.43 -LCB- a bushel; soybeans were 8 cents to 35 -LCB- cents lower with July at $ 6.92 a bushel. Cattle futures were mixed while pork futures were higher in early trading on the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>. Live cattle were .15 cent lower to .08 cent higher with August at 72.67 cents a pound; feeder cattle were unchnaged to .23 cent higher with August at 83.95 cents a pound; hogs were .10 cent to .42 cent higher with July at 48.30 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies were .50 cent to 1.20 cents higher with July at 30.05 cents a pound. Cattle futures settled mixed on Wednesday while pork futures were mostly higher.
