<HEAD>Bankruptcy Judge Makes Ruling Today</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: Leads with 7 new grafs to UPDATE with judge approving $75 million
release, reports of Eastern considering sale of Latin American routes.
Picks up 5th graf pvs, Frank Lorenzo...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARC RICE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A federal bankruptcy judge today approved the release of $ 75 million cash from escrow to <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION>, which the strikebound carrier's creditors indicated should help meet the company's financial needs through the end of the quarter. The Miami-based airline initially had asked <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Bankruptcy Judge <PERSON> Burton </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Lifland </PERSON> for the release of $ 100 million from its creditors, while a committee representing <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> creditors asked for only $ 40 million to be released. However, the parties agreed to the $ 75 million figure and the judge approved it, with the understanding Eastern could request additional funds in the future. Eastern was expected to file a plan for reorganizing with the bankruptcy court by the end of the week. Separately, published reports indicated <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> was prepared to sell Latin American routes and most of its terminal space to <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> because of continuing difficulties in contract negotiations with its striking pilots' union. A memo from Eastern senior vice president <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Matthews </PERSON> to the <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Line </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pilots </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> said the route sale idea would be scrapped if the company reached a contract agreement with the pilots, according to today's editions of The <ORGANIZATION> Sun-Sentinel </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lauderdale </LOCATION> and The <ORGANIZATION> Miami </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Herald </ORGANIZATION>. Eastern spokeswoman <PERSON> Karen </PERSON> <PERSON> Ceremsak </PERSON> said the company would not comment on the report. <PERSON> Al </PERSON> <PERSON> Becker </PERSON>, spokesma