<HEAD>Maine Company Bilked Investors Out of Nearly $30 Million, Feds Say</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 5th graf, `Case Equipment's' with 2 grafs to UPDATE with
comment from company owner. Adds one graf with further comment.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DIRK BEVERIDGE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PORTLAND, Maine (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Investors who believed they could get rich selling T-shirts and bumper stickers were bilked of up to $ 30 million by the company that made the printing equipment, the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> said. The <ORGANIZATION> Case </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Equipment </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> was ordered to temporarily stop making promises about its `` sublicolor'' system, which actually consists of old-fashioned mimeograph machines that were sold for $ 10,000 each. A federal judge also ordered <ORGANIZATION> Case </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Equipment </ORGANIZATION>'s assets frozen while the <ORGANIZATION> FTC </ORGANIZATION> tries to recoup money believed to have been lost by people from all 50 states and <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>. The company's scam cheated `` somewhere between 2,000 and 4,000 people, multiplied by a minimum of $ 10,000 each,'' said <ORGANIZATION> FTC </ORGANIZATION> attorney <PERSON> Sara </PERSON> <PERSON> Greenberg </PERSON>. `` We estimated up to $ 30 million in court papers.'' Case Equipment's owner, <PERSON> Anthony </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Casella </PERSON>, said this morning that his equipment works as advertised. He said customers who made no money using it probably were just not cut out to be in business for themselves. <PERSON> Casella </PERSON> said he had sold about 3,800 of the machines. `` We sell to an awful lot of people who have never been in business before, and they think the equipment is going to make them a millionaire, and that's not true,'' <PERSON> Casella </PERSON> told The <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> in a telephone interview. `` People make themselves millionaires.'' The <ORGANIZATION> FTC </ORGANIZATION> last week asked <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Gene </PERSON> <PERSON> Carter </PERSON> to issue a temporary restraining order against <ORGANIZATION> Case </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Equipment </ORGANIZATION>. Ms. <PERSON> Greenberg </PERSON> said from her <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION> office that <ORGANIZATION> FTC </ORGANIZATION> lawyers plan to return to <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> on Friday to seek a preliminary injunction that would halt the allegedly fraudulent sales until the <ORGANIZATION> FTC </ORGANIZATION>'s civil lawsuit against the company is resolved. `` It's OK if he sells the equipment,'' she said. `` He just has to tell the truth about it. We're seeking restitution for customers, which is plenty. There's your $ 20 million to $ 30 million.'' Case Equipment is also named in a separate lawsuit in <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> in which customers from several states say they were bilked. They are asking for compensatory and punitive damages. Case Equipment has operated in Turner since 1984. Prior to that <PERSON> Casella </PERSON>, also known as A.J. <PERSON> Casella </PERSON> and A.J. Case, abandoned a similar operation in <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> when that state's attorney general's office began investigating complaints, Ms. <PERSON> Greenberg </PERSON> said. She said potential investors were lured to <ORGANIZATION> Case </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Equipment </ORGANIZATION> by national magazine advertisements, flown into <LOCATION> Portland </LOCATION> <LOCATION> International </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jetport </LOCATION> and picked up in limousines that took them to <ORGANIZATION> Case </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Equipment </ORGANIZATION>'s showroom in Turner. They were shown impressive samples of printing and given a sales pitch that said making money with the `` sublicolor'' system would be easy, and that Case Equipment had service centers around the country and long lists of potential customers, Ms. <PERSON> Greenberg </PERSON> said. The customers' living expenses were paid during their visits. `` It's a wine'em and dine'em sort of operation, and the people are impressed,'' Ms. <PERSON> Greenberg </PERSON> said. `` Even people who had some knowledge of the printing industry were taken in. They have told customers stories about how a 15-year-old could use it. They said anyone can use it.'' But once people bought the Case Equipment machinery, they were ignored and given little training in using it, <ORGANIZATION> FTC </ORGANIZATION> documents say. The machinery could not be operated by untrained workers and produced sloppy printing without regular maintenance, the <ORGANIZATION> FTC </ORGANIZATION> said. The company falsely claimed to have service centers all over the nation, when it had none, the <ORGANIZATION> FTC </ORGANIZATION> said. `` Consumers not only lose their initial $ 10,000-plus investment, they spend significant additional sums and valuable time in vain trying to get the equipment to function,'' the <ORGANIZATION> FTC </ORGANIZATION> said. The commission accuses Case Equipment of cheating `` mostly working people looking to start or expand their own small business ventures. However, the only ones to profit have been Case and <PERSON> Casella </PERSON>.'' <PERSON> Casella </PERSON> said the companies that make and distribute his equipment provide numerous service centers. He said his company provides food and lodging to potential customers to make sure they come see what they are buying. He said he insists buyers attend training sessions and sign a form saying they are trained in the use of the sublicolor and satisfied with its performance.
