<HEAD>Textron Earnings Decline</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PROVIDENCE, R.I. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Textron </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> said Thursday its second-quarter earnings declined nearly 14 percent, reflecting an arbitrator's decision that <ORGANIZATION> Textron </ORGANIZATION> owed money to <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> and because of weakness in its aerospace division. The diversified company said it had income of $ 59.3 million, or 67 cents per share, compared with $ 68.9 million, or 78 cents per share, in the 1988 quarter. Revenue was $ 1.85 billion, compared with $ 1.79 billion a year earlier. Earnings were depressed by an arbitrator's ruling that <ORGANIZATION> Textron </ORGANIZATION> owed <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> $ 9.5 million under an agreement to jointly produce helicopters, said company spokesman <PERSON> Raymond </PERSON> <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Caine </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>. <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> had paid for materials in 1978, but they had not been shipped before <ORGANIZATION> Textron </ORGANIZATION> was prohibited by the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> government from providing any further supplies to <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>, he said The aerospace division's earnings decreased nearly $ 2.5 million, primarily because of increased costs on fixed-price development programs for the V-22 Osprey and on some rocket and smart-bomb systems, <PERSON> Caine </PERSON> said. That was offset by an increase of almost $ 10 million in earnings for financial services. <ORGANIZATION> Textron </ORGANIZATION> also recorded a $ 14 million increase in interest expense, mostly from its acquisition of <ORGANIZATION> Avdel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> PLC </ORGANIZATION>, a British fastener manufacturer. <ORGANIZATION> Textron </ORGANIZATION> has been unable to complete the acquisition and absorb the earnings, however, because of <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> opposition. <ORGANIZATION> Textron </ORGANIZATION> has interests in a number of industries including aerospace technology, commercial products and financial services.
