<HEAD>Schlumberger Reports Decline In Second-Quarter Earnings</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Schlumberger </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ltd. </ORGANIZATION> said Thursday its second-quarter profit declined 12 percent in the second quarter, partly reflecting a decline in oil rig activity and oil-price uncertainty. For the three months ended June 30, the oil exploration company had after-tax earnings of $ 127 million, or 53 cents a share, down from $ 144 million, or 53 cents a share, in the 1988 period. Operating revenue totaled $ 1.20 billion, down 5 percent from $ 1.26 billion in the comparable 1988 period. <ORGANIZATION> Schlumberger </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Evan </PERSON> <PERSON> Baird </PERSON> said earnings-per-share remained unchanged in the quarter because of fewer shares outstanding as a result of the company buying 34.5 million shares in 1988 for $ 1.2 billion. The quarterly results included one-time gains of $ 13 million, or 5 cents a share, from the sale of <ORGANIZATION> Schlumberger </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Systems </ORGANIZATION> businesses and $ 22 million, or 9 cents a share, from an award by the Iran-U.S. Claims Tribunal. In the previous year, the compnay has a one-time $ 35 million increase in from the sale of a division. The company's oil field services revenue was 3 percent lower as crude prices continued to decline from April levels. For the first six months of the year, the New York-based energy concern had net income of $ 209 million, or 88 cents a share, down 14.7 percent from $ 245 million, or 90 cents a share, in the 1988 period. Operating revenue was $ 2.4 billion, down 5 percent from $ 2.5 billion in the same year-ago period.
