<HEAD>FCC Approves Sale of NY Radio Station</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAY ARNOLD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communications </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> said Thursday it has approved a $ 25.5 million sale of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> talk radio station WOR-AM to Buckley-WOR <ORGANIZATION> Broadcasting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp </ORGANIZATION>. Under the FCC-approved settlement, the seller, <ORGANIZATION> RKO </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, would receive only 65 percent of the proceeds, with the remainder going to six other applicants who had challenged the fitness of RKO and its parent, <ORGANIZATION> GenCorp </ORGANIZATION>. of <LOCATION> Fairlawn </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>, to hold the WOR license. The other applicants were: <ORGANIZATION> South </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Jersey </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Radio </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Atlantic </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.J. </LOCATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Freedom </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Broadcasting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Riverside </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> R.I. </LOCATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Women </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Owning </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Radio </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, whose principals include broadcaster <PERSON> Gail </PERSON> <PERSON> Trell </PERSON> <PERSON> Barker </PERSON> and TV-radio personality <PERSON> Arlene </PERSON> <PERSON> Francis </PERSON>; <ORGANIZATION> COZZIN </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communications </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Cleveland </LOCATION>, which numbers comedian-actor <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Cosby </PERSON> among its stockholders; S-G Communications of <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION>; and <ORGANIZATION> Magna </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Media </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp </ORGANIZATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> FCC </ORGANIZATION>, in a 2-1 decision on July 14 that was released Thursday, said <ORGANIZATION> RKO </ORGANIZATION>'s license renewal application would be dismissed and RKO will transfer the station to S-G Communications. S-G will transfer the license to an RKO subsidiary, GRADH-107, which in turn will transfer the license to <PERSON> Buckley </PERSON> upon consummation of the settlement. The <LOCATION> Greenwich </LOCATION>, Conn.-based <PERSON> Buckley </PERSON> will pay RKO $ 24 million, of which <ORGANIZATION> RKO </ORGANIZATION> will pay $ 7.425 million to the other applicants. <PERSON> Buckley </PERSON> also will pay $ 1.5 million, in addition to the $ 24 million, directly to principals of the competing applicants. The <ORGANIZATION> FCC </ORGANIZATION> said `` RKO's receipt of less than full market value for the station would serve as an effective deterrent against license misconduct.'' The sale was the latest step in the FCC-ordered dismantling of the RKO network, which began in the 1960s when challenges were filed to RKO's fitness to operate its stations. In a 1980 ruling that stripped RKO of one TV license, the <ORGANIZATION> FCC </ORGANIZATION> noted that <ORGANIZATION> GenCorp </ORGANIZATION>, the former <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tire </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Rubber </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, had been accused of improper domestic political contributions and of bribery overseas. The FCC has approved similar sales agreements for <ORGANIZATION> WOR </ORGANIZATION>'s sister station, <ORGANIZATION> WRKS-FM </ORGANIZATION>, for $ 50 million; <ORGANIZATION> KHJ-TV </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> KRTH-AM-FM </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>, $ 320 million and $ 86.6 million, respectively; plus WHBQ-AM, <LOCATION> Memphis </LOCATION>; WGMS-AM, <LOCATION> Bethesda </LOCATION>, Md.; WGMS-FM, <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>; and WRKO-AM-FM, <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION>.
