<HEAD>Bristol-Myers, Colgate-Palmolive Post Double-Digit Quarterly Income
Gains</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: UPDATES thruout with American Brands results.</HEAD>
<HEAD>Precede NEW YORK BC</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Bristol-Myers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Colgate-Palmolive </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>. Thursday reported they had double-digit income growth in the second quarter despite suffering adverse consequences from the dollar's strength <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Brands </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, meanwhile, reported its net income fell 22 percent despite a strong performance by its tobacco units. Bristol-Myers, maker of medicines, toiletries and household products, posted an 11.6 percent profit increase in the quarter ended June 30. After-tax income rose to $ 212.51 million, or 74 cents a share, from $ 190.48 million, or 66 cents a shares, in 1988's second quarter. Sales came to $ 1.53 billion vs. last year's $ 1.46 billion, an increase of about 5 percent. <ORGANIZATION> Colgate-Palmolive </ORGANIZATION>, a major manufacturer of consumer products ranging from soap to pet food, said its second-quarter net income increased 12.4 percent to $ 73.6 million, or $ 1.06 a share, from $ 65.5 million, or 96 cents a share, in the second 1988 quarter. Sales rose about 9 percent to $ 1.29 billion from $ 1.19 billion. <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Brands </ORGANIZATION>, whose products include Lucky Strike cigarettes and <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Beam </PERSON> alcoholic beverages, said its profit sank to $ 120.2 million, or $ 1.25 a share, from $ 154.7 million, or $ 1.57 a share, in the year-ago quarter. Revenue edged up 0.1 percent to $ 2.722 billion, from $ 2.718 billion. <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Brands </ORGANIZATION>, based in <LOCATION> Greenwich </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Conn. </LOCATION>, said its 1988 results included a $ 46 million gain from discontinued operations. <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gelb </PERSON>, Bristol-Myers' chairman, said international sales edged up just 1 percent while, domestically, sales were up 7 percent. Changes in the dollar's value against other major currencies during the quarter cut international sales by an estimated 6 percent, <PERSON> Gelb </PERSON> said. For the first half of the year, <ORGANIZATION> Bristol-Myers </ORGANIZATION> earned $ 449.6 million, or $ 1.56 a share, up 12.1 percent from $ 401.1 million, or $ 1.39 a share, a year earlier. Sales amounted to $ 3.14 billion, up about 5 percent from $ 2.98 billion in the first six months of 1988. <PERSON> Reuben </PERSON> <PERSON> Mark </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Colgate-Palmolive </ORGANIZATION>'s chairman, president and chief executive officer, said the financial improvement reflected continuing momentum in international operations and the <PERSON> Hill </PERSON>'s Pet Products division. The second-quarter earning included $ 6.5 million, or 9 cents a share, from the sale of land in <LOCATION> England </LOCATION>. This real estate gain partially offsetthe negative impact of a higher dollar. <ORGANIZATION> Colgate-Palmolive </ORGANIZATION> said in a news release that the dollar's strength, combined with economic difficulties in <LOCATION> Venezuela </LOCATION> and currency translation losses in other hyperinflationary countries, reduced second-quarter income by about $ 13 million, after taxes For the first six months of this year, <ORGANIZATION> Colgate-Palmolive </ORGANIZATION> earned $ 140.8 million, or $ 2.04 a share, up 7.6 percent from $ 130.9 million, or $ 1.91 a share, in the first half of 1988. Sales grew about 7 percent to $ 2.5 billion from $ 2.3 billion. Both Colgate-Palmolive and Bristol-Myers have their corporate headquarters in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. Some of <ORGANIZATION> Colgate-Palmolive </ORGANIZATION>'s well-known brands include <ORGANIZATION> Ajax </ORGANIZATION> cleanser, Fab laundry detergent and Irish Spring soap. Among Bristol-Myers' brands are Bufferin and Excedrin pain relievers,