<HEAD>Quarterly Net Drops Nearly 5 Percent</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> PPG </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industries </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> said Thursday weakness in its glass business and unfavorable currency exchange rates led to a 4.8 percent drop in second-quarter profit. The company earned $ 127.3 million, or $ 1.13 per share, in the second quarter compared with $ 133.8 million, or $ 1.22 per share, a year earlier. Sales for the comparable quarters edged higher by 2.7 percent from $ 1.45 billion to $ 1.49 billion. `` Despite the slowing <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> economy, we are optimistic that 1989 will rank among PPG's best years for both sales and earnings,'' Chairman <PERSON> Vincent </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Sarni </PERSON> said in a statement. First-half net earnings totaled $ 257.1 million, or $ 2.28 per share, up 1.9 percent from $ 252.4 million, or $ 2.29 per share, a year earlier. Six-month sales rose 4.6 percent from $ 2.82 billion to $ 2.95 billion. PPG said it benefited in the second quarter from continued strong sales of fiber glass products and auto replacement glass. It was hurt, however, by high product development costs and softness in North American markets. New production capacity in the <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> and European flat glass industry lowered sales volumes for some products, <ORGANIZATION> PPG </ORGANIZATION> said. Sales of <ORGANIZATION> PPG </ORGANIZATION>'s paints and other coatings were strong worldwide. In its chemicals business, chlor-alkali sales volumes and prices remained strong, but markets showed weakness for chlorine derivatives.
