<HEAD>Multimedia Reports Higher Earnings in Second Quarter</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GREENVILLE, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Multimedia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> said Thursday its second-quarter earnings rose 31 percent, spurred by the success of television programming such as the <PERSON> Phil </PERSON> <PERSON> Donahue </PERSON> and <PERSON> Sally </PERSON> <PERSON> Jessy </PERSON> <PERSON> Raphael </PERSON> shows. Revenues rose 6 percent overall, including gains in its newspaper, broadcasting, cable and entertainment divisions, the company said. Multimedia reported earnings of $ 10.8 million, or 87 cents a share, on revenues of $ 121 million for the quarter ending June 30. During the same period in 1988, the company earned $ 8.2 million, or 67 cents a share, on revenues of $ 114.3 million. Revenues from the entertainment division rose 21 percent, to $ 19.2 million, up from $ 15.8 million. The three other divisions each reported revenues increases of less than 10 percent. The broadcasting division accounted for $ 39.5 million of the company's second-quarter revenues. Newspapers brought in $ 35 million and cablevision $ 19.2 million. First-half earnings climbed 65 percent from $ 9.3 million, or 77 cents a share, to $ 15.4 million, or $ 1.24 a share. Revenues rose 6 percent in the first six months from $ 214.3 million to $ 227.3 million. `` The quarter and the first six months were as expected,'' said <PERSON> Walter </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Bartlett </PERSON>, president and chief executive officer. `` Newspapers were weak in retail advertising. Broadcasting was good, fortunately, because of our two major <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION> properties in <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Louis </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Cincinnati </LOCATION>. `` Cable was very strong and entertainment was very strong due to the continued success of <PERSON> Donahue </PERSON> and the expansion of the <PERSON> Sally </PERSON> <PERSON> Jessy </PERSON> <PERSON> Raphael </PERSON> show to more markets and to an hour in length.'' The gain in first-half earnings was the result of higher revenue and less interest payments on a recapitalization project that began in 1985, <PERSON> Bartlett </PERSON> said in a statement. Multimedia is a mediacommunications company that publishes 14 daily and 40 non-daily newspapers. It also owns and operates four television and seven radio stations, more than 100 cable franchises in four states and produces and syndicates television programming, including the <PERSON> Phil </PERSON> <PERSON> Donahue </PERSON> and <PERSON> Sally </PERSON> <PERSON> Jessy </PERSON> <PERSON> Raphael </PERSON> shows.
