<HEAD>Pork Belly Futures Soar On Signs Of Stronger Demand</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 Pork belly futures prices soared Thursday by as much as 2 cents a pound, the permitted daily limit on the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, on signs that lower bacon prices may finally be stimulating demand for the sizeable supplies of pork bellies in cold storage. Hog futures prices also rose while cattle futures were mixed. On other markets, orange juice futures fell sharply for the fifth straight day; grains and soybeans finished mixed as the July contracts expired; precious metals erased some of Wednesday's losses; and energy futures advanced Frozen pork bellies settled 1.53 cents to 2 cents higher with the contract for delivery in July at 30.55 cents a pound; hogs were .03 cent lower to .98 cent higher with July at 49 cents a pound; live cattle were unchanged to .20 cent higher with August at 72.75 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .22 cent lower to .07 cent higher with August at 83.72 cents a pound. The pork-belly market turned in its strongest performance in more than six weeks in a delayed reponse to Tuesday's weekly exchange report on pork-belly stocks in <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> commercial freezers outside of <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>. The report showed a net out-movement of nearly 5.4 million pounds last week compared to 3.9 million pounds for the same period a year ago. Supplies of frozen pork bellies, the part of the pig from which bacon is made, are at near-record levels. Stocks normally decline during the summer, due to a seasonal drop in hog slaughters, but reports since spring have failed to confirm the development of the trend this year. The slack demand has prompted grocers to sharply cut retail prices for bacon, which has been running 8 percent to 20 percent below last year for most of the summer, said <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Morgan </PERSON>, president of <ORGANIZATION> Sterling </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZ