ents lower at $ 2.47 -LCB- a bushel; July oats expired 3 cents lower at $ 1.43 -LCB- a bushel. Wheat settled 3 cents to 6 -LCB- cents higher with September at $ 3.97 -RCB- a bushel; corn was 2 cents lower to -LCB- cent higher with September at $ 2.40 a bushel; oats were 2 -LCB- cents to 3 cents lower with September at $ 1.51 \ a bushel; soybeans were 6 \ cents lower to 4 -LCB- cents higher with August at $ 6.81 \ Gold and silver rebounded on <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>'s Commodity Exchange in reaction to a weaker dollar, partially erasing Wednesday's losses. Gold settled $ 2.90 to $ 3.10 higher with August at $ 372.20 a troy ounce; silver was 1.4 cents to 2.8 cents higher with July at $ 5.181 a troy ounce. Energy futures prices advanced on the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> in a technically inspired rally following a sharp decline on Wednesday. West Texas Intermediate crude oil settled 5 cents to 23 cents higher with August at $ 19.90 a barrel; heating oil was .98 cent to 1.56 cents higher with August at 51.83 cents a gallon; unleaded gasoline was .89 cent lower to .56 cent higher with August at 53.80 cents a gallon.
