<HEAD>Heating Oil Prices Higher, Other Energy Futures Mixed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Wholesale home heating oil prices rose Thursday amid expectations of energy supply shortages overseas due to the labor and ethnic unrest in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>. Crude oil and unleaded gasoline futures were mixed. On the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, No. 2 heating oil for August delivery rose 1.46 cents to 51.83 cents a gallon, after falling 0.13 cent on Wednesday Contracts for heating oil delivery in more distant months also posted gains and the September contract rose 1.56 cents, settling at 52.57 cents a gallon. Among other refined products traded on the exchange, the August contract of unleaded gasoline declined 0.59 cent to 54.10 cents a gallon, adding to Wednesday's drop of 1.37 cents. Other unleaded gasoline contract months settled with moderate gains and losses, with the September contract falling 0.29 cent to 53.08 cents a gallon. West Texas Intermediate crude oil for August delivery settled 5 cents higher at $ 19.90 per 42-gallon barrel on the last trading day for that contract. The September contract for the benchmark grade of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> crude oil rose 13 cents to $ 19.68 a barrel. <PERSON> Evan </PERSON> <PERSON> Baron </PERSON>, of the energy group at <ORGANIZATION> Elders </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Futures </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, said continuing troubles in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> which have disrupted production in various industries `` is creating tight supplies in <LOCATION> European </LOCATION> heating oil markets right now and that, in turn, is affecting our markets.'' He said there have been reports that scheduled oil shipments from the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> have not moved. News that saboteurs in the country's <LOCATION> Abkhazia </LOCATION> region have damaged the electric power system added to speculation that the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> will need to keep more of its oil at home to compensate for energy shortages due to strikes at coal mines.
