<HEAD>Bevill, Bresler Felons Rebuild Lives</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANIEL J. WAKIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEWARK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 One man helps run a restaurant on the <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION> shore after cleaning toilets in jail. Another solicited companies as a consultant on business ethics. A third maintains a 4.0 grade point average studying for an MBA at a prison camp. A fourth just sold his horse transporting business and the fifth, serving a six-year prison term, is scheduled to be sentenced Monday for lying on the witness stand at trial. Those are the lives of five former wealthy exectives of <PERSON> Bevill </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Bresler </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Schulman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, once <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION>'s largest brokerage house. All have gone to jail for crimes in connection with the April 1985 collapse of the <PERSON> Livingston </PERSON> firm and related entities. The collapse has cost customers _ which include more than 75 financial institutions, municipalities and individuals in 20 states _ more than $ 100 million. Authorities have said the executives siphoned off $ 15 million for personal use. Half-million-dollar homes, jewelry, boats, investments, furs, <ORGANIZATION> Mercedes-Benz </ORGANIZATION> autos belonging to the defendants are long gone now, seized by trustees overseeing the former firm's assets. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Bevill </PERSON>, 46, was the firm's chairman. He is scheduled for release July 27 from a federal prison camp at <ORGANIZATION> Maxwell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Base </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Montgomery </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ala. </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Bevill </PERSON> will have served slightly more than 21 months of a sentence that began on Black Monday, the Oct. 19, 1987, stock market crash `` I feel guilty, I feel shameful _ wish I could make it go away,'' <PERSON> Bevill </PERSON> said in a telephone interview from prison. <PERSON> Bevill </PERSON>'s grade-point average is a perfect 4.0 in business courses from <ORGANIZATION> Troy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> He said he is considering taking a job managing apartment complexes in <LOCATION> Tennessee </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Alabama </LOCATION> owned by his brother. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Rooney </PERSON>, the former treasurer at <PERSON> Bevill </PERSON>, <PERSON> Bresler </PERSON>, cleaned bathrooms at the federal prison in <LOCATION> Allenwood </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Pa. </LOCATION>, during his 1 -LCB- - year prison term The 43-year-old <PERSON> Rooney </PERSON> called the experience `` very humbling'' in a letter to <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Dickinson </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Debevoise </PERSON>. Several miles from the <LOCATION> Monmouth </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Beach </LOCATION> condominium he once owned, <PERSON> Rooney </PERSON> now works as as a bookkeeper at a restaurant in which his mother made an investment. He prefers not to discuss his life or the case in detail. `` I feel better about things,'' <PERSON> Rooney </PERSON> said. `` I'm trying to start my life all over again. It's behind me.'' He is working on a unique part of the sentence imposed by <PERSON> Debevoise </PERSON> on the four defendants who pleaded guilty and cooperated with the government: to read six books about `` suffering and afflicted'' people and write reports in the form of a syllabus and description of a possible college course on social ethics. <PERSON> Stuart </PERSON> <PERSON> Gottlieb </PERSON>, a former senior vice president at the firm, was sentenced to nine months in prison. He is trying to parlay the book-reading assignment into a new business _ using his status as a white-collar criminal to solicit corporations for a course or manual on business ethics. `` I am now extremely devoted to attempting to prevent others, because of unethical behavior, from placing themselves, their firms or society at large, at risk,'' <PERSON> Gottlieb </PERSON>, 42, says in his solicitation letter. <PERSON> Gottlieb </PERSON>, living in a rented condomimium in <LOCATION> Pluckemin </LOCATION>, would only say in an interview, `` It's behind me. It's over.'' <PERSON> Gottlieb </PERSON> for a time worked at a video rental store, according to assistant <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Attorney <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Weissman </PERSON>. The store was transferred to his wife's name, but was padlocked by the <LOCATION> Morris </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> sheriff and its assets sold at auction March 27 after a video distributor obtained a judgment for unpaid debts. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Levine </PERSON>, 46, former executive vice president, said he sold his <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> horse carrying business in the past several weeks because `` it just was n't worthwhile.'' The trustee settlement had left him and his family about $ 770,000 in assets. At <LOCATION> Allenwood </LOCATION>, where he served three months, <PERSON> Levine </PERSON> washed dishes. <PERSON> Gilbert </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Schulman </PERSON>, 42, the firm's former president, was convicted, sentenced to eight years and had the term reduced to six. He pleaded guilty to a later charge of giving perjured testimony. He is to be sentenced by <PERSON> Debevoise </PERSON> on Monday. <PERSON> Schulman </PERSON>'s later cooperation helped bring about the guilty plea of <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> A. Rough, a former director of the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION>, to charges of leaking secret interest rate data to the <PERSON> Bevil