<HEAD>CBOT Chairman Defends Emergency Order on Soybeans</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Ledes with 13 new grafs to update with Chicago Board of Trade
chairman's testimony, picks up with 7th graf pvs: CFTC Chairwoman ...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN M. DOYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> took its emergency action in the soybean futures market last week after federal regulators took steps against a single concern, the <ORGANIZATION> CBOT </ORGANIZATION>'s chairman testified Thursday. Chairman <PERSON> Karsten </PERSON> <PERSON> Mahlman </PERSON> would not identify the `` major participant,'' believed to be Italian agribusiness giant <ORGANIZATION> Feruzzi </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> SpA </ORGANIZATION>, which took a massive position in July soybean futures. <PERSON> Mahlman </PERSON> said the <ORGANIZATION> CBOT </ORGANIZATION> board voted the emergency order, which required liquidation of large positions in the July bean futures market, after determining that only one board member, who was excused from the meeting and did not vote, owned or controlled positions in July soybeans. `` We hope our strong action in July will not be necessary in August,'' <PERSON> Mahlman </PERSON> told reporters after testifying before a <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> subcommittee. Although he conceded, under repeated questioning by Rep. <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Nagle </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Iowa </LOCATION>, that several other board members were employed by companies that controlled or served customers that controlled soybean positions, <PERSON> Mahlman </PERSON> defended the <ORGANIZATION> CBOT </ORGANIZATION>'s action. Outside the hearing room, he said: `` I think we have dramatically enhanced the credibility of the board.'' <PERSON> Mahlman </PERSON> said eliminating all board members with employer links to futures positions would force about one-third of them to resign. <PERSON> Mahlman </PERSON>'s version of the emergency order differed from that given by federal regulators earlier this week. The hearings are being conducted on proposed legislation that would tighten anti-fraud rules and also reauthorize the agency that regulates futures markets, the Commodity Futures Trading Commission. In earlier testimony, the head of another <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> exchange said <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> should not ban the controversial practice of dual trading _ where brokers trade for themselves and their customers. Critics say dual trading allows brokers to take care of their own needs first, but banning it outright `` would be dangerous,'' said <PERSON> Leo </PERSON> <PERSON> Melamed </PERSON>, chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>'s executive committee <PERSON> Mahlman </PERSON> concurred with that position. In a prepared statement submitted to the subcommittee, <PERSON> Mahlman </PERSON>, chairman of the world's oldest and largest futures exchange, also opposed a ban on dual trading, saying it `` will adversely affect the liquidity of futures markets, particularly agricultural markets, by increasing the cost of doing business. The <ORGANIZATION> CBOT </ORGANIZATION>'s emergency order last week, and federal regulators' reaction to the order was a hot topic during a subcommittee session on Tuesday <ORGANIZATION> CFTC </ORGANIZATION> Chairwoman <PERSON> Wendy </PERSON> <PERSON> Gramm </PERSON> exasperated committee members Tuesday with her cautious answers to questions about the agency's consulting role in the <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> soybean situation Ms. <PERSON> Gramm </PERSON>, who also said more study was needed before dual trading was banned, said her agency was reviewing the <ORGANIZATION> CBOT </ORGANIZATION>'s emergency order but neither directly approved or disapproved the action Subcommittee Chairman <PERSON> Glenn </PERSON> English, <LOCATION> D-Okla </LOCATION>., alluded to his frustration with the <ORGANIZATION> CFTC </ORGANIZATION> at the start of the second session when he said the congressmen present `` want to get complete answers instead of the ones they got Tuesday. The proposed bill, sponsored by English and the subcommittee's ranking Republican, <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Coleman </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Missouri </LOCATION>, would allow dual trading in only certain circumstances including futures that have an average daily trading volume of less than 7,000 contracts But <PERSON> Melamed </PERSON>, the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> official, said dual trading was needed to maintain liquidity when there are few customer orders. He added that pegging dual trading permissibility to volume ignores the monthly idiosyncracies of various markets such as soybeans, cattle, oil or gold. On the other hand, <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Josserand </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cattlemen </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, advocated complete elimination of dual trading to restore public confidence.
