<HEAD>Admitted Inside Trader Starts Consulting Practice</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Dennis </PERSON> <PERSON> B. </PERSON> <PERSON> Levine </PERSON>, the admitted inside trader whose confessions spawned Wall Street's scandals, told a group of business students Thursday he has started a financial consulting practice in mergers and acquisitions. On other matters, <PERSON> Levine </PERSON> praised the performance of government investigators as `` phenomenal,'' said the criminal justice system treated him fairly, criticized the media's portrayal of him as greedy, and expressed remorse for breaking the law. `` In my case, the combination of inexperience, unbridled ambition, impatience and gross errors of judgment led me to break the law,'' <PERSON> Levine </PERSON> told about 100 students and faculty at <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>'s business school. `` I blame myself and make no excuses and take full responsibility for my actions,'' he said. <PERSON> Levine </PERSON>, 36, who was not paid to speak at <ORGANIZATION> NYU </ORGANIZATION>, traced his involvement in a network of securities trading that used illegally obtained information about pending corporate takeovers to net $ 11.6 million in illicit profits. <PERSON> Levine </PERSON>, a managing director at <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Burnham </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lambert </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> when he was charged in May 1986, said his illicit activities included a network of code names, foreign corporations and overseas bank accounts. `` In a vastly different environment, when I made the decision to cross the line I did n't think about getting caught,'' he said. `` I was a wet-behind-the-ears naive rookie who should have known better but did n't.'' Answering a student's question, <PERSON> Levine </PERSON> said that since his parole he has started a financial consulting practice and fought civil lawsuits he said have sought $ 1 billion in claims. `` I believe as a result of my prosecution and others the insider trading has declined,'' he said, adding that people who try that kind of activity today `` are playing Russian roulette.'' In a plea bargain with prosecutors, <PERSON> Levine </PERSON> pleaded guilty to four felonies, was fined $ 362,000 and returned $ 11.6 million in illegal profits. He also told the government about <PERSON> Ivan </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Boesky </PERSON>, the now-imprisoned insider trader who himself made millions of dollars using information supplied by <PERSON> Levine </PERSON>. <PERSON> Levine </PERSON> was paroled last September from a two-year prison term for securities fraud, tax evasion and perjury.
