<HEAD>EPA Chief Says President's Clean Air Bill Will Be `Faithful'</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 13 grafs to UPDATE; picks up 5th graf pvs, `In contrast
...,'' DELETES now-redundant last graf pvs.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY MARGASAK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Last-minute changes in the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration's clean air bill would ease up on requirements to reduce motor vehicle pollution and let the government push back cleanup deadlines, according to an administration summary made available Thursday. The changes were made after a June 30 draft became public and was widely criticized by environmentalists as not living up to what President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> promised on June 12. The <ORGANIZATION> Environmental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Protection </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> summary was given to members of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> on Thursday, a day before President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> was to hold a White House ceremony to formally present the bill to lawmakers. Members of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> gave the summary to reporters. After studying the summary, the head of an environmental group coalition, <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Ayres </PERSON>, said the bill would allow `` chicanery and fraud'' by industry and permit an <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> administrator so inclined to wreck the effort to clean the nation's dirty air. <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> Administrator <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Reilly </PERSON>, however, told reporters earlier the bill was `` faithful in every respect'' to the program <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> outlined on June 12 to fix the nation's air pollution problem. `` There are no games,'' he said, indismissing the environmentalist criticism as `` inevitable pre-positioning'' on the legislation. `` Today's draft is far weaker than last month's draft, which was far weaker than the president's promises,'' said Rep. <PERSON> Henry </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Waxman </PERSON>, chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> environment subcommittee, which will hold the first hearing on <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s bill Monday. `` It undercuts the clean fuel program, pushes back compliance deadlines and loosens emissions standards. The bill actually appears to allow emissions from cars and trucks to increase from today's levels,'' <PERSON> Waxman </PERSON> said. Some of the changes: _ New buses in cities of more than 1 million population would be required to use special clean-burning fuels, starting in 1991-1994 The earlier draft required them in all cities of 250,000 or larger. The final bill also would permit the <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> to delay the requirement for two years. _ The <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> administrator could postpone for two years a clean fuel program for automobiles that would have to be sold in the nation's most polluted cities in _ The deadline for all cars to meet new emissions standards for hydrocarbons and nitrogen oxides was pushed back from 1994 models to 1995 models _ Tougher emissions standards for light trucks could be phased in from 1993 to 1995 instead of being required by 1993 _ Criminal penalities against automakers for violating the anti-pollution standards were dropped In contrast to the environmental groups' vocal comments, industry has lobbied quietly, telling the administration _ and repeating to reporters who asked _ that the legislation has become too strict on business. A group of Republicans who appeared with <PERSON> Reilly </PERSON> Thursday praised the bill, but kept repeating that the legislation was n't perfect, lacking tough cleanup timetables. `` The package does not pass all the tests,'' said Rep. <PERSON> Sherwood </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Boehlert </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-N.Y. </LOCATION>, who added that the bill would have been better if <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> and <PERSON> Reilly </PERSON> had written it alone. The <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Management </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Budget </ORGANIZATION> reportedly fought often during the drafting of the bill, according to government sources who spoke only on condition they not be named. The sources said the <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> generally took the environmentalists side. Rep. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Smith </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-N.H. </LOCATION>, said he would co-sponsor the legislation, but believed it needed tougher provisions for some industrial boilers, more incentives for utilities to pursue energy conservation, more specifics on reducing air toxics emissions and consideration of tougher provisions to reduce emissions of a contributor to smog _ nitrogen oxide. The environmentalists' criticism has included these points: sulfur dioxide emissions would be reduced less than originally indicated in the acid rain section; proposed fleet-wide averaging for auto emissions would fail to reduce motor vehicle pollution as promised; and that provisions to reduce toxic chemical emissions could be undermined by giving too high a priority to industry's economic considerations <PERSON> Reilly </PERSON> said the bill will be `` faithful in every respect to the spirit and letter of the promises he -LRB- <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> -RRB- made,'' adding there was no `` post-announcement erosion.'' He contended environmentalists have been `` astonished at the sweeping breath of the legislation,'' but acknowledged `` they have their reservations as does everyone else. Some of the groups are going to advocate more. That's their role. Eventually, the country is going to unite behind this.''
